<FIRST>r a AM-Homosexual-Scouts     03-20 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homosexual-Scouts,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Minister Threatens To Drop Boy Scouts Over Homosexual Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Denver minister said Monday that he would drop
his church's sponsorship of a Boy Scout troop unless the
organization reverses itself and allows a homosexual man to serve on
the troop's parents committee.
   ``I believe the Boy Scout law is a correct one _ to serve God and
country,'' said the Rev. Edward Ostertag, rector of St. Barnabas
Episcopal Church.
   ``But I don't think God or my country trashes people. If the Boy
Scouts have departed from that, they should let the sponsoring
agencies know they have departed from that old law.''
   Ostertag said the homosexual man, who has a son in Troop 13, was
one of 16 people appointed to the parents committee, which
supervises the activities of the 35 scouts in the troop.
   He said the Boy Scout organization revoked the man's registration
after learning that he was an admitted homosexual. Ostertag would
not name the father.
   The Boy Scouts of America has upheld the decision at the district
and regional levels. The case now is before the National Council of
the Boy Scouts, Ostertag said.
   Barclay Bollas, a spokesman at the organization's national
headquarters in Irving, Texas, said Monday that the Boy Scouts of
America has a policy barring membership to homosexuals and has
invoked that policy before.
   ``We do not believe homosexuals make appropriate leaders for a
youth organization like the Boy Scouts,'' Bollas said.
   Both the troop committee and the parents of the scouts have voted
to support Ostertag's campaign on behalf of the man.
   Ostertag said it is not easy finding volunteers who will take
scouts on camping trips and oversee their work on merit badges,
especially in Denver's Capitol Hill neighborhood, where many
residents are single.
   ``This is Holy Week, and I feel uncomfortable celebrating Good
Friday and then having to turn around to this man and say, `You're
trash, and we don't want you around,''' the minister said. ``I don't
go for that.''
</TEXT>
