<FIRST>r a AM-JFK-Evacuation     03-20 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-JFK-Evacuation,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Bomb Forces JFK Building Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wing of the International Arrivals Building at
John F. Kennedy International Airport was evacuated Sunday night
after an airline received a bomb threat and a suspicious bag was
found, authorities said.
   The threat turned out to be false and police from the bomb squad
determined that the bag did not contain a bomb, said Port Authority
Police Officer Phillip Montuori.
   Shortly after the bag was found sitting in the departure level of
Aer Lingus airline with no apparent owner, a telephone bomb threat
was received by Egyptair airline, said Port Authority Police Officer
Robert Ebert. The anonymous caller told Egyptair that a bomb was set
to explode at 10:05 p.m. in the arrivals building, Ebert said.
   Some 300 to 400 people were evacuated from the east wing of the
building at about 8:20 p.m., Ebert said. They were permitted to
return at about 10 p.m., he said.
   Ebert said the scare ``delayed whatever flights were there for
several hours, whatever flights would have been going out of the
east wing. The Egyptair flight that was going to take off didn't
until the whole thing was over.''
   No information was available on the bag's contents and police
could not immediately determine its owner, Ebert said.
</TEXT>
