<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Security     03-20 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Security,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor's Security Staff Babysit, Run Errands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington Mayor Marion Barry's security force
often erforms duties such as babysitting, running personal errands
and soliciting home telephone numbers from new female acquaintances,
The Washington Post reports.
   The Post, in its Monday editions, said two city-paid security
officials babysat the mayor's son and a playmate while the mayor was
in a hotel 20 minutes away during a trip to the Virgin Islands last
year.
   The paper quoted a model identified as Grace T. Shell as saying
that one of the mayor's security officers approached her for her
telephone number in 1987.
   About two dozen security officers make up the $1 million-a-year
detail.
   The paper said police officials have voiced concern that the
mayor often requires the officers to station themselves a few blocks
away or at the police garage where the security detail is based.
   ``The security detail should not be leaving the mayor anywhere,''
the paper quoted one high-ranking police official as saying.
   Mayoral spokesman John White said he had received no official
notification of any practice of using security officers for
babysitting or personal errands while Barry is left unprotected.
   White said it is important for the mayor to be adequately
protected, adding, ``From time to time, the mayor has had threats
against his life and his family.
   Barry has been dogged by recent allegations that he has used
drugs and by charges of drug-selling lodged in the Virgin Islands
against a former associate, Charles Lewis, whom Barry had visited
several times at a Washington hotel in December. The mayor has
repeatedly denied using drugs or having any knowledge of any
possible drug connection involving Lewis.
</TEXT>
