<DOCNO> AP890320-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Iran-RocketFuel     03-20 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Rocket Fuel,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Agencies Apparently In Conflict Over Rocket Fuel Bound For Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs officials are trying to block a
shipment of a rocket fuel component allegedly headed for Iran, but a
lack of cooperation between federal agencies could help free the
chemical soon, it was reported.
   A shipment large enough to fuel 300 military missiles was seized
in Europe in February 1988 when Customs Service agents said it was
being loaded onto an Iranian freighter, according to Sunday's Los
Angeles Times.
   But the State Department issued a special export license to the
chemical's owner, blocking Customs' court fight to forbid the
shipment, the newspaper said.
   A federal judge in Houston issued a temporary injunction
requiring the government to release the 1,144 drums of ammonium
perchlorate last week. Another hearing is scheduled for today.
   U.S. District Court Judge Sim Lake ruled the rocket fuel
ingredient was not among munitions restricted for shipment to Iran
by the State Department and that Customs failed to prove the
shipment was bound for Iran.
   The 286,000 pounds of the rocket fuel component shipped from
Houston in January 1988 by Grindius Corp. of Tampa, Fla., was seized
the following month as it was being loaded onto an Iranian freighter
in the Dutch port of Rotterdam.
   The shipment was being sent during the Iran-Iraq war, when those
countries were using surface-to-surface missiles.
   Grindius contends it never intended to sell the chemical to Iran.
The shipping bill of lading shows it was bound for a buyer in Basel,
Switzerland.
   Following the seizure, the State Department issued a special
export license covering the shipment.
   The Customs Service has urged the State Department to revoke the
license. The department has declined to do so and wouldn't comment
on the case pending its court outcome.
   Customs officials also said the Justice Department is not sure
whether it will pursue the agency's case because of Lake's initial
ruling.
   Lake blamed a lack of cooperation and communication between the
various governmental agencies for the apparent conflict.
   The United States exports between 1 million and 2 million pounds
of ammonium perchlorate every year, mostly to friendly nations.
   The compound has been in short supply since May when an explosion
in Henderson, Nev., destroyed a plant operated by Pacific
Engineering and Production Co., the primary manufacturer of ammonium
perchlorate.
</TEXT>
