<DOCNO> AP890320-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-OldandPoor     03-20 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Old and Poor,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Documentary Shows Troubles of Elderly Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``That's my problem, I'm a survivor,'' said the
old woman.
   As she said it, she raised her blue eyes so they made contact
with the social worker sitting across the table and, coincidentally,
with the camera.
   There was a smile on her face as she talked about how strong she
was, how strong she had been all her life, how she had always taken
care of herself _ and of her husband before he died.
   But now, she was alone and sick and poor and beyond finding much
to look forward to on Earth.
   The more she talked the sadder she became until she concluded
that ``68 is long enough to live.'' And then she wept.
   It is but one of several such scenes from a television
documentary _ ``On the Other Side of Easy Street'' _ airing this
week on Public Broadcasting System stations across the nation.
   Without exception, the old people put on faces of strength, even
humor for the camera. But they are not actors and, also without
exception, their eyes reflect despair and, in some cases, a
bewildered sense that they thought it wasn't supposed to turn out
this way.
   Indeed, that is the central point to the film: that despite the
Social Security program that has helped keep an increasing
proportion of elderly Americans from the poverty that afflicted
their own elders, those who remain poor _ well over 3 million _ do
so with little hope.
   ``The film shatters the stereotype that elderly persons are well
off and none are poor,'' said Horace Deets, executive director of
the American Association of Retired Persons. ``... So many people
struggle every day to retain some dignity in the face of extreme
poverty.''
   Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of the Villers Foundation,
which financed the film along with AARP, said after a preview
screening that the problems portrayed in the film ``are not
insoluble.''
   ``Frankly, it's a question of political will,'' said Pollack, who
made the point that _ unlike younger and healthier people _ the
elderly have little prospect of working their way out of poverty.
   While not a pleasant viewing experience, the film drives home the
point that even the best laid plans don't always turn out.
   And it shows that cutting through government red tape to get
available benefits is not the easiest thing to do, especially for a
new widow reeling from the death of her husband from a long illness
that wiped out what they thought would be a financial cushion.
   AARP issued a study in conjunction with release of the film that
showed fewer than half the elderly people eligible for the
Supplemental Security Income program, which is supposed to provide a
safety net for the poorest of the poor, actually get their benefits.
   The reasons vary widely from state to state and individual to
individual but, in most cases, result from failure of the
bureaucracy make the program easily available for those too
unsophisticated or too proud to seek it out.
   For those who do, the maximum benefit is $368 per month for an
individual and $553 per month for a couple.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Tower'sShadow Bjt   03-20 0916</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower's Shadow, Bjt,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nominee Faced Grilling on Warm Milk, Cigarettes and Derrieres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the aftermath of the brutal Senate battle
over former Sen. John Tower's attempt to run the Pentagon, the tenor
of a confirmation hearing seems to be getting, as one senator says,
a little bizarre.
   As evidence, here are a few questions put by Sen. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., to Lawrence Eagleburger during his confirmation
hearing last week to be deputy secretary of state:
   Humphrey: Well, let's get to the important questions, Mr.
Eagleburger. ... First of all, have you ever drunk anything stronger
than warm milk?
   Eagleburger: Yes, sir. (Laughter)
   Humphrey: Strike one. I notice you smoke, too. Strike two. ...
Have you ever in public or private pinched a woman's behind?
   Eagleburger: Can I divide that into two questions? (Laughter) ...
No, sir.
   The nominee, a man to whom laughter came as easily as diplomatic
analysis during the drawn-out hearings, apparently took no offense
at Humphrey's questions and went on to discuss with him the tragedy
of hunger that is gripping the African nation, Sudan.
   The 30-year veteran of government service, who'd accumulated a
massive store of goodwill among senators, was swiftly confirmed a
day later by the full Senate.
   But all kidding aside, Eagleburger's two days of confirmation
hearings served to point out that much confusion remains about what
is required of a nominee for high public office, whether in personal
standards of conduct, or in attempting to deal with questions of
real or apparent conflict of interest.
   It was clear that the shadow of Tower's ruined quest for
confirmation, which foundered on allegations of alcohol abuse,
``womanizing'' and the nominee's $1 million in fees as a consultant
for defense contractors, haunted Eagleburger's nomination, and may
well haunt others in the future.
   Some of the most tense questioning during the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee hearings came from Sen. Jesse Helms, R.-N.C.. He
prodded Eagleburger about the more than $900,000 in income, bonuses
and severance the nominee received during his last of four years
with the international consulting firm headed by former Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger.
   ``You know the big deal that was made about John Tower,'' Helms
told Eagleburger. ``He was a piker compared to your income.''
   Helms, an arch-conservative who had been a vocal critic of
Kissinger's policy of pursuing detente, said he was worried about
possible influence by the firm's foreign clients.
   ``There are a lot of people who wonder whether the advice you
might give to the president or the secretary of state might be
colored by the ongoing interest of firms, foreign firms ... who have
been paying you substantial fees,'' Helms told Eagleburger.
   Eagleburger said he had provided analyses of political, economic
and societal developments for his clients, many of them
multinational corporations, but that he never lobbied the U.S.
government on their behalf or engaged in any political activity for
them.
   To return to government and avoid ``even the appearance of a
conflict of interest,'' Eagleburger said he cut all ties with
Kissinger Associates, sold all his investment stocks, and
volunteered to disqualify himself for a year from any dealings with
the 15 clients he'd worked for while at Kissinger's firm and been
paid more than $5,000.
   This, his attorney William Rogers argued, went ``far beyond''
what has customarily been required from government appointees, such
as cutting all ties with their former business associates and then
being recused on a case-by-case basis on the advice of government
ethics attorneys.
   But Eagleburger's actions did not satisfy Helms, who said he
wanted the names of all of the Kissinger clients made public,
whether Eagleburger had worked for them or not.
   Helms argued that since Eagleburger had been paid out of a
company pot of funds, and not just by the clients he served, it was
necessary for the Senate panel to have such information.
   Eagleburger said that was difficult for him, since the list was
considered confidential by the company.
   Helms' request proved too much for Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who
argued that ``it's bizarre'' to require a nominee to disqualify
himself from all dealings with any client that paid part of his
income, even though he'd had no business dealings with them.
   He said such a requirement would have disqualified former
Secretary of State Cyrus Vance, former deputy secretary of state
John Whitehead, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, OMB Director
Richard Darman, Secretary of State George Shultz and Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter, many of whom had extensive business
contacts with huge investment or law firms.
   ``I think we're getting a little daffy. ... We'll be assured that
the only person who'll we'll ever have as a secretary of state will
be someone who has a career that is distinguished by doing
nothing,'' Biden argued.
   Eagleburger sought to defuse the problem by offering to
disqualify himself from any possible future dealings with any client
of the Kissinger firm from the past two years, even those he didn't
work with.
   As well, an ``informal'' arrangement was worked out, Biden said,
that did not require the nominee to meet a higher standard than what
is required under the law.
   Eagleburger agreed to disclose the names of the clients to the
State Department legal adviser, who is obligated to keep them
private under an attorney-client relationship, and provide the list
to the committee chairman, Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., and Helms,
who agreed to treat it as a classified document.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
