<DOCNO> AP890320-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0524EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hollywood-Mob     03-20 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hollywood-Mob,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Says Mafia Families Argued Over Proposed Film About Crime Figure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film proposal to depict the story of the
late mob leader Meyer Lansky reportedly triggered a struggle between
two powerful Mafia families, according to federal court documents.
   Recently unsealed FBI affidavits revealed evidence that New
York's Genovese crime family wanted to win the lead role for actor
James Caan, the Los Angeles Times reported Sunday.
   A prominent Hollywood executive backing a different script about
Lansky turned for help to the rival Gambino crime family, according
to the affidavits.
   The present status of the rival concepts weren't reported.
   The involvement of the Genovese and Gambino crime families
demonstrated the fascination mobsters have with their image, as well
as with potential profits from box-office successes, the Times said.
   The bickering over the Lansky film began in 1987 when ``The
Untouchables,'' a film about Treasury Agent Elliot Ness' campaign
against Al Capone, already had grossed nearly $75 million, the
newspaper said.
   Lansky died in 1983 at age 81 as what investigators called the
undisputed patriarch of an organized crime syndicate founded on
drugs, loan sharking, gambling and prostitution.
   Martin Bacow, a writer, producer and labor negotiator, claimed to
have known Lansky personally and said in 1987 he already had a
Lansky script in hand.
   Eugene F. Giaquinto, then president of MCA Inc.'s Home Video
Division, tentatively offered to pay Bacow $4.5 million for the
video and pay-television rights to the film if it was made, the
newspaper said.
   But Bacow said Caan was proposing his own Lansky project and
allegedly told several reputed members of the Los Angeles Mafia
family during a dinner party that the rival movie would ``never be
distributed,'' according to the newspaper.
   Caan's attorney, Donald E. Santarelli, said the actor dined with
Mafia figures but neither made nor was aware of any attempt to
interfere with Bacow's project.
   He called the dinners actor's research, saying Caan has had a
fascination with organized crime figures since his Oscar-nominated
performance in ``The Godfather.''
   There is no evidence he knew that the mob tried to intercede on
his behalf, the newspaper said.
   But the FBI is investigating whether Genovese family members
tried to pressure Bacow and Giaquinto.
   Federal agents also contend Giaquinto said in a telephone call
that he had thwarted Genovese pressure tactics by getting help from
the Gambino crime family.
   Giaquinto was unavailable for comment Sunday. He was put on
forced leave of absence from MCA, and his attorney, Richard P. Crain
Jr., does not have a local telephone listing. A call to MCA was not
answered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Observers     03-20 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Observers,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observers Call Salvadoran Elections Free and Fair</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. observers called El
Salvador's presidential election a success despite widespread
violence and a rebel intimidation campaign.
   ``Based upon our observations, our determination is that the
election was free and fair,'' the 21-member delegation said in a
report released late Sunday.
   The presidential commission arrived in El Salvador on Saturday
and was to leave today. They visited about 50 of the nation's 262
precincts.
   ``I think I'll call it a successful election. It wasn't peaceful,
but it was successful,'' Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the delegation
chariman, told a news conference Sunday evening after the polls
closed.
   Florida Gov. Robert Martinez praised the voting as a victory over
leftist rebels who have been at war with the U.S.-backed government
for nine years.
   ``This nation wants to govern itself with the most powerful
ammunition there is: the vote,'' the Republican governor said.
   Despite widespread fighting between government troops and the
guerrillas, the observers were never exposed to combat or attack,
officials said.
   The observers said they talked to voters, election workers and
soldiers.
   ``What we have observed in El Salvador is a passionate commitment
of a people to participate in the democratic process despite being
faced with: intimidation, threats, violence and death from persons
outside the political process,'' the report said.
   Still, observer William Doherty of the AFL-CIO said rebel
intimidation hindered the voting. ``We have still got a long way to
go until we call this a democracy,'' he said.
   The White House named the official delegation of congress
members, state politicans and private citizens. The U.S. Embassy
selected the precincts the observers visited by motorcade and
helicopter.
   Earlier in the day, delegation members said the balloting
appeared to be conducted under conditions designed to prevent fraud.
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker said the rebels ``didn't stop a
lot of people voting today. We saw nothing but essentially a civic
fiesta.''
   Delegation member Rep. Robert K. Dornan, R-Calif., said he
welcomed a victory by the right-wing Nationalist Republican
Alliance, or Arena, over the incumbent Christian Democrats.
   ``Now I see that the momentum has changed to the Arena party,''
Dornan said. ``I'm a conservative. It's time for my guys to win.''
   Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said Arena supporters apparently
turned out strongly, lining up at polling stations in the capital
and countryside. ``It looks like they (the voters) were chosen by
the Arena party,'' he said.
   Coelho said disputes may arise in Washington after the election
because current policies have not brought an end to the war and
Congress will need to debate whether military and economic aid to El
Salvador should continue at present levels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
