<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Chronology     03-20 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Chronology,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of Recent Salvadoran Events</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events
in El Salvador's history over the past 10 years:
   _Oct. 15, 1979: A group of reformist military officers overthrows
the rightist government of President Gen. Carlos Humberto Romero.
Cols. Adolfo Arnoldo Mejano and Jaime Abdul Gutierrez install a
junta of themselves and three civilians.
   _Jan. 1, 1980: Civilian junta members resign, including Social
Democrat Guillermo Ungo, who claims the government is moving too
slowly to improve social conditions. Ungo later becomes a political
leader of the guerrillas.
   _March 1980: Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat, joins
the junta.
   _March 24, 1980: Roman Catholic Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero
is assassinated as he celebrates Mass. Linked to the killing is
Roberto d'Aubuisson, who the following year founds the rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena. D'Aubuisson denies the
charge.
   _March 30, 1980: Scores die when gunmen fire on a crowd attending
Romero's funeral.
   _April 1980: Leftist organizations form the Democratic
Revolutionary Front to become the political wing of the rebel
movement.
   _Oct. 5, 1980: Five rebel groups form the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front.
   _Dec. 2, 1980: Four American women _ three Roman Catholic nuns
and a lay worker _ are kidnapped. Their bodies are found in a
shallow grave Dec. 4.
   _Dec. 5, 1980: The United States suspends military and economic
aid to El Salvador pending determination of those responsible for
the killings. Four National Guardsmen ultimately are sentenced to 30
years in prison for the murders.
   _Dec. 12, 1980: Duarte is named the first civilian president of
El Salvador in 30 years.
   _Jan. 3, 1981: The president of the Salvadoran Institute of
Agrarian Reform and two U.S. labor advisers are killed.
   _March 28, 1982: First elections for a National Assembly. Of 60
seats at stake, 24 go to Christian Democrats, 19 to Arena and the
remainder to smaller political groups.
   _March 25, 1984: Duarte and d'Aubuisson finish ahead of four
other candidates in the first round of presidential elections.
Guerrillas boycott and threaten violence.
   _May 6, 1984: Duarte defeats d'Aubuisson in runoff elections and
becomes first civilian president chosen by popular vote in 50 years.
   _March 31, 1985: Congressional and municipal elections. Christian
Democrats win 33 of 60 assembly seats.
   _March 1988: Congressional and municipal elections. Arena takes
32 of 60 congressional seats.
   _June 1988: Duarte is found to have terminal liver cancer.
   _Jan. 24, 1989: The guerrillas offer to participate in the
presidential election and abide by the results if it is postponed
from March 19 until September and security and anti-fraud conditions
are adopted. The rebels withdraw the proposal after discussions with
the political parties fail to achieve progress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Glance     03-20 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Glance,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at El Salvador,
where voters have elected a new president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GEOGRAPHY _ The country covers 8,260 square miles, about the size
of Massachusetts. It is rugged, a land of volcanoes and lakes and
rich soil. It is about 950 miles southwest of Miami, 950 miles
southeast of Brownsville, Texas.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POPULATION _ Its more than 5 million people are mainly Roman
Catholic and mestizo _ people of both Indian and Spanish heritage.
More than 500,000 of its residents have fled its 9-year-old civil
war, most of them to the United States.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ It was conquered in 1525 by the Spanish. It became
independent on Sept. 15, 1821 and joined the Central American
Federation, which later split into the nations that now make up
Central America.
   It was ruled for most of this century by a land-owning oligarchy
in alliance with the military.
   In 1932 a peasant rebellion organized by Farabundo Marti was
crushed by a military regime that killed 30,000 people; the leader
of that rebellion inspired the present guerrillas, the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY _ It is mostly agricultural, with coffee the main cash
crop. In the 1960s and 1970s it became a manufacturing center for
the Central American market. Its largest input is U.S. military and
civil aid, which comes to $1.5 million a day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE WAR _ The conflict began in 1979 when a group of young
officers overthrew former president Gen. Carlos Humberto Romero. A
junta tried to impose agrarian and social reforms, but dissatisfied
leftists began a rebellion in late 1979.
   The conflict has led to more than 70,000 deaths, most of them
civilian, and many suspected leftists killed by right-wing death
squads in the early 1980s.
   In 1984, Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat, became the
first popularly elected president in 50 years. Sunday's election
marks the first time Salvadorans have had a chance to replace an
incumbent civilian government with a different party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
