<DOCNO> AP890320-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Indiana-Congress     03-20 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indiana-Congress,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Congressional Election Campaign Enters Final Two Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political game of musical chairs has
some Republicans fearing they could be left standing in the cold
while the Democrats plop into a GOP congressional seat.
   On March 28, for the second time in less than five months, voters
will elect a U.S. House representative from northeast Indiana's 4th
District.
   Last November, the seat was again a Republican shoo-in,
little-watched as political interests focused on closer races.
   The good fortune of two Indiana Republicans, however, may have
changed that.
   With the election of Dan Quayle to the vice presidency and the
appointment of incumbent Rep. Dan Coats to fill Quayle's vacated
Senate seat, Republicans were forced to pick a special election
candidate from a field of relative unknowns.
   Against the GOP choice, the Democrats already had decided to run
Jill Long, a candidate with a mixed resume. Long already had lost
two races for federal office, both by wide margins: Quayle defeated
her in 1986 to win a second Senate term and Coats repeated the
drubbing in 1988 for his fifth House term.
   The Republicans picked Dan Heath, a 36-year-old aide to Fort
Wayne Mayor Paul Helmke. Heath, an attorney with Washington
experience as a member of Coats' staff, had never sought elective
office.
   He began the campaign largely unrecognized outside Fort Wayne,
where he had served Helmke's administration as public safety
director, Republicans concede. Long, on the other hand, despite her
defeats, was better known among voters when the campaign began in
mid-January.
   With both parties predicting an extremely low voter turnout,
Republicans fear a Democratic candidate could slip through the lines.
   ``There's nothing we'll need to do that we won't do,'' said Rich
Galen, director of the National Republican Congressional Committee.
``We're not going to lose this seat.''
   The committee has given Heath's campaign access to active
contributors, help with voter turnout programs and phone banks. The
GOP committee and the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
may spend an estimated $50,000 in cash and even more with in-kind
contributions on the campaign.
   Democrats concede the circumstances of a special election mean
problems for their candidate as well. A low voter turnout in a
district that has voted 2-1 Republican in past congressional races
may still favor the GOP. And Long, as well as Heath, has had trouble
igniting enthusiasm among party stalwarts during the relatively
brief period between nomination and election, both sides say.
   Neither candidate has a lengthy public record to run on, or to
attack.
   Long has attempted to play on a perceived resentment of
attorneys, frequently pointing out that Heath holds a law degree and
contending that Washington doesn't need another lawyer.
   Heath reaches back more than a decade to critize Long for
supporting a local tax increase while a member of the Valparaiso
City Council in the 1970s. He has attempted to tag Long as a
liberal, with one advertisement combining photos of Long and Michael
Dukakis, the 1988 Democratic presidential candidate whose
unsuccessful campaign was wounded by the same label.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Nightingales-Ads     03-20 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nightingales-Ads,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler and Sears Won't Advertise On NBC Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chrysler Corp. and Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. have
decided not to advertise any more on NBC-TV's ``Nightingales,''
which has provoked criticism from women because it has shown
scantily clad nurses.
   Chrysler advertised on one episode of the Wednesday night series
about student nurses because NBC owed it time, said Chrysler
spokesman Thomas Houston.
   But, ``based on the response we got from viewers, which was
obviously negative,'' the company reviewed the show and decided not
to continue, Houston said.
   Sears ran a few commercials about its new pricing strategy, but
``we pulled the one more that we had because we decided that the
program did not meet our guidelines as suitable for family
viewing,'' said a spokeswoman, Kathy Gucfa.
   The Kansas City-based American Nursing Association said last week
it has circulated lists of ``Nightingales'' advertisers to its
189,000 members, urging them to ``communicate their concerns'' about
the series, which began Jan. 25.
   ``Nightingales'' exploits women, said association spokeswoman
Carol Grimaldi.
   ``It uses nurses to show these very pretty girls in their
underwear and in the shower,'' Grimaldi said. ``It shows very lax
educational standards _ when it does say anything about nursing
education.''
   NBC responded that ```Nightingales' is a continuing drama about
the personal lives of fictional people who happen to be nurses.''
The network noted that a registered nurse reviews every script and
consults with the production company on nursing procedures and other
medical aspects.
   ``It's a drama about young women coming of age in Los Angeles
today,'' added NBC publicist Merry Aronson. ``It's very focused on
their personal lives. The hospital setting is almost an aside.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
