<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     03-20 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in thin European trading
today. Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said interest in dollar-buying was
dampened by fears of central bank intervention. Central banks in
several European countries reportedly intervened in the currency
markets on Thursday and Friday.
   ``It's very quiet,'' said a trader at a large West German bank in
Frankfurt. ``I don't think the dollar is going to do much today. I
think, if anything, we're at the top of the range now.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.85 yen to a closing 131.92. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 131.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8749 West German marks, down from 1.8770
   _1.6155 Swiss francs, up from 1.6140
   _6.3465 French francs, up from 6.3450
   _2.1146 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1145
   _1,375.00 Italian lire, down from 1,376.25
   _1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1965
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7137, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.7135 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $395 a troy ounce, up
from $393.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $395.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $393, unchanged from late Friday's
bid price.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.94 to close at a bid $396.81.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.17 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
