<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PLO     03-20 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Wants Talks Upgraded So Arafat Can Take Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization
wants to upgrade the level of its talks with the United States so
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat can take part, the Palestinian ambassador
to Riyadh said today.
   Ambassador Rafik Natsheh reiterated the PLO position while
denying a published report that said Arafat would participate at the
next round of the PLO-U.S. talks on Wednesday in Tunisia.
   ``Yasser Arafat will not take part in the talks with the
Americans at the level of ambassadors,'' said Natsheh. ``We are
demanding that the United States upgrade the level of the talks so
that Abu Ammar can take part.'' Abu Ammar is an Arafat nickname.
   To upgrade the talks would be place them on a level
``commensurate with the developments in the region,'' said Natsheh,
who also expressed ``strong displeasure ... at the slow pace'' of
the dialogue to date.
   He added: ``We look forward to serious American-Palestinian talks
through which we can reach a just settlement that guarantees the
Palestinian people's rights.''
   The dialogue began formally on Dec. 16 when Washington lifted a
13-year ban on official dealings with the PLO after Arafat and the
Palestine National Council, which acts as a parliament-in-exile,
made clear their acceptance of the state of Israel and renounced
terrorism.
   The PLO is seeking to create a Palestinian state in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, where Palestinians have been demonstrating for 15
months against Israel's 21-year military occupation.
   The U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert Pelletreau, is the highest
ranking American diplomat authorized to handle discussions with the
PLO.
   The session in Tunisia on Wednesday will only be the second
formal session, but there have been informal contacts between
Pelletreau and the Palestinians.
   His PLO counterpart in the talks has been Yasser Abed-Rabbo, a
member of the PLO executive committee.
   A weekend report in the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Rai Al-Aam said
Arafat would sit opposite Pelletreau at the Wednesday session.
Arafat is presently in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad, where the PLO
has military headquarters.
   Meanwhile, Salah Khalaf, Arafat's second-in-command in the
mainstream PLO group Fatah, was quoted as saying that no particular
agenda has been fixed for the Wednesday session.
   Khalaf, in statements published in the Saudi Arabian newspaper
Okaz, said the talks will be open to deal with ``all issues and
measures related to developments of the Palestinian case and the
practical American steps to solve the problem.''
   Khalaf also disclosed that Arafat will be holding a summit
session with President Francois Mitterrand of France in Egypt in
April.
   Under the PLO umbrella are several organizations which sometimes
battle among themselves.
   In Damscus, Syria, the dissident Palestinian Fatah-Uprising
guerrilla group threatened Sunday to assassinate Palestinians who
make direct contact with Israeli leaders.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press, Fatah-Uprising
particularly mentioned people ``considered by the enemy close to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.'' It gave no names in the threat,
which apparently was designed to jeopardize Arafat's peace
initiatives.
   On Friday, Arafat spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif said several
Palestinians have been meeting with the Israelis.
   Fatah-Uprising, a Syrian-backed group led by Col. Saeed Mousa,
broke away from Arafat's mainstream Fatah movement in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
