<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-20 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Spring Arrives, Snow Still Widespread Across Parts of Rockies,
Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring began today as snow fell in the Rockies and heavy rain was
widespread across the Midwest.
   The official start of Spring was this morning at 10:28 a.m. EST,
and it meant springlike storms for parts of southern and western
Texas as moist air surged north from the Gulf of Mexico and strong
thunderstorms developed in the unstable air mass.
   Showers and thunderstorms also broke out northeast of a low
centered over the Texas Panhandle, stretching from Kansas across
central Missouri into southern Illinois.
   Elsewhere, winter held on. The Texas Panhandle low sent snow
across the central and southern Rockies. Snow was expected to
accumulate up to 8 inches today along the front range of the Rockies
in Colorado.
   Snow also was falling from eastern Iowa across much of Wisconsin
into upper Michigan. A mixture of snow and rain fell in northern
Illinois.
   Winter storm watches were posted for tonight for the south
central mountains and central highlands of New Mexico and portions
of northwest Texas.
   A cold front dipped into the central Rockies and the central
Plains this morning and continued to head south toward the southern
Plains.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
southern Plains across the middle Mississippi and Ohio valleys to
Pennsylvania and across to the Gulf Coast and South Carolina;
widespread rain in the Ohio Valley; and snow in northern New
England, the Great Lakes region, the central High Plains and
southern Rockies.
   Highs will be in the teens to 20s in the northern Plains and
northern Great Lakes region; 30s and 40s across the northern and
central Rockies, central Plains and the southern Great Lakes region
to the north Atlantic Coast states; 70s and 80s in interior and
southern sections of California, the desert Southwest, southern New
Mexico, a large part of Texas and the Gulf Coast to Florida; and 50s
to 60s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at Houlton, Maine, to 74 at St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 56 cloudy; Boston 26 fair; Buffalo 22 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 48 fair; Cincinnati 39 cloudy; Cleveland 30
cloudy; Detroit 31 cloudy; Miami 70 fair; New York 29 fair;
Philadelphia 30 fair; Pittsburgh 29 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 16 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 11 fair; Chicago 36 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
68 windy; Denver 27 snow; Des Moines 34 cloudy; Indianapolis 35
rain; Kansas City 40 thunderstorms; Minneapolis-St. Paul 30 snow;
Nashville 51 cloudy; New Orleans 67 foggy; St. Louis 39
thunderstorms.
   _West: Albuquerque 57 partly cloudy; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las
Vegas 62 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 63 fair; Phoenix 69 partly
cloudy; Salt Lake City 35 cloudy; San Diego 59 cloudy; San Francisco
51 fair; Seattle 39 fair.
</TEXT>
