<FIRST>r i PM-Solzhenitsyn 2ndLd-Writethru a0507 03-20 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solzhenitsyn, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0507,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Magazine Prints Essay by Solzhenitsyn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `moreover, the...' to ADD circulation of publication;
pickup 6th graf pvs `The 2{-page...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small circulation Soviet magazine has printed an
essay Alexander Solzhenitsyn wrote shortly before he was forced into
exile in which he appeals to his countrymen to cast off
officially-sanctioned lies.
   The magazine also carried a commentary crediting the Nobel
laureate for helping prepare the way for President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms.
   The publication represents another step in the gradual
rehabilitation of an author whose major works remain banned in his
homeland.
   However, the magazine did not publish Solzhenitsyn's most
trenchent criticisms of Soviet politics, including his charge that
repression has been a key element of Kremlin policy since the days
of Vladimir I. Lenin.
   Moreover, the essay was printed in a magazine destined in part
for foreign markets, selling 50,000 copies abroad in Russian,
English, French, Spanish and German, and with only a 100,000-copy
circulation at home.
   The 2{-page essay ``Live Not by Lies!'' was published in the
February bulletin of the officially sanctioned Soviet Peace
Committee's monthly, Twentieth Century and Peace.
   It was written shortly before Solzhenitsyn was arrested and
expelled from the Soviet Union for his writings.
   In the essay, which was circulated at the time in thousands of
illegal self-published copies, Solzhenitsyn called on his countrymen
to display courage and resist pressure from the country's rulers.
   An honest man, wrote Solzhenitsyn, ``does not raise his hand to
vote for a proposal that he does not sincerely sympathize with, does
not vote either openly or in secret for a person he believes is
unworthy or doubtful.''
   That sort of language, considered anti-Soviet and seditious under
President Leonid I. Brezhnev's rule in the 1970s, is now fully in
line with Gorbachev's calls for greater openness, civic
responsibility and democracy.
   Author Igor Vinogradov, in the commentary appended to
Solzhenitsyn's essay, called the arrest and banishment of the 1970
Nobel Prize winner ``a shameful act'' and lauded the writer's ``high
spiritual and civic courage.''
   Without such brave people who spoke out against abuses of the
Soviet rulers of their time, Gorbachev's drive for ``perestroika,''
social and economic reforms, may never have come about, Vinogradov
said.
   ``Those changes which started in our country three years ago _
could they be possible if in our society, in all its strata,
contempt and loathing had not ripened among nearly everyone for
those who personified the ruling evil and violence, and for their
miserable servants, flooding the country with lies and
demagoguery?'' he wrote.
   In an interview published today by The New York Times,
Solzhenitsyn's wife, Natalia, who often speaks for him, said she was
disappointed that the essay was published in such a
small-circulation journal because the piece was written as a broad,
national appeal.
   ``Given that this was meant as an address to the people, this is
not the place it should be published,'' Mrs. Solzhenitsyn was quoted
as saying in a telephone interview from her home in Cavendish, Vt.
   Vadim A. Medvedev, the Communist Party's ideology chief, said
late last year he favored a continued ban on publishing works by
Solzhenitsyn because they would undermine Soviet society.
   ``I am against the publication of a number of works by
Solzhenitsyn and in the first place such works as `Lenin in Zurich'
and `The Gulag Archipelago,'' the Politburo member told a Nov. 29
news conference.
   ``To publish Solzhenitsyn's works would mean to, in effect,
undermine the foundations on which today's life rests,'' Medvedev
said.
   His remarks indicated there are still limits on the amount of
openness allowed under Gorbachev's reforms.
   Solzhenitsyn's ``One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich,'' a
chronicle of life in Soviet labor camps under dictator Josef V.
Stalin, was published in 1962 during the thaw allowed by Nikita S.
Khrushchev following Stalin's death.
   Some Soviet writers, artists and activists have clamored for the
publication of Solzhenitsyn's works and his return to the Soviet
Union. In October, the filmmakers' union asked for a review of his
1974 expulsion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
