<DOCNO> AP890320-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AppleControversy     03-20 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apple Controversy,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anatomy of a Chemical Scare: TV, Celebrity Bring Issue to Fore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The farm chemical Alar has for four years been
a symbol of industrial arrogance and regulatory foot-dragging to
followers of the consumer movement.
   But despite activists' efforts, it's a safe bet most Americans
knew little or nothing about Alar, which is used to grow crisper,
more colorful apples, and which has been linked to cancer in animal
tests.
   That's changed dramatically in the last two weeks.
   The Alar-apple debate quickly gained public-policy star status
through a ``60 Minutes'' television report, the involvement of
actress Meryl Streep and surprise moves by educators in New York and
Los Angeles to yank apples from school lunchrooms.
   Despite reassurances from the government and health establishment
that Alar isn't all that unsafe, signs of alarm have mounted:
   _By the end of last week, the heads of the Environmental
Protection Agency and the Food and Drug Administration both felt
compelled to defend the nation's apple supply. They were joined by
Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who released a statement Saturday
saying: ``I wish to send a message to mothers across the country:
It's OK, Mom, apples are good for your kids!'''
   _Apple growers in Washington state blamed the controversy for a
drop of nearly 10 percent in shipments of apples out of state in two
weeks.
   _Grocers and apple processing companies across the country
reiterated policies against accepting apples sprayed with Alar.
Meanwhile, the manufacturer of the chemical, Uniroyal Chemical Co.
of Middlebury, Conn., has repeatedly cited research showing Alar in
the concentrations found in apples doesn't pose a cancer threat.
   The Alar debate has been around with varying degrees of fervor
since August 1985, when the EPA considered but rejected a ban on the
chemical, used to control ripening and improve quality, consistency
and shelf life of apples.
   In early February, the EPA finally did propose a phaseout of use
of the chemical, which would take it off the market starting
probably next year. But the EPA said the threat of Alar was not so
severe that the ban had to start right away.
   Consumer groups, including Ralph Nader's Public Citizens Health
Research Group and the National Resources Defense Council, have
campaigned for an immediate ban instead.
   The periodic consumer campaigns have prompted many big
supermarket chains and apple processors across the country to quit
accepting Alar-treated apples. As a result, use of the chemical fell
to an estimated 5 percent to 10 percent of the crop from a high
around 50 percent. Many growers hoped controversy was behind them.
   But on Feb. 26, the dormant controversy erupted anew.
   The CBS television show ``60 Minutes'' reported a study by the
Natural Resources group suggesting children, because of low body
weight and proportionately high consumption of apples, had a
heightened risk of cancer from Alar.
   Then Miss Streep appeared on TV talk shows and gave interviews
about her fears for her three children's health.
   The resulting blast of publicity prompted officials in the
nation's two biggest school districts, New York and Los Angeles, to
temporarily pull apples and apple products from their cafeterias.
Reports of the apple bans quickly spread.
   ``In our democratic process, an angry mob will be listened to no
matter what the facts are,'' said Mark Helmke, a Washington, D.C.,
consultant with the Robinson, Lake, Lerer and Montgomery public
relations firm.
   ``That's what's happened in this case _ this story has struck a
nerve,'' Helmke said.
   Studies show Alar, a trade name for the chemical daminozide,
could be linked to cancer in laboratory animals. A breakdown product
of Alar called UDMH also was shown to cause cancer when give to test
animals in large amounts.
   The American Academy of Pediatrics adopted a position paper March
11 calling for an end to Alar use but said parents shouldn't worry
about farm chemicals applied in legal amounts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Congress 2ndLd-Writethru   03-20 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Congress, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0501,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Urges Chinese To Tighten Belts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf `The only...' to move up reference
to Deng not attending, provide additional detail on on leaders, seating
arrangement. Pickup 6th graf `The tone...'; DELETES 12th graf pvs `Sitting
behind...' to remove redundant material.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng opened the annual session of
China's legislature today by calling on Chinese to work harder and
make more financial sacrifices to collectively overcome worsening
economic woes.
   ``Both government and people should be mentally prepared for a
few years of austerity,'' Li told more than 2,000 delegates at the
Great Hall of the People in central Beijing.
   He urged officials to give up their ``vested interests in favor
of the interests of the whole.
   ``If we set a good example and explain clearly to the people the
need for tightening our belts, they will surely understand and
support it,'' he said.
   The only exceptions Li made to the tight-money policy were
agriculture and education. Li said the education budget would be
increased and more loans would be made to farmers.
   Sitting behind Li on the rostrum were other government and
Communist Party leaders. Senior leader Deng Xiaoping, 84, was
absent, but there was no official explanation. Deng attended last
year's opening session.
   The chair normally filled by Deng, next to Communist Party chief
Zhao Ziyang, was filled by President Yang Shangkun. Next to Yang sat
Li and next to him sat Vice Premier Wang Zheng. Two chairs were
empty.
   The tone of Li's speech contrasted with last year's, when he
called for bold new efforts to move the economy away from rigid
central planning that long stifled growth. Since then, however,
inflation has climbed to a post-war record annual rate of 36
percent, and overheated demand has caused shortages, hoarding and
several bank runs.
   Li blamed the economic problems on ``a tendency to be too
impatient for quick results.
   ``More often than not we tended to ignore the fact that China has
a huge population, is relatively short of resources and has an
unevenly developed economy,'' Li said in a criticism of policies
that he helped shape.
   ``We ... did not pay sufficient attention to taking comprehensive
and coordinated measures and failed to tighten control and
supervision at the right moment,'' he said. ``We were too
optimistic.''
   Li was interrupted by applause when he reaffirmed China's claim
to sovereignty over Tibet and denounced foreign support of Tibetan
separatism as ``outrageous interference in China's internal
affairs.''
   He also reiterated China's position that it was justified in
imposing martial law in Tibet on March 8 after three days of
anti-Chinese violence in which at least 12 people died. Tibetan
activists claim the region was independent before the Communist
takeover in 1950.
   Li did not mention letters sent to the congress by more than 100
intellectuals appealing for an amnesty for political prisoners, or
the growing public clamor for greater freedom of speech.
   Most of Li's speech was devoted to economic problems and
austerity measures, including strengthening control over price
increases, loans and new construction.
   However, he said the state would increase its grain purchase
price by 18 percent beginning April 1 in an effort to end a
four-year slump in production. Banks will increase agricultural
loans, he said.
   ``Agriculture stands out as the weakest link in the national
economy at present,'' he said.
   Li also announced a 15 percent increase in the education budget,
to $10 billion.
   ``This figure is the best the government can do under the present
tight budget, although it still falls far short of actual needs,''
he said. He said alternate sources of funding would have to be found.
   The congress meets through April 4 to hear more government
reports and discuss proposed laws.
   Congress delegates are elected by provincial congresses, which in
turn are chosen by municipal and county congresses in each area.
Citizens actually vote only for representatives in the lowest-level
local congress.
</TEXT>
