<HEAD>Israeli Planes Bomb Palestinian Positions in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with casualties, editing for transition.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today bombed Palestinian
guerrilla bases in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley, and police
said six people died and nine were wounded.
   It was the fourth Israeli air raid in Lebanon this year.
   The positions attacked today belong to the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command, a pro-Syrian faction of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, the Israeli army said.
   Police in Beirut said six Israeli planes took part in the attack
on Bar Elias, about six miles west of the Syrian-Lebanese border.
   The Israelis said all their planes returned safely to base.
   The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command
has claimed responsibility for several recent infiltration attempts
into Israel, including a Feb. 12 attack in which two of its members
were killed in Israel's self-proclaimed security zone in south
Lebanon.
   On Feb. 28, Israeli warplanes attacked the headquarters of the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine in the village of
Ainab, 10 miles south of Beirut. Two members of the guerrilla group
were killed and 33 people were injured in that attack, including 26
children.
