<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Refuge 2ndLd-Writethru a0520 03-20 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Refuge, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0520,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Black Detaines Escape, Seek Refugee At Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with details on four blacks, background.
No pickup. Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four black activists escaped
from South African custody today and requested refuge at the West
German Embassy in Pretoria, an embassy official said.
   Embassy Counselor Klaus Bonnemann said the men, all detainees who
had been on hunger strikes, arrived at the embassy this afternoon
and said they belong to the banned United Democratic Front, the
country's largest anti-apartheid coalition.
   The men said they escaped from Hillbrow Hospital in Johannesburg,
where they were being treated for fasting to protest their detention
without trial, Bonnemann said. Hundreds of detainees have taken part
in hunger strikes since January, demanding they be released or put
on trial.
   Bonnemann declined to say exactly what the men want from the West
German Embassy and added no decision had been made concerning them.
   South African police confirmed four detainees escaped from
Hillbrow Hospital today, but declined to give any additional details.
   In Bonn, the West German Foreign Ministry said the four men were
in ``administrative custody.'' Spokesman Hans Schumacher indicated
he did not know precisely what the men were seeking.
   The West German Embassy did not release the names of the men, but
human rights lawyer Azhar Cachalia identified them as Job Sithole,
Ephraim Nkoe, Mpho Legoro and Clive Radebe.
   Cachalia declined to say how the men left the hospital and
traveled to the West German Embassy. Pretoria is about 40 miles from
Johannesburg.
   Journalists were not allowed inside the embassy this afternoon,
but from the street, the four black men could be seen standing in
the foyer of the building, clad in T-shirts and jeans.
   People have escaped from South African custody and taken refuge
in foreign diplomatic missions several times in recent years.
   Most recently, three detainees escaped from a hospital in
September and holed up in the U.S. Consulate in Johannesburg for
more than 40 days before deciding to leave.
   The South African government promised that the three men, all
United Democratic Front members, would not be detained or restricted
once they left the consulate. The three have regularly spoken on
behalf of the front in recent months.
   In another incident, Klaas de Jonge, a Dutch citizen accused of
smuggling weapons for the African National Congress guerrilla
movement, took refuge in the Dutch Consulate in Pretoria for more
than two years before he was returned to the Netherlands in
September 1987 in an exchange involving in four countries.
</TEXT>
