<FIRST>r w PM-IRSWhistleblower     03-20 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IRS Whistleblower,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Worker Goes Public With Complaint; Gore Promises Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRS employee who, under a cloak of
anonymity, accused the agency of not telling people who neglect to
subtract withholding when figuring their taxes went public on
network television today and was promised protection by Sen. Albert
Gore Jr.
   ``If they try any kind of reprisal, they better watch out'' Gore,
D-Tenn., said of Internal Revenue Service officials.
   The IRS employee, Linda Johnson, a return examiner in the
agency's service center in Memphis, appeared with Gore on NBC's
``Today'' show. She had planned to appear in silhouette and with her
voice disguised, but dropped those precautions because ``I found out
that it's probabaly known out there ... who has actually reported
it,'' she said.
   Ms. Johnson originally told her story during a private meeting
with Gore. She repeated it in an interview with The Associated Press
last week, but insisted that she not be identifed at the time
because of fear of retaliation.
   She is involved in the IRS's program to detect taxpayers who fail
to report some or all their taxable income.
   About 15 months after tax returns are filed, computers match
returns with Form 1099s, W-2s and other source-of-income reports and
if some income does not show up on a return, examiners such as Ms.
Johnson decide whether the taxpayer should be sent a letter
demanding an explanation.
   In 1987, while checking 1985 returns, Ms. Johnson said, she and
colleagues found numerous returns on which filers had failed to
subtract withheld taxes from taxes owed. That meant the taxpayers
were overpaying.
   When she went to supervisors, she said, they told her IRS policy
required taxpayers to find their own mistakes. After protests, she
added, her superiors checked with IRS headquarters in Washington and
were told to abide by the policy.
   ``It was stealing from the taxpayers,'' Ms. Johnson said.
   She said the disputed policy was changed last year to allow IRS
employees to notify taxpayers when they fail to subtract taxes that
have been withheld from wages or periodic pension payments. But the
old policy still stands for taxpayers who neglect to subtract taxes
withheld from lump-sum pension payments.
   The IRS has steadfastly refused to comment directly on Ms.
Johnson's assertions, saying it is reviewing its employee manual and
policies.
   However, in an appearance before the House Ways and Means
oversight subcommittee last week, acting IRS Commissioner Michael
Murphy said ``it is possible that taxpayers did not get the refund
they were entitled to.''
   Even after changes were made last December, Murphy said, ``I
still am not completely satisfied with that program.''
</TEXT>
