<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bullet     03-20 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bullet,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Bar Oklahoma Prosecutors From Forcing Removal of
Bullet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to bar Oklahoma
prosecutors who seek incriminating evidence from forcing the
surgical removal of a bullet from a murder suspect's arm.
   The court, without comment, turned down Harold Allan Andrews'
arguments that removing the bullet would violate his constitutional
protection against unreasonable searches and seizures.
   The Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals, by a 2-1 vote last Oct.
27, ruled that the surgery could be peformed against Andrews' will.
   The operation has not yet taken place.
   Andrews is charged with first-degree murder in the March 3, 1988,
shooting death of Hatten Lee Ledford in rural McClain County.
   Before he died, Ledford told someone he thought he had wounded
the man who shot him, whom he identified as John D. Miser.
   Andrews was found, suffering from a gunshot wound, about 750 feet
from Ledford's home.
   A state judge approved county prosecutors' request to compel
surgical removal of the bullet lodged in Andrews' upper arm.
   The state appeals court, in upholding that ruling, noted a
doctor's testimony for prosecutors that removal of the bullet would
not be life-threatening, and would require only a local anesthetic.
   ``The extent of the surgical intrusion upon the defendant's
protective interests, privacy ... personal dignity and body
integrity is not impermissibly significant,'' the state appeals
court ruled.
   In the appeal acted on today, Andrews argued that the Oklahoma
court's decision conflicts with what the justices ruled in a
Virginia case four years ago.
   In the 1985 decision, the high court refused to let Virginia law
enforcement officials force the surgical removal of a bullet from a
criminal suspect's chest.
   ``A compelled surgical intrusion into an individual's body for
evidence ... implicates expectations of privacy and security of such
magnitude that the intrusion may be unreasonable even if likely to
produce evidence of a crime,'' the court said in the 1985 case.
   The justices in that decision drew a distinction between the
surgical removal of a bullet and the taking, over a suspect's
protest, of a blood sample to establish intoxication.
   The court allowed such takings of blood samples in a 1966 ruling.
   The Oklahoma court, distinguishing Andrews' case from the 1985
decision, said the surgery required in the Virginia case was riskier.
   The case is Andrews vs. Love, 88-1296.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
