<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Photographer     03-20 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Photographer,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Newspaper Photographer Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper photographer convicted for pursuing
a police chase and photographing a suspect's arrest in Troy, Mich.,
three years ago lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, left intact Mark Robert Hoffman's
conviction on charges of obstructing police work.
   Hoffman, also convicted of reckless driving in connection with
the May 6, 1986, incident, was sentenced to five days in jail and
fined $400.
   His appeal did not challenge the reckless-driving conviction.
   But the appeal attacked a Troy city ordinance that states no one
``shall obstruct, resist, hinder or oppose'' any police officer's
duties.
   Hoffman's lawyers said the ordinance, when invoked against him,
violated free-press rights. They also argued that the ordinance
should be struck down because ``it places unfettered enforcement
discretion in the hands of the police.''
   Hoffman, then working as an intern photographer for The Detroit
News, was driving along Interstate 75 when he heard on his radio
that a nearby police car was pursuing a car that had rammed it.
   Hoffman pulled onto the highway shoulder and waited until he saw
a state police car chasing another car. He then followed, driving up
to 80 miles an hour to stay right behind the state trooper's car.
   When the suspect's car came to a stop, the state trooper stopped
his patrol car right behind it, jumped out and drew his gun.
   Troy police also had guns drawn and pointed at the suspect.
   Hoffman photographed the tense scene, from what his lawyers said
was about 10 feet away. But lawyers for the city told the justices
that Hoffman was as close at 18 inches to the suspect, and that he
refused to get out of the way when ordered to do so by police.
   Hoffman no longer lives in Michigan, his lawyer said, but still
works as a newspaper photographer.
   He has not yet completed the 5-day sentence, or paid the $400
fine.
   The case is Hoffman vs. Troy, 88-1212.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
