<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-SanOnofre     03-20 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-San Onofre,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal by Workers at California Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
workers at a California nuclear power plant who are challenging
their employer's random drug tests.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that threw out,
at least temporarily, a lawsuit attacking the tests.
   The justices already are studying the validity of drug tests in
three other cases, one involving a private employer and two
concerning federal workers or federal regulations.
   The case acted on today stems from tests initiated by Southern
California Edison Co. at its San Onofre nuclear plant.
   The tests, modified in December 1986, require randomly selected
workers to produce urine samples for laboratory analysis. The
workers are told the day before they are tested.
   The plan was challenged by Local 246 of the Utility Workers Union
of America.
   The union said the tests violate the collective bargaining
agreement between the workers and the utility, and also violate
provisions of the California Constitution protecting privacy and
freedom from unreasonable searches and seizure.
   The union's lawsuit was filed in state court and transferred to a
federal court at the request of Southern California Edison.
   A federal judge in 1987 temporarily blocked the tests pending
resolution of a grievance filed by the union.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the judge's
injunction, and also ruled that the lawsuit was preempted by federal
labor law.
   The appeals court said the federal Labor Management Relations Act
governing worker-employer disputes bars the nuclear plant workers
from filing a suit now claiming their rights guaranteed by the
California Constitution were violated.
   ``Drug testing does not implicate the sort of non-negotiable
state-law rights'' that would allow the suit to be decided in court
before it is determined whether the tests violate the workers'
collective bargaining agreement, the appeals court said.
   The appeals court said the next step for the union is to submit
the case to arbitration to decide whether the contract was violated
because the utility unilaterally adopted the tests.
   The appeals court did not rule out the possibility that Local 246
could return to the courts if it loses in arbitration.
   The union said it should be entitled now to a ruling on whether
the California Constitution protects workers against random drug
tests.
   The case is Utility Workers Union vs. Southern California Edison,
88-1180.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Judge     03-20 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Judge,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Hear Appeal by Judge in Pittsburgh in Bankruptcy
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by a federal judge in Pittsburgh who issued orders in a
bankruptcy case after he disqualified himself from presiding over
the matter.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that set aside
the judge's orders.
   U.S. District Judge Paul A. Simmons announced in his courtroom on
Jan 29, 1988, that he was disqualifying himself from a case
involving the Jeannette Corp. glass company because of the
appearance of a conflict of interest.
   Simmons disclosed that his daughter worked for Mellon Bank, a
creditor of Jeannette Corp.
   The judge then continued to preside over a hearing that lasted
more than six hours.
   On March 16, 1988, Simmons granted a request to convert
Jeannette's bankruptcy petition from one aimed at reorganizing the
corporation to one dissolving it.
   Simmons also sharply criticized two lawyers involved in the case,
Robert A. Cindrich and Douglas A. Campbell. He accused them of
``trying to rip off this estate in millions of dollars.''
   The lawyers said Simmons' announcement of his orders in the case
were a ```press conference'' to which reporters had been summoned by
the judge's secretary. The attorneys also said there was no basis to
Simmons' accusations against them.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last September that
Simmons should have stepped aside immediately after announcing there
was a potential conflict of interest.
   ``Once a judge has disqualified himself, he or she may enter no
further orders in the case,'' the appeals court said in ordering the
bankruptcy matter assigned to a different judge.
   The appeals court also urged Simmons, ``in light of the animosity
that appears to have arisen'' between himself and the two lawyers,
to consider never again presiding over any matter involving their
firms.
   The appeals court also said the way Simmons announced his orders
at the March 16 proceeding appeared to ``highly inappropriate.''
   The case is Simmons vs. Moody, 88-1174.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
