<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Hustler     03-20 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Hustler,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon, New York Anti-Porn Leaders Lose Efforts to Revive Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women active in fighting pornography today
lost Supreme Court attempts to revive libel lawsuits against Hustler
magazine and its publisher, Larry Flynt.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that 1985 articles
villifying each woman in pornographic terms are constitutionally
protected expressions of opinion.
   Peggy Ault, who founded an anti-pornography group in Milwaukie,
Ore., and Dorchen Leidholdt, a New Yorker who helped found Women
Against Pornography, were the targets of a column published each
month in Hustler.
   The column, which frequently elicits libel suits from its
subjects, singles out people who oppose the sexually explicit
magazine's views. Carrying an epithet as its title, the column
usually engages in personal attacks as well as criticizing its
targets' views.
   Ms. Ault was the column's target in the magazine's April 1985
issue; Ms. Leidholdt in the June 1985 edition.
   Some of the gentler terms used to describe Ms. Ault included
``fanatic,'' ``crackpot,'' ``threatened by sex'' and ``deluded
busybody.''
   Ms. Leidholdt's lawsuit charged that the June 1985 column falsely
described her as ``sexually repressed,'' a person who hates men and
herself and suffers from ``bizarre paranoia,'' ``vengeful
hysteria,'' and ``demented thinking.''
   Ms. Ault sued in federal court in Oregon; Ms. Leidholdt in
federal court in Wyoming.
   Both suits were dismissed by a trial judge before they reached a
jury, and the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the
dismissals last October.
   In Ms. Ault's case, the appeals court said, ``We think it clear
that there is a heated and spirited debate on pornography of which
this article is a part, in which epithets, fiery rhetoric and
hyperbole are expected.''
   The appeals court added, ``It is unfortunate that the legal
category of opinion must be used to describe a statement that is no
more than a vicious slur but base and malignant speech is not
necessarily actionable (libel).''
   In the appeals acted on today, lawyers for both women argued that
the 9th Circuit court rulings unduly expanded the concept of legally
protected expressions of opinion.
   ``What public debate is furthered by this type of assault on
personal dignity?'' one appeal asked. ``Elevation of such conduct to
the pedestal of protected speech should not be tolerated.''
   But lawyers for Flynt and his magazine, in urging that the
appeals be rejected, argued that the Constitution protects even
``vituperative, pejorative or pernicious opinion.''
   The cases are Leidholdt vs. L.F.P. Inc., 88-1214, and Ault v.
Hustler Magazine Inc., 88-1215.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
