<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Chrisman     03-20 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Chrisman,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Libel Suit Against Los Angeles Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
libel lawsuit against the Los Angeles Times by a Naval commander
court-martialed in 1984 after his ship ran aground in Hawaii.
   The justices, citing a lack of jurisdiction, left intact
California court decisions dismissing Cmdr. Willard G. (Bud)
Chrisman's suit that alleged seven Times articles ruined his Naval
career.
   The state courts cited Chrisman's failure to request a correction
or retraction, a requirement under state libel law, and the legal
protection given to fair and accurate reports of governmental
proceedings.
   The first sued-over article reported allegations that Chrisman
had been intoxicated when his ship, the San Diego-based USS
Thomaston, ran aground in Port Allen, Kauai, on Jan. 24, 1984.
   The second article reported that the Navy had decided to
court-martial Chrisman on charges stemming from the grounding.
   The last five articles reported on each day of the court-martial,
concluding with a report that Chrisman had been convicted of
negligently hazarding his ship but acquitted of charges that he was
drunk at the time.
   A state trial judge refused to dismiss Chrisman's suit against
the Times, but an appeals court later ordered that the case be
thrown out.
   The California Supreme Court refused to hear Chrisman's appeal
last July 28.
   In the appeal acted on today, Chrisman argued that the California
retraction law should not have been invoked in his case because the
Times articles had been published with ``actual malice.''
   The appeal also contended that the articles reporting his
court-martial ``were neither true or fair because the testimony was
incorrectly or falsely summarized.''
   Chrisman said the state court rulings ``unconstitutionally extend
the scope of the `neutral reportage' privilege, and literary license
doctrine ... so as to deprive (him) of the right to protect his
reputation from defamatory statements.''
   Lawyers for the newspaper urged the justices to reject Chrisman's
appeal.
   The case is Chrisman vs. Times Mirror Co., 88-844.
</TEXT>
