<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Tax     03-20 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Tax,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Let Idaho Officials Tax Income of Some Railway Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to let Idaho
officials tax the income of railway workers who live elsewhere but
pass through the state as crew members on non-stop freight trains.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that such a tax
would violate the Constitution and be unfair to the workers.
   The Idaho Supreme Court ruled last May that Burlington Northern
Railroad crews working on trains traveling between Spokane, Wash.,
and Whitefish or Missoula, Mont., may not be forced to pay the tax.
   The trains cross Idaho's panhandle without making any scheduled
stops in the state.
   Idaho officials in 1983 ordered the railway workers to pay taxes
on income received from 1978 through 1982. The state sought to
impose the tax on a portion of the workers' income state officials
said was earned while in Idaho.
   The state Supreme Court said, ``Idaho is not the source of this
income since there is no contribution by Idaho to the production of
this income. It would be unfair to allow the state to impose a tax
on the income of the train crews earned while they are merely
passing through Idaho.''
   The state court said the tax violates the Constitution by
interfering with interstate commerce and by denying the workers due
process protection.
   The state court added that the workers' wages while passing
through Idaho ``are not attributable to any economic activity within
Idaho, and Idaho markets and commerce do not affect their income in
any degree.''
   The state court relied largely on U.S. Supreme Court rulings
holding that the test for the constitutionality of a state tax
affecting out-of-state residents is ``whether the state has given
anything for which it can ask return.''
   The state Court said while the state has given something of value
to Burlington Northern, it ``has not given anything to the train
crews for which it can ask return.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Idaho officials said the state
court ruling ``sets a dangerous and disruptive precedent'' and
conflicts with decisions by other courts giving states sweeping
power to tax non-residents who work within those states.
   ``Taxpayers in other jurisdictions are now lining up to challenge
taxation of non-residents based on Idaho's decision,'' the state's
appeal said.
   The case is Idaho Tax Commission vs. Blangers, 88-1266.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
