<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-UN     03-20 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-UN,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says He's Heartened By Changes at United Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that he's pleased by
management reforms at the United Nations and said he believes it is
``on the right track'' toward securing greater influence in world
affairs.
   Speaking at a swearing-in ceremony for Thomas Pickering, the new
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Bush said ``I take the United
Nations very seriously and I am pleased with the changes that have
been taking place there.''
   In the first days of his presidency, Bush invited U.N. Secretary
General Javier Perez de Cuellar to a private White House dinner in a
meeting that Bush aides said was aimed at conveying the new
administration's support for the world body.
   The Reagan administration late last year agreed to begin repaying
to the United Nations more than $474 million in payments that the
United States had withheld in protest over what it said were
inadequate management controls and insufficient attention on
peace-making initiatives.
   In his remarks today, Bush, who served as U.N. ambassador during
the Nixon administration, said he wants Pickering to put the
spotlight on the human rights situation in communist Cuba as he
takes up his post.
   ``The United Nations is on the right track toward reform and is
not a more effective organization,'' the president said. He praised
Pickering, 67, as a ``skilled diplomat, a veteran of high-priority,
tough assignments.''
   Bush also said that ``there was a time when a lot of us got a
little pessimistic about the U.N.'s peacekeeping role,'' but said
that the body's performance has improved vastly in recent times,
including its mediating role in Afghanistan, the Iran-Iraq war and
the Angola-Namibia conflict.
   Pickering, after taking the oath of office from Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, joked that he and James Lilly, the new
ambassador to China, might find themselves working under close
scrutiny by Bush, who he said ``knows more about our jobs than we
do.'' Bush headed the U.S. Liaison Office in Beijing in 1974-75.
   ``I will be on my toes in New York,'' said Pickering, who
previously held ambassadorial posts in Israel, Jordan, Nigeria and
El Salvador.
   Pickering succeeds Vernon Walters in the U.N. post.
</TEXT>
