<HEAD>Government Troops Clash with Communist Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops clashed with
communist rebels on the southern island of Mindanao, killing at
least 16 people and wounding scores of others in two separate
incidents, the military said today.
   A military report said government troops killed at least 10
guerrillas and wounded an undetermined number of others during a
battle Sunday in a remote, hilly area north of Davao City, 610 miles
southeast of Manila.
   The report said army troops patrolling the area stumbled into a
100-strong group of communist New People's Army guerrillas near
Paquibato village.
   The report said the rebel casualty figure was based on an actual
body count and gave no further details.
   Also Sunday, five soldiers died and 17 were wounded when their
vehicle struck a rebel landmine near Lakewood in Zamboanga del Sur
province, about 550 miles south of Manila.
   One rebel died when survivors opened fire on guerrillas who had
triggered the mine, the military report said.
   Three soldiers died instantly and the others died before reaching
a hospital in Pagadian, the report said.
   The New People's Army is the armed wing of the Philippine
Communist Party and has waged a 20-year insurgency to establish a
Marxist state.
