<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-AgeBias     03-20 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Age Bias,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Use New Jersey Case to Decide Age Discrimination Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to use a New
Jersey case to decide whether federal courts may make it easier to
broaden age discrimination lawsuits against employers.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Hoffmann-La Roche Inc.,
which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off some
1,200 employees at New Jersey plants.
   The company dismissed the employees on Feb. 4, 1985. A group of
older workers, who called the day ``Black Monday'' for many veteran
Hoffmann-La Roche workers, said a disproportionately high number of
those laid off was over age 40.
   The group filed a federal lawsuit, charging the company with
violating the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act.
   The group's leaders then sought to contact all fired Hoffmann-La
Roche employees over 40 eligible to join the so-called class-action
lawsuit.
   Some 400 employees agreed to join. But the leaders of the court
battle against the company said they believed there may be 200
additional fired workers who are members of the class allegedly
victimized by age discrimination.
   The leaders sought to contact the potentially missing workers by
direct-mail and notices posted at Hoffmann-La Roche plants.
   U.S. District Judge Harold A. Ackerman authorized the employees'
group, once the missing workers are found, to provide them with an
explanation of the suit and a form that would allow them to join the
suit.
   Hoffmann-La Roche officials appealed the ruling, arguing that
Ackerman exceeded his authority. But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals upheld the judge's decision.
   ``There is no legal impediment to court-authorized notice in an
appropriate case'' where those who have filed a class-action suit
are seeking other potential plaintiffs, the appeals court said. ``We
assume that the district courts will exercise caution that notices
approved by the courts will not give the erroneous impression that
maintenance of the action has a judicial imprimatur of approval.''
   An increased number of plaintiffs in such suits can be a big
advantage because it spreads out the court costs. In seeking workers
to join the suit, the leaders of the court fight asked for _ but did
not require _ a $200 contribution to help defray the costs.
   In appealing to the Supreme Court, Hoffman-La Roche officials
noted that federal appeals courts elsewhere have disagreed with the
3rd Circuit court decision. The officials urged the high court to
clear up the confusion.
   The case is Hoffmann-La Roche vs. Sperling, 88-1203.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0088 </DOCNO>
