<FIRST>r i PM-Saudi-Awards     03-20 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saudi-Awards,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Given Faisal Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA FENN-HEINTZEN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Americans were among eight
winners of this year's King Faisal awards for excellence in science,
medicine, Arabic literature, Islamic studies and service to Islam.
   At a ceremony attended by about 500 people Sunday, Crown Prince
Abdullah presented the awards. Each award carries a $93,000 cash
prize.
   The American winners were Luigi Mastroianni, director of human
reproduction at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine
and Ahmed H. Zewail, a physicist at the California Institute of
Technology.
   Mastroianni, who runs an in vitro fertilization program, shared
the prize in medicine with Professor Robert Edwards of Great
Britain. Edwards helped pioneer the technique that led to the birth
of the world's first test-tube baby in 1978.
   Zewail, an Egyptian-born American, shared the science award for
his research in spectroscopy with Theodore W. Hansch, a professor at
the University of Munich in West Germany. Hansch was honored for his
work in laser physics.
   The prize for service to Islam went to 72-year-old Egyptian
Mohammed Ghazalli, author of 40 books on the faith.
   The Arabic literature prize was shared by Shakir M.K. Saham of
Syria and Yousef A. Khlais of Egypt for studies of Islamic poets and
writers.
   The Islamic studies award went to Iraq's Salah Ahmed Ali for a
study on the emergence of the Iraqi city of Basra under Islam.
   The Faisal Foundation was started in 1976 to honor the late King
Faisal and promotes projects that benefit developing nations.
</TEXT>
