<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Budget     03-20 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Budget,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Approves $140 Billion Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's parliament ratified a $140 billion
budget today after 12 days of debate, Tehran radio reported.
   It said the budget also was approved by the Guardian Council,
which vets all parliamentary bills to determine whether they comply
with the fundamentalist state's Islamic religion and constitution.
   The council made some amendments and dropped unidentified items
from the budget, according to the radio report monitored in Nicosia.
It did not detail changes.
   Earlier this month, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported
parliament had approved in principle a $123.7 billion budget.
Neither IRNA nor the radio explained the higher figure announced
today.
   Since the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war, Tehran has
said its priority is rehabilitating sectors of the economy destroyed
by the eight-year war.
   On Saturday, parliament gave the state's Central Bank permission
to borrow up to $1 billion for electricity generation, provided
repayment of the loan does not exceed $150 million a year, Tehran
radio reported. It did not say where the bank might borrow the money.
   Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh has said Iran would resume
borrowing abroad, reversing its longstanding policy of eschewing
foreign loans.
   But the new policy was rejected by hard-liners such as Ayatollah
Ali Montazeri, designated successor of Iranian leader Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini.
   ``If we start thinking about foreign borrowing, it would mean
selling the country to foreigners,'' Montazeri said.
   Parliament's decision to approve borrowing was seen as indicating
concern about the size of the budget deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
