<FIRST>r a PM-Gotti-Threat     03-20 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gotti-Threat,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Removed From Reputed Mob Leader's Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police discovered a bomb at the front door of a
mob hangout early today after an anonymous caller said there was a
``gift'' there for John Gotti, reputed head of the Gambino organized
crime family.
   Investigators have said that Gotti and Vincent Gigante, reputed
boss of another Mafia crime family, are locked in a power struggle.
FBI agents have told Gotti they uncovered evidence of a plot to kill
him.
   Officers moved the small bomb from the steps of the Ravenite
social club in the Little Italy section of Manhattan to a bomb squad
range in the Bronx, where it was defused. The club was empty when
the bomb was found.
   The club was the hangout of Gotti's Mafia patron, the late
Aniello Dellacroce, and is one of Gotti's haunts.
   Inspector Richard Mayronne said the device contained a pound of
explosive powder.
   A bomb squad detective, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said it could have ``seriously injured anyone passing by,'' in
addition to damaging the front of the club.
   A man who did not give his name telephoned the Police
Department's Organized Crime Control Bureau and said, ```There is a
gift for John Gotti at the social club,''' according to police Sgt.
Raymond O'Donnell.
   Police described the bomb as a plastic box that contained
batteries wired to a circuit board with an electric timer. It was
not clear when the timer was set to go off, police said. The powder
was contained in an aluminum bottle.
</TEXT>
