<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0509 03-20 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Rejects Status Quo in Opening Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with more from Peres, background. EDITS to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today opened a
conference of 1,100 visiting Jews by saying Israel needs peace but
rejected talks with the PLO or creation of a Palestinian state.
   As Shamir's conference on solidarity with Israel began, an aide
to Finance Minister Shimon Peres broke ranks with Shamir and called
for talks with the PLO.
   Deputy Finance Minister Yossi Beilin, who spoke on Israel radio,
urged the left-of-center Labor Party led by Peres to open talks with
the PLO even if Shamir and his right-wing Likud bloc disagree. ``I
think it's time to say, dear friends, the emperor is naked,'' Beilin
said.
   In the occupied territories, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded a
20-year-old Palestinian protester in the thigh, Arab reports said.
   About 330,000 Palestinians in the Gaza Strip were kept indoors by
curfew restrictions imposed as merchants launched a three-day
general strike to protest seven Palestinian fatalities in clashes
with the Israelis over the weekend.
   Four of the deaths were Sunday, bringing the death toll in the
15-month Palestinian uprising to 403 Arabs. Seventeen Israelis have
also died, including six soldiers.
   Israeli news reports said some leading Jewish personalities
declined to attend Shamir's conference, attended by Jews from 30
countries.
   The Haaretz daily listed among the absentees Hollywood stars
including Kirk Douglas and Barbara Streisand, who reportedly gave
non-political reasons for staying away.
   Critics complain the three-day conference aims to boost support
for Shamir's hard-line policies before his U.S. visit next month.
   However, Jewish leaders at the conference were cautious about
endorsing Israel's policies. ``We are not here to support specific
peace proposals,'' Seymour Reich, president of the U.S.-based
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations,
told reporters.
   In his keynote speech, Shamir restated positions he is expected
to bring to Washington, offering the Palestinians ``a maximum degree
of self-rule that is consistent with our security.''
   ``We fully recognize that the status quo is not in our interest,
because it means absence of peace, and peace is our paramount
goal,'' Shamir said in the speech closed to the press but later
distributed to reporters.
   Shamir reiterated his reasons for refusing to talk to the
Palestine Liberation Organization or withdraw from the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which it seized from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle
East War.
   ``We are opposed to negotiations with the PLO because it will
inevitably lead to a demand for a (Palestinian) state west of the
Jordan River,'' he said.
   He referred to ``the strategic dangers and vulnerability of our
eastern borders.''
   The Israeli leader also voiced veiled criticism of Jewish leaders
abroad who have met with PLO leaders.
   Peres suggested today he is willing to talk to PLO supporters in
the occupied territories if they prove they are non-violent. Asked
his conditions for negotiating with the PLO, he said: ``We want to
negotiate with people who reside in the territories. ... We will not
censor their minds.''
   The U.S. government agreed to talk directly with the PLO after
leader Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
