<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--NATO     03-20 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--NATO,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Howe Named Commander-in-Chief of NATO's Southern Europe Command</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTEAU, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Vice Adm. Jonathan T. Howe has been
named commander-in-chief of NATO's forces in southern Europe, the
alliance announced Monday.
   Gen. John Galvin, NATO's supreme military commander in Europe,
said Howe will begin his new job in late April or early May.
   Howe, who will succeed Adm. James B. Busey, is assistant to the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in Washington. He also has
been deputy chairman of NATO's military committee and director of
political-military affairs for the State Department.
   Busey has been nominated to head the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   The southern Europe command, based in Naples, Italy, is the
largest of the four military regions that fall under the European
umbrella of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The command spans an area of 1.5 million square miles, covering
Italy, Greece, Turkey and the Mediterranean and Black seas.
</TEXT>
