<SECOND>AM-BRF--Maldives,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for Four Maldivians Accused in Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trial has begun for four men who
participated in last year's attempt to overthrow Maldivian President
Maumoon Abdul Gayoom, an official in the Indian Ocean archipelago
said Monday.
   The trial of the four Maldivians began Thursday in Male, the
Maldivian capital, and the defendants included Abdul Lutfi, the
alleged leader of the November coup attempt, said Ibrahim Hussain
Zaki, the Maldivian foreign secretary.
   He said the trial of 45 Sri Lankans who also took part in the
coup attempt would begin soon.
   Gayoom has said participants in the coup attempt could face the
death sentence.
   Sri Lankan Tamil militants led by Lutfi raided the Maldives on
Nov. 3, but they fled when 1,600 Indian paratroopers landed in
response to a call for help from Gayoom.
   At least 18 Maldivian civilians were killed in the raid. Most of
the attackers were pursued by Indian naval ships, arrested and
brought to Male.
   The Maldives, about 500 miles south of Sri Lanka, are made up of
about 2,000 islands, of which only 200 are inhabited.
</TEXT>
