<HEAD>Anti-Arab Militants Set Fire to Mayor's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish militants who claimed to support
anti-Arab leader Rabbi Meir Kahane set fire Monday to the front door
of an outgoing mayor's home, Israel radio reported.
   No one was injured in the attack, which was the third of its kind
in the last five days.
   Dov Tavori, the outgoing mayor of Petah Tikva, a small town about
10 miles from Tel Aviv, said his door was burned before dawn. Tavori
said he had clashed with members of the U.S.-born Kahane's Kach
Party over opening movie theaters in his town on Friday nights, the
eve of the Jewish Sabbath.
   The radio said an anonymous caller told the Yediot Ahronot
newspaper: ``We have set fire to Dov Tavori's house and car. We
identify with Kahane.''
   Police said Tavori's door was destroyed but the rest of the house
did not catch fire. They said traces of flammable liquid were found
around his car.
   Two other attacks occurred Thursday on homes belonging to a
left-wing legislator and a television host who interviewed a
pro-Palestine Liberation Organization figure.
