<HEAD>Karl Lagerfield Gives a Leggy Look at Chanel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Designer Karl Lagerfeld gave a leggy, saucy look to
Chanel's ready-to-wear winter collection in his Monday show.
   It looked a bit dated, somehow, like a black-and-white photograph
of the 1960s, or from his previous show for the Lagerfeld label.
   As the Beatles' song ``Help'' played on, the Chanel models in
miniskirts or cat-suits with very long jackets smacked of Twiggy and
Co.
   Lagerfeld is a talented designer, but perhaps too much is
expected of him. His Chanel show repeated many of his themes from
earlier in the week, such as ribbed tights with tiny tunic skirts,
or skirts that were short in front, dipped in back.
   Less leggy but newer and niftier were the straight shirtwaists in
navy and taupe pleated satin with enormous mother-of-pearl buttons.
   The fitted redingote jacket used as a coat-dress paraded through
the collection. For daytime, it was best with a wide band of velvet
down the front edged in gold buttons. For those who haven't the
greatest legs, it would look fine with a skirt as well.
   This jacket-dress also came out for evening in a fitted military
jacket blazed with swirling gold braid. It also appeared as a long
blazer in colorful satin, either on its own with tights, or
unveiling an eyeful of leg between an open, long chiffon skirt.
   Lagerfeld bErin Hayes and Pat Slattery showing how the city sewer
department dumped sludge into creeks and rivers; WBRZ-TV, Baton
Rouge, La., for a documentary by John Camp on the Louisiana Office
of Alcoholic Beverage Control.
   Radio: WGST, Atlanta, for stories by Denis O'Hayer about
questionable practices of a foundation that claimed to raise money
to grant the wishes of terminally ill children.
   Books: ``Secret Warriors'' by Steven Emerson about Pentagon
involvement in covert operations during the Reagan Administration;
``Blowback'' by Christopher Simpson on the use of Nazi war criminals
by American intelligence during covert operations after World War
II; ``A Bright Shining Lie'' by Neil Sheehan on an accounting of the
Vietnam War told primarily through the actions of John Paul Vann, a
military and civilian American officer there.
