<HEAD>AP President Receives Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis D. Boccardi, president and general
manager of The Associated Press, has received the Paul Miller
Journalism Award for 1989.
   The award was presented March 16 by the Oklahoma State University
School of Journalism and Broadcasting in honor of Miller, 82, who
served as chairman of The Associated Press and president of Gannett
Co. Inc. before his retirement in 1978.
   Boccardi joined AP in 1967 and was named president and general
manager in 1985.
   Boccardi has twice served as a Pulitzer Prize juror and has been
elected a Distinguished Service member of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors.
   He also is a member of advisory boards for the Media and Society
Seminars, Gannett Center for Media Studies, Center for International
Journalism at the University of Southern California and the Center
for Communications.
   Miller graduated from Oklahoma State in 1931 and joined AP in
1932. He spent 15 years with the AP before joining Gannett in 1947
as executive assistant to Frank E. Gannett. Miller was with Gannett
for 31 years, the last 16 as president and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Brinkley and Rosenberg Named To N.C. Journalism Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC television correspondent David
Brinkley and retired Associated Press international correspondent
and bureau chief Morris Rosenberg are among the nine men who will be
inducted into the North Carolina Journalism, Advertising and Public
Relations Halls of Fame April 9.
   Brinkley, a native of Wilmington, N.C., began his journalism
career as a high school student writing for The Wilmington Star. He
got his first full-time broadcasting job with NBC News in 1943. He
stayed with NBC until 1981, when he moved to ABC.
   Rosenberg, a native of Charlotte, N.C., is a 1940 graduate of the
University of North Carolina School of Journalism. He served as a
correspondent for The Associated Press in Venezuela and as an editor
for AP World Services in New York.
   He was bureau chief in Paris from 1966 to 1977, then directed
AP's Latin American bureaus. He headed AP's world service operations
in the Washington bureau from 1979 until his retirement in 1987.
   Others who will be inducted into the hall of fame include John B.
Adams, former dean of the UNC School of Journalism; David Gillespie,
former editorial page editor of The Charlotte Observer; the late
Brodie Griffith, former editor of The Charlotte News; and Jim
Shumaker, associate professor of journalism at UNC and former editor
of The Chapel Hill Newspaper.
   The UNC School of Journalism started the Journalism Hall of Fame
in 1981. Since then, 39 journalists with ties to North Carolina have
been inducted, including Tom Wicker, Vermont Royster and Charles
Kuralt.
</TEXT>
