<FIRST>r a AM-LethalLeftovers-Note     03-20 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lethal Leftovers-Note,0177</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eds: This publishable editor's note is for use with the two-story
package on low-level nuclear waste, AM-Lethal Leftovers and AM-Lethal Leftovers-`God's
Country.'    The stories were sent origially in advance for use in Monday
PMs. They have been re-sent as a0582 and a0583.    Two other stories,
suggested for side-by-side use and looking at two communities' opposite
receptions of waste dumps, are AM-Lethal Leftovers-Leaks and AM-Lethal
Leftovers-`Good Neighbor. They will move spot tomorrow for Wednesday AMs.
       ^___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ In reactors, radiology departments and research
labs, workers at the end of the day cast off gloves and other
discards whose radioactivity, though relatively mild, requires
careful disposal. Now, with federal prodding, states are acting to
find new ways of getting rid of mountains of low-level nuclear
waste. Associated Press reporters have looked at the leaky legacy
and uncertain future of the disposal process. Here, they examine the
complexities of dealing with potentially lethal leftovers and how
rural Nebraskans reacted to the possibility of a dump site in their
midst.
</TEXT>
