<FIRST>u a PM-Eastern-Trump 1stLd-Writethru a0573 03-20 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Trump, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0573,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Lowers Offer for Strike-Bound Eastern Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Trump saying he wants price
cut at least $125 million; no immediate response from Texas Air. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `The New...'. ADDS 1 graf on end with detail on effort
to get comment. Version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real-estate magnate Donald Trump said today he is
no longer willing to pay $365 million for the Eastern Airlines
shuttle, citing the labor problems that have largely grounded the
financially troubled air carrier.
   He said he wants to cut the price by more than one-third. There
was no immedite response from Texas Air Corp., Eastern's
Houston-based parent company.
   In a letter to Frank Lorenzo, head of Eastern's parent company
Texas Air, Trump said, ``The shuttle has become an entirely
different business in that its market share and customer base may be
lost for some time to come, if not forever.''
   ``Today the business is worth considerably less than the price
negotiated last fall,'' Trump said.
   Asked in an interview today how much he wants to cut the price,
he said: ``I'm looking for a reduction in excess of $125 million.''
   The New York billionaire financier announced last October that he
would purchase the moneymaking operation for $365 million in cash
and name it after himself.
   However, the strike by Eastern's Machinists union members,
chiefly mechanics and baggage handlers, and the unwillingness of
most of the airlines' pilots to cross their picket lines has forced
Eastern to file for bankruptcy.
   Only about 200 of the 3,600 Eastern pilots have been working
since the strike by the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers began March 4.
   Eastern has been operating only slightly more than 100 daily
fights, about one-10th its normal level.
   The airline, which has begun advertising for new pilots, has
acknowledged there are no near-term prospects for expanding its
operations.
   Shuttle flights are among those still taking off. The airline has
been struggling to keep the shuttle between Boston, New York and
Washington in the air by offering a number of passenger incentives,
including promotional fares as low as $12. Fares returned to normal
Saturday.
   Trump said he remained interested in buying the shuttle and would
like to close a deal ``before the shuttle operations become worse.''
   In his letter, he asked Lorenzo to call him later today to
discuss the sale.
   Asked about the Trump report, Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said,
``We don't have any comment at all. We know absolutely nothing about
it here.'' In Houston, Texas Air spokesman Art Kent did not
immediately return a telephone call seeking comment.
</TEXT>
