<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerRiot     03-20 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Riot,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heysel Trial Ends; Verdict Expected April 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trial ended Monday for two dozen
Britons accused in the deaths of 39 fans during a riot at the 1985
European soccer championship final, and the three-judge panel will
issue a verdict April 28.
   The defendants, charged with involuntary manslaughter in Europe's
worst soccer riot, face up to 10 years in prison if convicted.
   Two Belgian police officials and a former chairman of the Belgian
Soccer Federation face lesser charges of poor security organization
at the match.
   Monday's closing arguments ended more than five months of
hearings to establish blame in the riots at Heysel Stadium prior to
the May 29, 1985 final between Liverpool and Juventus Turin of Italy.
   ``All the cards are on the table'' for the judges to make their
final decision, said public prosecutor Pierre Erauw.
   Belgian authorities requested the extradition of 26 Britons based
on videotapes and pictures showing British fans tearing down the
flimsy fence separating them from Italian supporters. The invasion
of the stands caused panic during which victims were trampled to
death as they tried to flee.
   Britain complied with the extradition request in September 1987
and the trial began in a year later. The defendants had been allowed
to wait at home for the trial to begin.
   More than 500 fans also suffered injuries in the riot.
</TEXT>
