<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXIE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second million comes easy, the adage
goes, but for Dixie Elementary students the problem is getting rid
of the first million.
   The first million aluminum can pulltabs, that is.
   The tabs fill a large wooden bin on the second floor, spill down
the stairways and litter the yard of the 1920s red brick schoolhouse
in this town northeast of Walla Walla.
   The collection began 2{ years ago in Cynthia Geddes' third- and
fourth-grade classroom as a math project to learn the concept of a
million.
   ``You don't often get the opportunity to see a million of
anything,'' Geddes said. ``The kids love to look at them.''
   Senior citizens, tavern owners, foreign students and a railroad
sent the tabs in response to letters written by pupils.
   At a celebration Jan. 31, contributors wore buttons that read:
``I Helped Dixie Save A Million.''
   The math lesson has expanded to geography and world affairs, said
Geddes. Dixie pupils pinned tabs from Finland, Japan, Australia,
South Africa and Israel to a world map, and sent each contributor a
hand-written thank you note.
   The school plans to donate the tabs to a charity _ at 50 cents a
pound, the tabs would be worth about $600 _ but is having trouble
finding the right one, said Ray Yoder, the school superintendent.
   School officials were told the tabs could be traded for time on
kidney dialysis machines, but found out later this was not true.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAUNTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopalians and Catholics have parted ways
again, but this time it was an amicable separation.
   Trinity Episcopal Church shared its facilities with St. Francis
for 10 months while the Roman Catholic church underwent restoration.
   On Sunday, after a joint service, Trinity members escorted the
parishioners back to their house of worship.
   The Rev. John Lane of Trinity said he was ``kind of sorry to see
them go, in a way.''
   ``I can think of nothing but that which was beneficial by meeting
there,'' said the Rev. H.G.D. Dodge of St. Francis. ``It was a
spiritual atmosphere and it gave us a chance to share with another
congregation.''
   Dodge said he had been trying to rent a movie theater or
auditorium during the renovation when Trinity unexpectedly offered
to share its space for free.
   ``We were deeply touched and impressed,'' Dodge said.
   During the renovation, Episcopalians held their services each
Sunday at 8 a.m. and 10 a.m., and the Catholics followed at 11:30
a.m.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Ross was a teen-ager when he dove into the
murky Charles River to rescue Maura Handren, 7, after she tumbled in
while accompanying him and a friend on a fishing outing.
   Ross, now 29, took the plunge again Sunday, when he and Maura,
now 22, were married.
   ``That's when Maura fell for Joey,'' said the bride's brother,
Stephen, of the incident 15 years ago.
   ``It was destiny,'' said the maid of honor, Karen Brady.
   Stephen was caring for Maura in 1974 when he and Ross, his best
friend, decided to go fishing and took her along. They handed her a
fishing pole to try her luck.
   When they looked again, her white sandals were floating on the
water, which was about 10 feet deep.
   ``There were bubbles coming up and all I could see was her
feet,'' said Ross, now a plumber at Babson College. He jumped in and
pulled her out.
   Ten years went by. When Handren was about to graduate from high
school, her brother suggested she ask Ross to the prom.
   ``It was her first date and they've been together ever since,''
said Brady. ``She has always had a crush on him.''
   ``When they fight, Joey'll tell her he should have left her in
the Charles,'' said Stephen.
</TEXT>
