<FIRST>r w AM-Army-Goggles     03-20 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army-Goggles,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army to Evaluate its Night-Vision Goggles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army said Monday it will conduct a special
one-time evaluation of every night-vision goggle in its inventory to
ensure the devices are safe for use by aviators.
   The service, in a brief statement, said the evaluation would
involve about 12,700 of the devices and would require at least two
weeks and possibly more to complete.
   The evaluation will include not only the two models of night
vision goggles that are being used now, but also two other models
that were suspended from flight use a year ago when safety questions
began arising.
   Critics have questioned whether the goggles function properly
when used if there is no moon or in cloudy weather. According to
recent published reports, 37 of 41 Army helicopter crashes since
1978 in which night goggles were used occurred when there was not
enough moonlight for the devices to amplify.
   The most recent incident in which the use of night vision goggles
has been questioned occurred just a week ago on the night of March
12. A CH-3E helicopter assigned to the Air Force Reserve crashed
near Tucson, Ariz., while ferrying some soldiers to a training
range. Fifteen servicemen died in the accident.
   According to Capt. Carlos Roque, a spokesman at the Davis-Monthan
Air Force Base, where the helicopter was based, the crewmen on that
chopper were wearing goggles that night. But investigators have
determined the goggles were not a factor in the accident, Roque said.
   The evaluations will be conducted by experienced Army pilots and
will take about 20 minutes each, said Lt. Col. Greg Rixon, an Army
spokesman. They can be performed on the ground in a specially
lighted room.
   Rixon said the Army inspections are aimed at eliminating from the
stockpile any goggles that suffer from a distortion problem that was
identified some time ago. Inside the light-amplifying tubes of each
goggle, there is a built-in twist to an optical fiber line that can
produce distortion in the lens if not made properly, he explained.
   ``Every goggle that can be used for flight is going to be
evaluated,'' Rixon said. ``If there are no problems, the goggle is
cleared for use. If there is a problem, it takes about 45 minutes to
change the tube.''
   The spokesman said the cost of replacing the goggle tubes ranged
from $1,100 to $5,000, depending upon the model.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
