<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Water     03-20 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Water,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Shortage Hits Okinawa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Okinawa's worst water shortage in seven years has
forced officials to cut water supplies throughout the southern
Japanese prefecture for 24 hours every other day, officials said
Monday.
   Water in two reservoirs averaged only 11.5 percent of capacity,
while five reservoirs were averaging 44.6 percent of capacity, a
local government official said.
   An Okinawa weather bureau official said only 0.78 inches of rain
fell in the prefecture in February, or 17 percent of normal.
   U.S. military spokesman Jake Rodrigues declined to comment on
U.S. armed forces radio reports saying all non-official travel by
American troops to Okinawa was suspended until further notice
because of the water shortage.
   Of the 64,000 U.S. troops in Japan, about 35,000 are stationed in
Okinawa, which has a population of 1.2 million.
   A water shortage in 1981-82 forced a similar 24-hour water supply
cutoff for about six months.
