<FIRST>u a AM-DrunkenDriving Bjt   03-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drunken Driving, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drunken Driving Drops When Drivers Estimate Blood Alcohol, Study
Suggests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Wagenaar' in last graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vermont town showed a markedly reduced drunken
driving rate after residents were taught to use an inexpensive
gadget to estimate their blood-alcohol levels, according to a study
that experts called promising.
   The town's rate of driving with hazardous blood-alcohol levels
was only about half that of a similar community that gave no
training, the study found.
   Although the small study could provide only preliminary evidence
that the program works, the results look encouraging, said co-author
John K. Worden of the University of Vermont College of Medicine.
   He and colleagues from the university and state government
present the work in this month's issue of the American Journal of
Public Health.
   Experts said the results were promising, but that some questions
about effectiveness remain to be answered. They also said such a
program should be considered only in combination with other
strategies to reduce drunken driving.
   The study involved three Vermont communities which Worden
declined to identify, two with populations of about 5,000 and the
third approaching 12,000. They were similar in terms of education
level, household income and the proportion of males among residents
aged 16 to 29.
   In one community, an education program featured wallet-sized
cards and small cardboard dials for estimating one's own
blood-alcohol concentration according to body weight and the number
of drinks consumed. About 3,000 dials were handed out in bars,
stores, restaurants and filling stations.
   Customers were trained to use the dials at those outlets and in
television announcements broadcast about 20 times a week. Worden
stressed that training at the outlets was important because it
ensured ``a lot of conversation about the program.''
   A second town was exposed only to the television announcements,
which mentioned a couple of local outlets for the dials. No training
was provided at those outlets.
   The third town received no portion of the program.
   Six months after the program began, police stopped all traffic on
six weekend nights in the three communities. Blood-alcohol
concentrations were measured in 333 drivers from the community that
had no part of the program, 405 from the town with only the
television announcements, and 154 from the community with the full
program.
   Analysis found that 11.1 percent of drivers from the town with no
intervention had concentrations of at least 0.05 percent, the level
at which the dial warned that driving becomes impaired.
   In the television-only community, 10.1 percent of drivers also
reached that level. But only 5.8 percent of drivers from the
full-program community scored that high.
   The legal driving limit of 0.1 percent blood alcohol was reached
by 3 percent of drivers from the no-program community and 4.7
percent from the television-only community, but only 0.6 percent
from the full-program community.
   Philip Graitcer, of the federal Centers for Disease Control's
division of injury epidemiology and control, cautioned that
questions remain about how effective such a program would be over a
longer period, whether it would work in other settings, and whether
it would in fact reduce accidents.
   Still, the relatively inexpensive program offers ``a strategy
that may work,'' he said.
   James F. Mosher, program director at the Marin Institute for the
Prevention of Alcohol and Other Drug Problems in San Rafael, Calif.,
said the program would be best used in combination with other
efforts, such as training bartenders and waiters to regulate
drinking among patrons.
   Such a package of strategies could also include increasing the
excise tax on alcoholic beverages and using local laws to decrease
risk of drunken driving, said Alex Wagenaar, head of the injury
analysis and prevention group at the University of Michigan
Transportation Research Institute in Ann Arbor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
