<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-20 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roh Puts Off Referendum, Dissidents Vow Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissidents said Monday they will fight
on to oust President Roh Tae-woo, who indefinitely postponed a
promised national referendum on his performance.
   Hundreds of students threw dozens of firebombs into two police
stations in the southern city of Kwangj, shouting ``Punish Roh
Tae-woo!'' according to the South Korean news agency Yonhap.
   The attack destroyed a police motorcycle and caused other
extensive damage, Yonhap said. There were no immediate reports of
injuries and arrests.
   Yonhap said the students also shouted slogans demanding an end to
annual ``Team Sprit'' exercises involving 200,000 South Korean and
U.S. soldiers.
   The attack came after police sneaked into Chosun University in
Kwangju and removed wall posters denouncing the exercises, Yonhap
said. Dissidents have accused the exercises of heightening tension
on the divided Korean peninsula and hampering unification with
communist North Korea.
   Roh has introduced broad democratic reforms since winning office
in late 1987, but many South Koreans distrust the government because
of its ties to the authoritarian regime of former President Chun
Doo-hwan.
   South Korea's main dissident alliance, the United National
Democratic Movement, urged Roh to stop ``fooling the people'' with
the referendum issue and said the alliance will push for Roh's
resignation.
   Roh postponed the midterm referendum he had promised during the
1987 election campaign, accusing anti-government forces of trying to
use the vote to organize violent protests and topple the government.
   The vote was expected to be scheduled for mid-April.
   ``Violent leftist forces are trying to overthrow the
government,'' Roh said in a nationally televised address Monday.
``Leftist forces are trying to use the midterm appraisal as a
foothold for overthrowing the free democratic system.''
   In Washington, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Roh was not legally required to call the vote.
   ``His decision is outside the normal constitutional requirements,
in the sense that this is a referendum that he proposed himself. We
certainly want to see a democratic process followed but at this
point we don't have any comment'' on the postponing of the
referendum, Fitzwater said.
   The dissident alliance charged Roh wants to delay the referendum
by recognizing his unpopularity. Some opposition and dissident
forces have demanded Roh stake his presidency on the referendum and
step down if defeated.
   It was not clear if Roh was backing away from the referendum
because of concern about potential unrest or because he feared the
government could not win the vote and might be forced into new
elections. Some government officials had expressed concern about
Roh's ability to win a referendum.
   The government had said earlier that Roh would not resign if he
was defeated, but some administration officials conceded a defeat
would put pressure on Roh to call elections.
   The main opposition parties said they accepted Roh's decision but
would watch to ensure the government does not attempt to retreat on
any other promises to bring in full democracy.
   The Party of Peace and Democracy of Kim Dae-jung welcomed the
referendum delay. The Reunification Democratic Party of Kim
Young-sam said it would accept only a temporary delay.
   Kim Young-sam had been pushing for a referendum after predicting
Roh would lose. Kim Dae-jung opposed a referendum, apparently
because Kim Young-sam's party had overtaken his in opinion polls.
   The Kims are bitter rivals who split the opposition vote in the
December 1987 elections, allowing Roh to win with 36 percent of the
vote. Roh promised during the election campaign to hold a referendum
after his first year in office to give voters a chance to evaluate
his performance.
</TEXT>
