<DOCNO> AP890320-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China Bjt   03-20 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Li Peng Opens Congress on Somber Note Stressing Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng opened the annual legislative
session Monday with a somber speech on China's economic crisis that
stressed centralized control and the need to halt political reforms.
   China's senior leader, 84-year-old Deng Xiaoping, did not attend
the session of the National People's Congress as he did last year. A
Foreign Affairs Ministry official said only that Deng ``asked for
leave.''
   Li's speech to the 2,768 legislators in the cavernous Great Hall
of the People marked the consolidation of a policy of economic and
political retrenchment that began in September.
   Whereas Congress last year called for democracy and bold attempts
to free China's economy from rigid central planning, Li's speech
called for control.
   ``Experience has proved time and again that without the necessary
centralization and unity, without strict organization and
discipline, it would be absolutely impossible to readjust the
economy and overcome difficulties,'' he said.
   Li also appeared to level veiled but pointed criticism at
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, who as premier in 1987 launched
China on an ambitious reform program.
   Silent for most of the 130-minute speech, the delegates erupted
in applause six times near its end when Li turned from the troubled
economy to issues at the heart of Chinese nationalism: Tibet and
foreign affairs.
   Any support for the independence of Tibet, Li said in reference
to recent bloody riots in Lhasa, ``constitutes an outrageous
interference in China's internal affairs and will absolutely not be
tolerated.''
   He also warned the United States to ``refrain from interfering
with China's internal affairs ... lest the existing friendly
relations between the two countries be impaired.''
   The U.S. Senate and State Department have expressed concern over
the violent suppression of Lhasa riots in which at least 16 people
were killed this month.
   Most of the speech, however, focused on China's troubled domestic
situation. Li read slowly, in a low monotone, pausing often to clear
his throat.
   China faces a record 36 percent inflation that has sparked panic
buying and bank runs. Rising crime affects its cities and corruption
sullies the halls of government.
   Much of the troubles have been blamed on inflation. In
September,China began a program to tackle price rises by slowing
reforms designed to introduce elements of a market economy to the
state-run system.
   ``Both government and people should be mentally prepared for a
few years of austerity,'' Li warned.
   Price reform, construction projects, loans, industrial growth and
consumer demand all should be cut, he said.
   Even some productive projects ``should be stopped or suspended''
and necessary construction projects ``follow an order of importance
and urgency.''
   Only education and agriculture would be spared, Li said.
   To halt a four-year slide in grain production, the state will
raise its grain purchase price by 18 percent on April 1, he said.
And banks will increase agricultural loans.
   He also announced a 15 percent increase in the education budget,
to $10 billion.
   Both sectors are considered key to development and critics say
they have been overlooked in recent budgets.
   Li appeared to blame party leader Zhao for inflation _ the root
of China's trouble.
   Zhao backed a full-steam-ahead approach to reforms when he was
premier in 1987, while Li was more cautious. At one point, Zhao said
the only criterion for whether reforms were successful was whether
they raised production.
   Li's speech roundly criticized this.
   ``We were too optimistic in our assessment of the economic
situation in 1987,'' he said. ``Instead of taking effective measures
... we relaxed control over and readjusted the prices of more
commodities only to intensify the panic of the masses over the price
hikes and evoke a buying spree.''
   The premier ignored a growing public clamor among intellectuals
for greater freedom of speech, evidenced by a recent call for an
amnesty for political prisoners.
   Instead, he said, all dialogue must take place ``under the
leadership of the Communist Party.''
   Li also said the economic troubles made it necessary to postpone
temporarily political reforms that would give more decision-making
power to businesses previously run by the state. Also, overstaffed
governments were to be cut back and a civil service system
introduced.
   The congress is meeting through April 4.
   Two important laws are expected to pass. One will give citizens
the right to sue the government. The other outlines the powers of
the congress, which does little but routinely endorse policy
directed by the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
