<FIRST>r w AM-Dumping-Hats     03-20 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dumping-Hats,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Department Says China Dumps Imports of Headwear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department said Monday it has made
a final determination that hats, caps and visors from China are
being sold in the United States at less than fair-market value.
   As a result of the finding, cash deposits or bonds will be
imposed on the imported headwear, which include items made from
certain natural and man-made fibers but not hats made of straw, felt
or wool.
   If the U.S. International Trade Commission finds that the
low-priced imports harm U.S. industry, Commerce will instruct the
Customs Service to collect the final anti-dumping duties. The ITC
has 45 days to make a ruling.
   The Commerce Department began its investigation after the
Headwear Institute of America filed a petition on behalf of the U.S.
industry. Imports of headwear from China in 1987 were valued at
about $40 million.
</TEXT>
