<HEAD>Envoy in Cuba for Talks on Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker is
in Cuba for talks on implementing the agreement under which Cuba
agreed to withdraw its forces from Angola, the State Department said
Monday.
   Crocker, who heads the State Department's Africa bureau, is
believed to be the highest-ranking U.S. official to visit Cuba since
Ambassador Vernon Walters went there in March 1982.
   But State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Crocker's
talks there are limited strictly to the southwest African issue.
Crocker and a Soviet official are attending the talks as observers.
   The discussions are centered on resolving disputes relating to
the agreement signed last December by Cuba, South Africa and Angola.
   In addition to the phased withdrawal of the more than 50,000
Cuban troops in stages from Angola, the agreement calls for South
Africa to relinquish colonial control over Namibia.
