<DOCNO> AP890320-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103-Ministers     03-20 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Ministers,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Dispute Produces Classic British Political Confrontation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the center of the controversy over bomb warnings
before the Pan Am Flight 103 disaster is a classic British political
confrontation: an old Etonian millionaire Cabinet minister vs. an
ex-waiter leading an opposition onslaught.
   For Transport Secretary Paul Channon, son of a British brewing
heiress and an American social high-flyer, the Dec. 21 crash in
Scotland was the low point in an unprecedented string of rail, air
and sea disasters in the past two years.
   And from his departure for a vacation at his private villa in the
Caribbean on Dec. 23 through mounting charges the past five days
that he bungled bomb warnings, Channon has been under concerted
attack by John Prescott, a railman's son who is the opposition Labor
Party's transport spokesman.
   ``My response is one of contempt,'' Channon said over the
weekend. ``His behavior has been both callous and cynical. ... He is
exploiting the grief of the bereaved.''
   The latest furor began after a newspaper revealed last week that
Channon's department warned British airlines Nov. 22 of a
radio-cassette bomb, four days after the Federal Aviation Department
sent the same warning to U.S. airlines, including Pan Am.
   A detailed description and picture of the bomb dated Dec. 19 was
mailed ``in the new year'' by the Transport Department to British
airlines and U.S. airlines _ well after a bomb hidden in a
radio-cassette player brought down Flight 103 over the Scottish
village of Lockerbie, killing 270 people.
   Despite unattributable briefings from Conservative Party Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's aides that she still supports him,
Channon looks increasingly defensive as Prescott hammers home
charges of cavalier and secretive behavior.
   Channon has said the Dec. 19 warning was ``unimportant'' and that
he didn't tell Parliament about either warning because of the
continuing inquiry and because the FAA dealt with Pan Am.
   Said Prescott: ``This has all the signs of a cover-up once they
realized the bungle they had made of it all.''
   Channon and Prescott come from the extremes of mainstream British
political life.
   Prescott, 50, left school at age 15 to become a ship's waiter and
got to Parliament after battling through the ranks of the National
Union of Seamen.
   Channon, 54, is reputedly the richest member of the Thatcher
Cabinet. He was born to privilege and politics and an inherited
fortune as a member of the Guinness brewing family.
   His father, Sir Henry Channon, came from a rich Chicago family,
married into the Guinness family and became a member of Parliament.
   After Eton, an elite Guards regiment and Oxford, Channon was
elected to Parliament at the age of 23. He was then its then
youngest member, representing a safe Conservative Party district,
Southend West, that had been held by his father, and before that by
two other family members.
   However, it took Channon 27 years to get into the Cabinet.
   Mrs. Thatcher named him Trade and Industry Secretary in 1986 and,
in what was widely seen as a demotion, moved him to transport after
Britain's June 1987 general election.
   Channon's 22-year-old daughter, Olivia, an Oxford University
student, died of a drug overdose in 1986 after an around-the-clock
party at the university to celebrate final examinations.
   Three fellow undergraduates, including a cousin and another
Guinness heir, were charged with drug offenses _ raising a public
outcry over a drugs scandal among the children of privilege.
   Since then, Channon has been one of the most publicized members
of the 22-member Cabinet: announcing in slightly tentative, upper
class tones another inquiry into yet another disaster, his face
anxious and solemn at another scene of carnage.
   He took over transport during an inquiry into the March 1987
British ferry disaster off the Belgian port of Zeebrugge that killed
193 people and revealed lax safety procedures.
   Then followed a fire at London's King's Cross subway station that
killed 31 people in November 1987; the Pan Am disaster; a British
Midland jet crash onto a highway on Jan. 8, killing 37 people; and
three major rail accidents since December that killed 42 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
