<DOCNO> AP890320-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2010EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CancerAward     03-20 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Award,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancer Gene Pioneer Gets $50,000 Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $50,000 Bristol-Myers cancer research award
has gone to Peter K. Vogt of the University of Southern California
School of Medicine for his discovery of a cancer-causing gene that
regulates other growth-related genes, it was announced Monday.
   The identification of the gene is ``one of the most significant
discoveries in the last several years,'' said Philip Sharp, director
of the Center for Cancer Research at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
   Sharp chaired the selection committee that chose Vogt for the
annual award.
   Vogt has also discovered several other cancer genes and has made
important contributions to the study of virology, Bristol-Myers said.
   ``His is an astonishing record of sustained productivity,
unrelenting in its importance and impact,'' wrote J. Michael Bishop,
a noted cancer researcher, in support of Vogt's selection, the
company said.
   Vogt discovered the so-called jun cancer gene, which is partly
responsible for switching other genes on and off inside living cells.
   When the gene is altered, it may send defective signals to the
genes it governs, producing the abnormalities seen in cancer.
   Vogt is the author of more than 210 scientific papers and was
elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1980, the company
said.
   He was selected by a 14-member independent group of researchers
chaired by Sharp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
