<HEAD>Experts Studying Bones From Site Bundy Said Was Victim's Grave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPITOL REEF NATIONAL PARK, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bones found at a site
identified by serial killer Ted Bundy as the grave of one of his
victims have been sent to state forensic experts to determine if
they are human, police said Monday.
   The Wayne County Sheriff's Department said the bones, which
investigators believe may be those of 17-year-old Nancy Wilcox of
Holladay, were delivered by Highway Patrol troopers to the state
medical examiner's office in Salt Lake City.
   Testing of the bones, found Friday, should be finished Thursday
or Friday, Sheriff Kerry Ekker said.
   Bundy was executed Jan. 24 in Florida's electric chair. Before he
died, he told detectives he had killed more than 20 women, including
eight in Utah. Of the Utah victims, he identified only three, among
them Wilcox, who he said was buried near Capitol Reef National Park,
200 miles south of Salt Lake City.
   The bones were among remains found at three sites a mile east of
the park. Also found at one of the sites was a fragment of what
appeared to be a tan blouse.
   Bones at two of the sites were believed to be those of animals.
   Ekker noted that the bones sent to the crime lab were found
partially exposed, and that the site would not be further excavated
until the medical examiner's office completes testing.
   The other two women Bundy identified among his early has,
