<DOCNO> AP890320-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chernobyl     03-20 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chernobyl,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Living on Radiation-Contaminated Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost a quarter-million Soviets are living on land
so contaminated by the Chernobyl disaster that they must receive
special food supplies to avoid overexposure to radiation, the
newspaper Pravda said Monday.
   The Communist Party daily printed maps showing contaminated areas
of Byelorussia, the Ukraine and the Russian republic in response to
readers' complaints they still didn't have full information about
the level of contamination nearly three years after the accident.
   It was accompanied by a commentary by Pravda science editor V.
Gubarev, who criticized officials for trying to duck public concern
about the safety of nuclear power.
   ``Yes, it is impossible to get around using nuclear power
stations. However, why then are they proposed for heavily populated
or seismic zones?'' Gubarev asked. ``Why is the quality of
construction so low, and why does so much defective equipment arrive
at nuclear plants? And, finally, what is the source of this fear
before a public which rightly demands a wide debate of every
proposed nuclear power station?''
   Yuri Izrael, chairman of the State Committee for
Hydrometeorology, said with decontamination efforts and food brought
into the area, those on the lands contaminated by Cesium 137 can
live safely without exceeding radiation limits set by the government.
   Soviet officials began bringing food supplies into areas
surrounding the Chernobyl plant shortly after the accident, but they
had not previously said how many people were living in those areas.
   The publication came as Soviet officials again started to move
villagers who have continued to live in areas surrounding the plant
since the accident in April 1986 that killed at least 31 people.
   In February, scientists decided that 20 Byelorussian villages
must be evacuated because over a lifetime their residents would
receive an unacceptably high dose of radiation. Earlier this month,
officials announced that five villages in the Ukraine also would be
evacuated.
   In November, the Soviet government set a maxium lifetime dose of
35 rem (roetgen equivalent, man) for exposure to radiation. That
figure has a comfortable margin of safety built into it, Izrael said.
   Izrael said the area of the three republics where the current
level of radiation from both the environment and existing food
supplies would expose residents to more than 35 rem includes 4,000
square miles including about 640 settlements with 230,000 people.
   That includes 800 square miles in the Russian republic, 600
square miles in the Ukraine and 2,800 square miles in Byelorussia,
including 1,200 square miles in areas that have been evacuated.
   ``So far they have gone the route here of trying to guarantee
this population clean food and extra income,'' Izrael said.
   Izrael said studies showed that residents could remain safely as
long as they did not eat the food, especially meat and milk produced
in the area, which sharply increased the amount of radiation to
which they were exposed.
   He quoted the newspaper Sovietskaya Byelorussia as saying in a
study of the Gomel, Mogilev and Brest regions of the republic less
than 0.1 percent of the population had received an unacceptably high
level of radiation. As of last fall, there had been no cases of
radiation sickness, he said.
   Scientists are debating how many more cancer deaths might be
expected in the Soviet Union and Europe as a result of the Chernobyl
accident. In Poland, they have estimated there may be up to 200,000
deaths in the next 20 to 25 years from Chernobyl radiation.
   But Izrael said that long years of work were ahead to
decontaminate the region. ``Insufficiencies in this work must be
compensated by replacement with clean food (especially by bringing
in milk). In this case life and work is possible within the
framework of the acceptable levels established by the Soviet
Ministry of Health,'' he said.
   Izrael said that within the first days after the explosion and
fire at the Chernobyl plant's No. 4 reactor, the direction of the
wind made a complete circle and dropped radiation all around the
plant.
   The entire population living within 18{ miles of the plant, or
about 135,000 people, were evacuated and resettled.
   Since then, many Soviets have begun to speak out against nuclear
power. Citizens' protests or tougher standards imposed after the
Chernobyl accident have stopped several nuclear power plants. A
plant near Yerevan, Armenia, not far from the site of the Dec. 7
earthquake, was shut down Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
