<DOCNO> AP890320-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Prosecutor'sNightmare     03-20 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prosecutor's Nightmare,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Reconsidered In Boston Police Misconduct Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detectives whose partner was killed during a drug
raid lied so many times to try to bring the alleged murderer to
trial that they blew the case, defense lawyers argued Monday.
   Other lawyers say the admitted misconduct by police could also
call into question dozens of convictions in which the officers
participated.
   Defense attorneys and the prosecutor agreed during the Superior
Court hearing Monday that there was serious police misconduct in the
case against Albert Lewin, 33, accused of shooting the detective
Feb. 17, 1987.
   But the prosecutor, Assistant District Attorney Francis O'Meara,
argued that Lewin should stand trial because there is strong
evidence against him and because the police have ``come clean'' by
admitting they lied to obtain a search warrant and hid the identity
of potential witnesses.
   The three detectives, Carlos A. Luna, 32, Hugo Amate, 31, and
Paul Schroeder, 33, were suspended with pay while the attorney
general investigates possible perjury.
   Judge Charles M. Grabau dismissed the murder charge against Lewin
last month, but agreed to consider reinstating it after the
detectives filed affidavits last week admitting they previously lied.
   Grabau said he would rule next week whether Lewin can be tried
for the murder of Detective Sherman Griffiths.
   Defense attorney Max Stern argued that the case against Lewin is
weak and depends heavily on testimony from other potential suspects
who may be lying to protect themselves.
   Griffiths, 36, was killed by a bullet shot through a door that he
was trying to break down to execute a drug search warrant.
   By the time his partners got through the steel-reinforced door,
the third-floor apartment was empty. They rushed down a back
staircase and found Lewin and six other people in an apartment on
the first floor.
   Charges were later dropped against the others in return for
damaging testimony against Lewin.
   A weakness in the prosecution's case from the outset was that
Lewin did not match the search warrant's description of the cocaine
dealer police said occupied the apartment and presumably fired the
fatal shot.
   An informant named John tipped detectives that drugs were being
sold from the apartment by a 5-foot-6 inch Hispanic man, according
to the police application for the warrant. Lewin is 6-foot-2 and
Jamaican.
   After the judge ordered the detectives last year to bring the
informant into court, they said they couldn't find him.
   In throwing out the case last month, Grabau said he believed the
police had intentionally disobeyed his orders to produce the witness.
   But in a stunning turnaround last week, the detectives admitted
John did not exist.
   According to the affidavits, the information attributed to John
actually came from two other informants, identified in court only as
``Y'' and ``Z.''
   O'Meara said Monday the detectives created John to protect their
real informants.
   ``When the playing field is not level, when it's skewed, when
it's fixed, then the (court) system can't work,'' Stern said.
``That's what you have here.''
   Stern also said the detectives obtained at least 30 other
warrants and conducted drug raids using information attributed to
``John.''
   Martin Rosenthal, a staff member for the Massachusetts Committee
for Public Counsel Services, said Sunday that defense lawyers are
now examining many of those cases and are likely to file motions for
new trials.
   Where faulty warrants led to arrests and convictions, he said,
convicted dealers could go free under a rule that bars evidence
obtained through police misconduct.
   Harvey Silverglate, co-chairman of the 320-member Massachusetts
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said the Lewin case has
revealed what many lawyers suspected all along.
   ``Anybody who practices criminal law here can tell you that we
have great skepticism about these warrants,'' Silverglate said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
