<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Explosion     03-20 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Explosion,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed, 41 Hurt in Explosion of Ammonia Tank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ammonia tank exploded at a factory in Lithuania
on Monday, killing at least two people and injuring 41, state media
said.
   The blast released a cloud of gas into the air that was being
pushed eastward by the wind, but officials said it was unlikely that
any populated areas would have to be evacuated.
   A government commission was formed to investigate the cause of
the blast at the Azot factory in Ionava, about 45 miles northwest of
the Lithuanian capital of Vilnius, the official Tass news agency
said. The tank contained about 7,000 cubic meters of ammonia.
   It took firefighters several hours to put out blazes that broke
out, and an unspecified number of people were evacuated near the
plant, Lithuania's Deputy Premier Y.L. Rusenko told Soviet
television.
   ``I think that the concentration will not be increased because
all the ammonium has practially been evaporated above Ionava,'' he
said.
   ``If it is necessary people will be evacuated in other regions,
if a cloud approaches and the concentration is high. But I think the
danger has passed,'' Rusenko said.
   Residents were warned about the explosion and the release of
ammonia by official radio after the late morning explosion, he said.
Without being specific, Tass said that security had been tightened.
   Residents of Lithuania and the other Soviet Baltic republics of
Latvia and Estonia are concerned about environmental damage caused
by the heavy concentration of industry in the almost 50 years since
they were absorbed into the Soviet Union.
   Many people blame the central government in Moscow for ordering
the heavy industrialization without showing concern for
environmental damage.
</TEXT>
