<FIRST>r w AM-FarmExports     03-20 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Exports,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Sales to Japan Top Sales to Europe for First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sales of farm products to Japan will reach
$8.2 billion to $8.3 billion this year, topping sales to Western
Europe for the first time, a federal official told Congress Monday.
   U.S. exports to the 12 countries of the European Economic
Community are expected to drop to $7.3 billion for the year ending
Sept. 30, said Administrator Thomas O. Kay of the Foreign
Agricultural Service. For all of Western Europe, which includes such
non-members of the community as Switzerland and Sweden, total U.S.
sales are expected to reach $7.8 billion.
   In the year that ended last Sept. 30, exports to the 12 EEC
countries reached $7.5 billion, against $7.3 billion to Japan.
   Kay, testifying at a hearing of the House Agriculture
subcommittee on Rural Development, said he agreed with the panel's
acting chairman, Rep. Daniel K. Akaka, D-Hawaii, that the biggest
gains for U.S. farm sales are coming from the Pacific countries.
   He noted that China is now the biggest importer of U.S. wheat,
and he predicted big increases in exports to South Korea, which are
rising to $2.5 billion this year from $2.3 billion.
   ``We are transferring our resources to that area _ that's where
the future lies,'' Kay said.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager at the Agriculture
Department, said this will be the last year in which South Korea
will get loans supported by the U.S. government to encourage its
purchases.
   Sims reported that in less than six months since Oct. 1, the
Agriculture Department has announced nearly $4.8 billion worth of
guaranteed loans to 23 countries, almost as much as in the 12
previous months.
   Kay said U.S. farmers ``love'' subsidies for sales abroad. The
program has increased their prices and reduced the surplus of farm
products, he explained.
   In testimony submitted to the subcommittee, Kay said total U.S.
exports this year are due to rise to $38 billion, up $2.7 billion
from 1988. He attributed the increase to higher prices because of
last summer's s drought. The volume of farm exports is due to drop
by 2 percent.
</TEXT>
