<FIRST>r i AM-China-Deng     03-20 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Deng,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Conspicuously Absent From Congress Opening</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deng Xiaoping, China's 84-year-old leader, was
conspicuous by his absence from Friday's opening of the nation's
annual legislative session.
   As the National People's Congress opened, Western reporters
sitting in the balcony of the huge Great Hall of the People clutched
their binoculars and scanned the dais for the country's senior
statesman. They came up empty.
   An official from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs would say only
that Deng had ``asked for leave'' from the conference. Chen Yun,
another elderly leader who heads the Communist Party's Advisory
Committee, had done the same, she said.
   Deng attended the opening last year's opening session as a
delegate from Sichuan province. He sat between Communist Party chief
Zhao Ziyang and Premier Li Peng.
   This year, President Yang Shangkun took Deng's seat.
   No empty seats appeared to have been set aside for the man who
fathered China's current economic reforms in 1978. Two seats were
empty on the left side of the dais, not traditionally the places for
high-ranking officials.
   Although he remains the power behind party and state in China,
Deng officially only has charge of the military.
   As the People's Liberation Army does not report directly to the
National People's Congress, his presence at the meeting is not
mandatory.
   Still, Deng's absence and the reaction it created among members
of the Western press illustrates one of the difficulties of
understanding Chinese politics. Much here is done for effect, but
often it is difficult to tell what the desired effect is.
   Deng last was seen Friday when he greeted Thai Prime Minister
Chatichai Choonhavan in Beijing.
   He appeared spry and remarked that Chatichai had played golf with
Zhao the day before.
   ``I'm also a sportsman,'' Deng said. ``I play bridge.''
</TEXT>
