<FIRST>r a AM-IllinoisHandguns     03-20 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Illinois Handguns,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose to Tighten Handgun Licensing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's easier to buy and register a handgun in
Illinois than to apply for a driver's license, two lawmakers said
Monday in proposing a package of laws to keep better track of
weapons and their owners.
   Residents now can obtain a Firearm Owner's Identification Card by
mail. The card is valid for five years and allows its possessor to
keep as many weapons of any kind as desired without reporting the
total number or serial numbers.
   Under the legislation proposed by Democratic state Sens. William
Marovitz and Phil Rock, owners would have to get separate ID cards
for each handgun, and fill out the applications at a local law
enforcement agency.
   The card would be good for three years, and applicants would have
to furnish more detailed personal history than currently required.
   Chicago police Supterintendent LeRoy Martin said Chicago's crime
rate dipped last year and said his force's confiscation of 14,000
weapons had a significant effect.
   ``Over 50 percent of the 14,000 can't be identified,'' he said.
``If we could trace them, it would make a big difference. We know
people are buying the guns and selling them or renting them to
gangs, and this would enable us to follow some of the weapons back
to the source.''
   James Zangrilli, a member of the National Rifle Association's
board of directors, objected to the legislation.
   Many states and localities have taken steps limiting gun sales or
possession in recent weeks. President Bush last week ordered a
temporary ban on imports of assault rifles.
</TEXT>
