<FIRST>r w AM-SurplusCommodities     03-20 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Surplus Commodities,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Commodity Stockpile Shrinking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive stockpile of government-owned grain
and other commodities has been reduced to about half what it was a
year ago, the Agriculture Department reported Monday.
   The department's Commodity Credit Corp., which handles price
support operations, said the value of products under its control as
of Dec. 31 totaled $15.8 billion, down from $29.6 billion a year
earlier.
   Under CCC programs, when a crop is placed by farmers under price
support loan, the commodity cannot be sold or used by producers
until the loan is settled. In many cases, when market prices fail to
rise enough to make it worthwhile to pay off the loans, farmers
forfeit the commodity to the CCC, which then holds it as
``inventory'' or surplus.
   As of Dec. 31, the CCC had loans outstanding on $11 billion worth
of commodities and held $4.8 billion in its inventories. A year
earlier, CCC holdings were $17.3 billion and $12.3 billion,
respectively.
   Last year's drought, which cut production sharply, helped force
up market prices and ease the CCC load. Overseas demand also has
been a factor. Domestic use and also higher market prices or changes
in program policies have been other reasons.
   In the case of corn and other feed grains, for example, the Dec.
31 total held by CCC was about 2.36 billion bushels valued at $7.77
billion, including both loans and inventory. A year earlier feed
grains totaled 7.52 billion bushels worth $16.7 billion.
   The Dec. 31 wheat total was less than 768 million bushels valued
at $2.69 billion, down from 1.77 billion bushels worth $5.99 billion
a year earlier.
   Holdings of dairy products bought by CCC to support the price of
milk paid to farmers totaled 454.7 million pounds valued at $602.2
million, compared with 1.16 billion pounds and $1.43 billion a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
