<FIRST>r a AM-Cuomo-DeathPenalty     03-20 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuomo-Death Penalty,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Vetoes Death Penalty Legislation for Seventh Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo told a college audience
Monday that New York state must show leadership in this ``hour of
fright'' and then vetoed the latest legislation that would restore
the death penalty.
   Before issuing his seventh consecutive veto, Cuomo defended his
opposition to the death penalty before a rally of about 400 people
at Albany's Roman Catholic College of St. Rose. He again urged
lawmakers to approve his alternative of life without parole for some
murderers.
   ``The people of New York ought now in this hour of fright to show
the way,'' Cuomo said. ``We should refuse to allow this time to be
marked forever in the pages of history as a time that we were driven
back to one of the vestiges of our primitive condition because we
were not strong enough ... to find a better end to the violence.''
   It was the opening salvo of what is expected to be an intense
legislative battle. New York is one of 13 states without an operable
death penalty law. New York, which introduced the electric chair to
the world in 1890, has not executed anyone since 1963.
   With a crack epidemic and its accompanying violence sweeping
through New York City, supporters of the death penalty in the
Legislature claim they'll have enough votes to override Cuomo's
veto. An override attempt is expected in June.
   ``I know that this society should strive for something better
than we are in our worst moments,'' Cuomo said. ``It isn't easy for
people to hold back their anger ... but that is the only rational
course.''
   Cuomo said there's no persuasive evidence the death penalty
deters murderers. He said most would be more frightened by the
thought of spending the rest of their lives in prison.
   Both houses of New York's Legislature have already approved the
latest death penalty bill, for the 13th consecutive year. Cuomo has
vetoed the legislation every year he's been in office, as did former
Gov. Hugh Carey in the six years before that.
</TEXT>
