<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-UN     03-20 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-UN,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Applauds Change at United Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush exhorted newly installed
Ambassador Thomas Pickering on Monday to push for continued changes
at the United Nations, saying he's pleased with what he considers
improvements so far.
   During a White House swearing-in ceremony for the veteran foreign
service officer, Bush said the awarding of the Nobel Prize last year
to the U.N.'s peacekeeping team in Lebanon was a sign of a
turn-around for the organization.
   ``The U.N. can be a force for peace, a forum for resolving
conflict,'' he said. ``And as proof of this, consider its
instrumental role in the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, in the
Iran-Iraq war.''
   With Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Pickering at his
side, Bush used the occasion to applaud changes in U.N. management
practices under the leadership of Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar, saying he ``is doing a good job and he deserves our
support.''
   The Reagan administration late last year agreed to begin repaying
to the United Nations more than $474 million the United States had
withheld in protest of what it said were inadequate management
controls and insufficient attention to peacemaking initiatives.
   In his remarks Monday, Bush, who served as U.N. ambassador during
the Nixon administration, said he wants Pickering to make a special
effort in the world body to focus attention on ``the question of
human rights in Cuba.''
   ``The United Nations is on the right track toward reform and is
now a more effective organization,'' the president said. He praised
Pickering, 67, as a ``skilled diplomat, a veteran of high-priority,
tough assignments.''
