<HEAD>Gunmen Kill 17 Sinhalese, Indian Troops Shoot 12 Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed 17 Sinhalese men in a
shooting spree in north-central Sri Lanka, and Indian troops shot
and killed 12 Tamil rebels in separate weekend clashes, witnesses
and the military said Monday.
   Residents of Tirappane village said on condition of anonymity
that the Sinhalese victims were shot and then hacked to death Sunday
by unidentified assailants.
   Also on Sunday, Sinhalese rebels were blamed for seven other
deaths, military officials said.
   The motive behind the Tirappane killings was not immediately
known, but residents said the murders may be linked to the
assassination of three policemen by Sinhalese radicals in a nearby
village earlier Sunday.
   The policemen were killed when Sinhalese rebels detonated
explosives by remote control and blew up a jeep at Epawalla village,
about 15 miles southeast of Anuradhapura town.
   Police said an organization known as the ``Black Cats'' may be
responsible for the Tirappane murders. The group's aim is to
eliminate supporters of the radical Sinhalese group known as the
People's Liberation Front, police said.
   The Sinhalese Front is opposed to the government's peace offers
to Tamil rebels.
   Sinhalese radicals also killed four people on Sunday in Kaduwela,
a Colombo suburb.
   Elsewhere, six Tamil rebels were killed when they tried to ambush
an Indian patrol in northern Jaffna, 185 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Six more rebels were killed in a second clash with Indian
soldiers in Mullaitivu district, about 170 miles northeast of
Colombo.
   India has an estimated 40,000 troops in Sri Lanka to enforce a
peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in the north and east, where they predominate.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They say they are discriminated against by the
Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
