<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Cristiani 2ndLd-Writethru a0659 03-20 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Cristiani, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0659,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cristiani Seeks to Overcome Party's Ultra-right Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 11-14, `Although Cristiani...economic problems' with
11 grafs to ADD background; CORRECTS that previous election in 1984 stead
1985 and that Cristiani was elected to National Assembly. Pick up 15th
pvs, ``We must...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfredo Cristiani used his own
commercial success and public discontent with a long civil war to
overcome his party's image of an ultra-right movement linked to
death squads.
   Cristiani, who claimed victory in Sunday's presidential election,
says his Republican Nationalist Alliance party, known as Arena, is a
political force no one can ignore.
   Arena was founded by Roberto d'Aubuisson, a former army major
frequently accused of organizing right-wing death squads, and many
people wonder whether Cristiani runs the party or is a figurehead
for d'Aubuisson.
   Before the election, Cristiani said the U.S. government ``cannot
dismiss'' his party ``in the simplistic manner it did in the past.''
   ``We consider the United States our natural ally, but it cannot
come and impose models or conditions,'' said Cristiani, who attended
Georgetown University in Washington.
   U.S. administrations have criticized d'Aubuisson, who was
dismissed from the army in 1980 on grounds of plotting a coup. The
party founder denies the allegations against him.
   D'Aubuisson formed the party in 1981. It has gained popularity in
recent years and it won a slim legislative majority in 1988, which
puts it in the position of controlling both the legislative and
executive branches.
   Cristiani, a 41-year-old coffee farmer and distributor of medical
supplies, appealed in the campaign to El Salvador's traditionally
conservative middle and upper classes, and to others tired of a
9-year-old war that has taken more than 70,000 lives.
   ``I'd rather be sitting in my office'' than running for
president,'' he said in a pre-election interview. ``I am here
because I am convinced that my country can progress if we are free
in every sense of the word and adopt an economic model for
development.''
   At his side throughout the campaign was d'Aubuisson, stirring up
the crowds at rallies.
   D'Aubuisson lost the 1984 presidential election to Christian
Democrat Jose Napoleon Duarte. Cristiani, a member of Arena since
1982, became the party president in 1985 when d'Aubuisson stopped
down from that post.
   D'Aubuisson is currently an Arena representative in the National
Assembly and is still referred to by many party members as ``maximum
leader.''
   Cristiani, who has not been linked to the death squads, was
elected to the National Assembly in 1985 and re-elected last year.
   In a recent interview by The Associated Press, Christiani was
asked why d'Aubuisson had quit as Arena president.
   ``He recognized that his figure and all that had been said about
him was prejudicial to the party's image,'' he said.
   Cristiani also commented on the United States and d'Aubuisson.
   ``D'Aubuisson personally cannot expect the support of the United
States,'' he said. ``Even if he were to be born again his image
could not be changed there. They damaged it so much beyond
salvation.''
   Cristiani blames Arena's image problem on the foreign news media
_ especially the U.S. media. He also has criticized the U.S.
government for what he calls the ``distortion'' of Arena's image.
   Cristiani is a tall, angular man with a soft voice, graying
moustache and hair combed straight back, an exemplar of the economic
class that blames the military and politicians of the past for the
nation's ills.
   ``We may be conservative,'' he said of Arena, ``but we are the
only party that has defined the social problems of the country and
that offers a solution.''
   He said President Duarte, barred by the consitution from seeking
re-election, failed to end the war and solve economic problems.
   ``We must have a clear economic model _ a free market _ that
benefits all sectors of society; avoid protectionism, (and) let the
government take care only of those services where private business
will not enter,'' he said.
   Peace is a ``viable probablity'' if leftist guerrillas join the
democratic process, he said.
   If they don't, the alternative is ``efficient, professional use
of the armed forces, but we would rather sit down and talk about a
national peace proposal so we all may re-enter a peaceful life,''
Cristiani declared.
   ``Some objectives have been achieved and the main thing is that
all political parties are participating in the election.''
   Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a member of the rebel political
commission, said in an interview in Mexico City that Cristiani is on
the ``rational'' right but she fears d'Aubuisson is ``the power
behind the throne.''
</TEXT>
