<DOCNO> AP890320-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DangerPay 630   03-20 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Danger Pay, 630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Bonus Ends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The payment of monthly ``imminent danger''
bonuses to sailors deployed in the Persian Gulf will come to an end
April 1, the Pentagon said Monday.
   The bonuses, previously known as hostile fire or combat pay, are
worth $110 a month and have been paid to servicemen working inside
the Persian Gulf since August 25, 1987.
   Defense sources disclosed almost two months ago that Gen. H.
Norman Schwarzkopf, the head of the U.S. Central Command, had
recommended an end to the bonuses because the truce in the Iran-Iraq
war was continuing to hold.
   Adm. William J. Crowe, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
approved the recommendation recently and officials in the Defense
Department's manpower office then signed the order Monday, said
William Caldwell, a Pentagon spokesman.
   According to Pentagon statistics, about $16 million has been paid
out in danger bonuses since August 1987. Before the ceasefire took
hold in the Iran-Iraq war last August, about 8,000 servicemen were
receiving the payments every month.
   While most of those receiving the bonuses were deployed on ships
in the region or flew warplanes over the Persian Gulf's waters,
servicemen assigned to small bases in Bahrain and Kuwait were also
eligible. As a result, about 1,300 women also received the bonuses
at one point or another, the Pentagon said.
   According to defense officials who declined to be identified,
Schwarzkopf concluded early last January the threat to Americans
assigned to the region ``has receded to the point that it is
difficult to justify danger payments.''
   ``And the fact that we went to a different regime _ one of
monitoring ship traffic instead of actually escorting tankers
directly _ changed things, too,'' observed one source, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The Central Command is the organization responsible for American
military operations in the Middle East and Indian Ocean region. As
such, it is the parent command for the Joint Task Force Middle East,
the unit responsible for guaranteeing the safety of merchant ships
flying the U.S. flag in the Persian Gulf.
   The administration of former President Ronald Reagan agreed in
the spring of 1987 to extend American military protection to 11
Kuwaiti tankers after they re-registered under the Stars and
Stripes. Kuwait, a friend of the United States and a key ally of
Iraq, had seen its ships become a special target of Iranian forces.
   In August 1987, one month after the first Kuwaiti tanker to be
escorted ran into an underwater mine, the Pentagon announced it
would start making the payments to the crews of warships operating
inside the Persian Gulf, the Strait of Hormuz and a small portion of
the Gulf of Oman, as well as personnel in Kuwait and Bahrain.
   Iran and Iraq agreed to a truce last August in their bloody,
8-year-old war and to date, the cease-fire has held. As a result,
the United States has slowly reduced the number of warships
operating in the region and stopped conducting closely supervised
convoy runs.
   Instead, the ships now in the region maintain what the Navy calls
a ``monitoring regime'' of keeping U.S.-flag tankers within radar or
radio range.
   The authority to make imminent danger payments was provided to
the Pentagon in 1983 under an amendment to a law that had previously
established procedures for providing hostile fire, or combat, pay.
   The new law specified that danger pay could be provided to
servicemen deployed in areas where there was a risk of terrorism or
other physical threats, even though American forces were not
directly involved in combat.
   After April 1, only a small number of servicemen assigned to four
countries _ Lebanon, El Salvador, Colombia and Peru _ will be
receiving the danger bonuses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-ElSalvador 2ndLd-Writethru a0676 03-20 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-El Salvador, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0676,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Support for Salvador Linked to Rights Performance</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 5 grafs after 8th graf pvs, ``But what, to update with
comment from McConnell, Coelho.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday it is prepared
to support the Salvadoran government that emerges from Sunday's
national election _ but only so long as it respects democracy and
protects human rights.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman praised the Salvadoran people
for having braved ``violence and terror'' by leftist guerrillas who,
he said, tried harder to disrupt Sunday's balloting than in any
other election in seven years.
   ``Our position is that we support the democratic process, that we
are prepared to support the person who emerges from that democratic
process,'' Redman said.
   ``Our relationship with that new government will dependon its
adherence to democracy and respect for human rights, the twin
pillars of our approach to El Salvador.''
   Redman spoke hours before the candidate of the ruling Christian
Democratic Party, Fidel Chavez Mena, conceded defeat to Alfredo
Cristiani, nominee of the rightist Arena party.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
judgments about human rights will be a ``very important factor'' in
guiding U.S. policy toward El Salvador.
   Vice President Dan Quayle also criticized FMLN guerrilla attempts
to disrupt the voting. Asked by reporters about the deaths of two
Salvadoran and one Dutch journalist Sunday at the hands of security
forces, Quayle said he lacked details.
   ``But what ought to be disturbing to the American people, and I
know it's disturbing to the people of El Salvador, is the fact that
the FMLN threatened the people of El Salvador with their lives for
exercising the democratic right to vote. That is a very disturbing,
shocking event and we ouht to be shocked about that,'' Quayle said
after an awards ceremony.
   Two members of a U.S. delegation sent by President Bush to
observe the election _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and Rep. Tony
Coelho, D-Calif. _ said the process appeared to be fair but the
actions of the new government will decide whether U.S. aid continues.
   ``We concluded that it was a free and fair and honest election,''
McConnell said. ``Clearly the activities of the FMLN had some impact
on turnout in some areas of the country.''
   Coelho said the delegation met with Cristiani and told him that
``if they return to the death squads, return to the killing of the
early '80s, they should not expect support from individuals in our
legislature as well as our government.''
   But McConnell cautioned against applying an unreasonable standard.
   ``We had more murders in this city (Washington) last year than
they did in the occupied territories of the Middle East. We're not
in a very good position to be lecturing people about violence,'' he
said. ``The standard we need to apply here is not to expect that no
violence will occur in a country in which a war is going on but
rather how incidents are handled.''
   Meanwhile, dozens of demonstrators were removed by police Monday
from a State Department entrance as hundreds of others protesting
U.S. support for the Salvadoran government chanted from across the
street.
   The demonstrators did not resist as they were dragged away from
the diplomatic entrance. Barricades were then put up and employees
were diverted to other entrances.
   Placards and chants accused the United States of supporting
right-wing ``death squads.''
   Redman said the government of outgoing President Jose Napoleon
Duarte was committed to democracy and to improving human rights
performance.
   ``We will look to the new Salvadoran government to uphold the
same standards and to press for improvement,'' Redman said.
   The election took place amid growing restiveness in Congress
about American policy in El Salvador, partly because of the Arena
party's growing strength.
   A key figure in the Arena hierarchy is Maj. Roberto D'Aubuisson,
who was once described by a former U.S. ambassador to El Salvador,
Robert White, as a ``pathological killer.'' In 1980, the Carter
administration stripped D'Aubuisson of his U.S. visa.
   As administration and congressional sources see it, continued
legislative support for large-scale aid for El Salvador will depend
in some measure on Cristiani's ability to demonstrate that he is
more than a front man for D'Aubuisson.
   Although returns are not final, Cristiani has claimed victory
over the candidate of the ruling Christian Democratic party, Fidel
Chavez Mena.
   The United States has provided about $3.5 billion in economic and
military assistance to El Salvador during this decade, making it the
largest recipient of assistance in the hemisphere.
   Some in Congress maintain that the United States has received
little in return on its investment, pointing out that
politically-motivated killings average about 20 a month and that
efforts to negotiate an end to the strife have not succeeded.
   The conflict, now nearly 10 years old, is estimated to have
claimed about 70,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
