<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     03-20 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negotiators Try To Solve Remaining Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and opposition negotiators
attacked a series of unresolved problems Monday as talks on
political and economic reform entered a crucial phase.
   Solidarity, the banned independent union movement, reported
progress on amending a draft law on upcoming Parliament elections
that the government last week sent to Parliament for discussion
without consulting the opposition.
   Solidarity national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said the
government agreed to an opposition proposal that each candidate have
a representative on vote-counting commissions. That clause had been
dropped from the government draft sent to Parliament.
   Government negotiators also accepted an opposition demand that
the draft clearly state the law would be valid only for the upcoming
elections in June, Onyszkiewicz said.
   He said other problems remain, including a debate over the number
of signatures needed to nominate a candidate, but ``it is a fact
that the government side is ready to assume a flexible stand on all
those problems.''
   Negotiators hope to wrap up talks at the working groups so that a
plenary session can be held April 3. The talks began Feb. 6.
   Negotiators at a working group on trade union issues have reached
agreement on most issues, said opposition negotiator Henryk Wujec.
   But he said the two sides had failed to agree on the future of
workers who were fired for their participation in Solidarity or
their refusal to leave it when it was banned after the December 1981
martial law crackdown.
   Solidarity wants a statement saying the fired workers have the
right to return to their jobs included in the round-table document
on trade unions. The government says it is prepared to issue an
appeal to managers to allow the workers to return, Wujec said.
   Tens of thousands of workers were dismissed from their jobs after
martial law, Wujec said.
   ``We (Solidarity) decided if this problem is not solved, we
wouldn't be able to sign the final document. I think some solution
must be found,'' he said.
   Although disputes remain, one senior Solidarity supporter
expressed optimism that the talks would end in agreement.
   ``I am not that much of a pessimist to think that the round table
will end with a crash,'' Jerzy Turowicz, editor of the respected
Catholic weekly Tygodnik Powszechny told reporters.
   In another development, the banned union Rural Solidarity
concluded a two-day national congress by expressing reservations
about the upcoming Parliament elections and asking that its property
confiscated under martial law be returned, a spokesman said Monday.
   The meeting Saturday and Sunday in a Warsaw church brought
together more than 400 private farmers from around the country in
the first congress of Rural Solidarity since it was declared illegal
following the imposition of martial law.
   Negotiators at the round-table talks have agreed in principle to
grant legality again to Rural Solidarity. Solidarity and Rural
Solidarity are separate groups but are allied on most issues.
   Rural Solidarity spokesman Jacek Szymaderski said the union does
not plan to boycott parliamentary elections now being negotiated
between the opposition and the government ``despite the fact that
the proposed electoral law is not democratic and the proposed date
is premature.''
   Szymanderski said Rural Solidarity can expect to gain the support
of about a million private farmers when it is legalized.
</TEXT>
