<FIRST>u a AM-SpringBreak     03-20 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spring Break,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daytona Beach Cashes In On Break Crowds Once Headed To Lauderdale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daytona Beach once again is
Florida's big spring break attraction, leaving some merchants in
Fort Lauderdale _ the original draw for college students _ hungry
for business.
   Daytona Beach officials have opened their arms to spring breakers
and expect more than 400,000 to show up at the beach and patronize
the city's hotels, bars and other resort businesses in the next two
weeks, pumping an estimated $100 million into the city's economy.
   And companies as diverse as Playboy Enterprises and AT&amp;T are
working to capitalize on the city that bills itself ``The World's
Most Famous Beach'' with major promotions to attract any loose
dollars.
   Volusia County lifeguards patrolling the shores in the Daytona
Beach area reported record crowds last weekend, and Chief Beach
Ranger John Kirvan estimated there were 150,000 beachgoers on
Saturday alone.
   ``We're busting at the seams,'' he said.
   But 229 miles to the south, the city popularized as the original
mecca for spring break revelers in the movie ``Where the Boys Are''
expects fewer than 20,000 students this year, down from 350,000 as
recently as 1985. Fort Lauderdale merchants believe they have lost
$100 million in annual business with the disappearance of the spring
break crowd.
   ``There's vacation, and then there's party,'' said Mark Aulb, 19,
a student from Ontario, Canada, who baked under the Daytona Beach
sun.
   Aulb, a student coordinator for spring break tours in Florida,
said he organized 20 busloads of spring travelers, with only one
headed to Fort Lauderdale.
   ``Daytona usually opens their arms to everyone,'' Daytona police
Officer N.F. Fiore said. ``It's a free-wheeling town.''
   Fort Lauderdale responded to large crowds several years ago with
a police crackdown on public drinking and driving infractions.
   Fort Lauderdale Mayor Bob Cox has made it clear since 1985 that
he doesn't want hordes of drunken college students in his city,
preferring to boost the South Florida destination as a family resort.
   ``I foresee nothing but a good impression,'' Cox said. ``There's
a couple of bar owners over there that don't agree. But by and
large, people say they've seen a real change in attitude.''
   T-shirt airbrush artist Edward Patterson, who has been coming to
Fort Lauderdale for spring break for the past nine years, said he is
selling his apartment and packing it up after this season. By
Friday, he had designed only one $12 shirt.
   ``Your lovely mayor has really screwed things up,'' he said. ``He
killed a billion-dollar business and didn't replace it with
anything. It's a shame that Fort Lauderdale has become a
seniors-only condo.''
   But in spite of missing college students, Richard Weaver,
president of the Greater Fort Lauderdale Visitors and Convention
Bureau, said 1988 was a record year for tourism.
   ``We're finding replacement markets that are beginning to
coalesce and replace the spring break,'' he said.
   Weaver said Fort Lauderdale pulled in $2.3 billion last year from
3.5 million visitors, a 4.5 percent gain over 1987, and he expects
to break records again in the first quarter of 1989.
   Linda Gill, president of the Broward County Hotel and Motel
Association, said there was a 17 percent occupancy increase in the
city's 30,000 rooms in January 1989, compared with January 1988.
</TEXT>
