<FIRST>u i AM-Plane-Wiring     03-20 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane-Wiring,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Evidence Found of Wiring Fault in Crashed Airliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators found no evidence of fire or
incorrect wiring in the right-hand engine of a British Midland
Airways jetliner that crashed on Jan. 8, killing 47 people, an
interim report said Monday.
   The bulletin issued by the government's Air Accident
Investigation Branch reached no conclusion about the cause of the
crash and said much work remains to be done on the investigation.
   The right-hand engine was shut off and the left-hand engine on
fire when the plane crashed early in the flight from London to
Belfast, Northern Ireland, the report said.
   It confirmed passengers' reports of a fire in the left-hand
engine of the brand-new Boeing 737 and said one fan blade had
fractured.
   In his first public comment since the accident, pilot Kevin Hunt
said, ``Both the first officer (David McLelland) and I agreed that
the right engine was causing us the problem.''
   Hunt, still hospitalized, said in a statement the crew had no
indication of a fire in the left engine until less than a minute
from crashing while trying to land at central England's East
Midlands Airport.
   The report quoted the flight crew as saying cockpit instruments
confirmed their belief that they had resolved their onboard
emergency by shutting off the right engine, and that the left engine
was operating normally.
   The left engine lost power when the airplane was nearly 2{ miles
from the airport and 900 feet above ground, and Hunt told McLelland
to restart the right engine, the report said.
   Seventeen seconds later, a bell rang warning of a fire in the
left engine, and 36 seconds after that the plane crashed without
ever regaining power in the right engine.
   Michael Bishop, chairman of British Midland, said the airline was
satisfied the report ``accurately relates the sequence of events so
far as they're known.'' He said he did not expect a final report to
be available until early next year.
</TEXT>
