<HEAD>Party Chairman Backs Daley Over Jackson-Supported Foe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic mayoral candidate Richard M. Daley
picked up an endorsement Monday from Democratic National Committee
Chairman Ron Brown, who spurned the candidate of his close ally,
Jesse Jackson.
   ``He is the Democratic Party's nominee and I am the national
Democratic Party's chairman,'' Brown said. ``Rich Daley stands for
the future of Chicago, for reaching out to all Democrats, for
building better schools, safer streets, and a stronger economy.
   ``These values are at the heart of the Democratic Party,'' he
said, ``and I heartily endorse them and him.''
   Jackson, who supported Mayor Eugene Sawyer in his losing primary
election bid against Daley, has since shifted support to a
third-party candidate, Alderman Timothy Evans.
   The victor of the April 4 election will serve the final two years
of the four-year term won by the late Mayor Harold Washington in
April 1987. He died in November 1987.
   Daley, the son of former Mayor Richard J. Daley, is white; Evans,
like Jackson, Brown, Sawyer and Washington, is black.
   Jackson was pivotal in helping Brown secure the Democratic
chairmanship, but Brown also worked hard to prove to moderates and
conservatives that he would be independent of Jackson and other
party liberals.
   ``The reverend knows I'm here. I'm not here to pick a fight with
Rev. Jackson or any other Democrats,'' Brown told reporters after
joining Daley for a breakfast with more than 100 black business and
political leaders.
   ``The Rev. Jackson and I are friends. I respect him. I told him
what I planned to do and he didn't try to persuade me otherwise,''
Brown said.
   Evans, the nominee of the Harold Washington Party, attempted to
take some of the glow off the morning meeting, calling it ``the
quickest trip a national party chairman has ever taken. He waved
hello and waved goodbye in a matter of a few hours.
   ``It doesn't sound like a ringing endorsement of Rich Daley to
me. I don't put down Ron Brown,'' he added. ``I know he's between a
rock and a hard place.''
   The most recent poll in the campaign, done by WLS-TV, showed 53
percent of the respondents favoring Daley to 36 percent for Evans, 5
percent for Vrdolyak and 6 percent undecided.
   The results of the telephone poll of 700 registered voters, taken
March 11 through March 15, had an error margin of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
