<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     03-20 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Urges Accelerator Development as Reactor Alternative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Use of a linear accelerator to produce tritium
for nuclear weapons appears to be a promising alternative to current
Energy Department plans to build new production reactors, according
to a scientific report released Monday.
   The report, prepared by scientists at the Los Alamos, N.M., and
Brookhaven, N.Y., national laboratories, urged consideration of an
accelerator as a possible backup to building new reactors at the
Savannah River complex in South Carolina and the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory in Idaho Falls.
   The report said construction of new reactors was the ``lowest
technical risk approach to supplying the critical need for tritium.''
   ``However, we believe it is prudent that DOE pursue other
technologies for tritium production to provide potential
alternatives as a contingency for the future,'' the report said.
``One concept that appears to be particularly promising is the
accelerator production of tritium.''
   Ronald Cochran, acting head of the Energy Department's Office of
New Production Reactors, told a special panel of the House Armed
Services Committee on Monday that the department has yet to see the
report.
   ``We will review the report with great interest,'' Cochran said,
adding that department believes the accelerator proposal involves a
``level of risk too great at this time'' to make it an alternative
to constructing the reactors.
   The nation's current supply of tritium is threatened by the
crumbling conditions at the department's existing production
reactors and weapons plants.
   An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic
particles are whipped at high speed until they crash into a target,
in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision
produces tritium _ a critical element in nuclear weapons that
increases the power of warheads, but decays rapidly.
   The report said that an accelerator could be completed within
eight to nine years on an aggressive schedule compared with at least
10 years to finish a new production reactor.
   An accelerator would cost about $2.3 billion, including $600
million for contingencies, the report said. The estimated cost of
the new Savannah River reactor has been pegged at about $3.2
billion, while the Idaho reactor would cost about $3.6 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
