<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0639 03-20 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth U.S.-PLO Meeting Set; Mubarak, Shamir to Visit in Early April</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, graf 3, ``Diplomatic sources,'' revised for Mubarak
visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next U.S. move in the Middle East will be a
plea to the Palestine Liberation Organization on Wednesday to ease
tensions on the Israeli-held West Bank and in Gaza, U.S. officials
said Monday.
   But prospects for success apparently are dim. PLO officials
already have vowed not to relent in their 15-month uprising while
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told 1,100 visiting foreign
Jews in Jerusalem that he would not deal with the PLO.
   Diplomatic sources said Shamir would come to Washington on April
5 and meet with President Bush on April 6. A U.S. official said,
meanwhile, that President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt would be here April
3 to 5 for similar meetings. King Hussein of Jordan is expected
later in the spring.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told a House appropriations
subcommittee last week he might urge Israel to talk to the PLO if
negotiations could not be held with other Palestinians.
   Baker also unveiled during a visit by Israeli Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens his hopes for reciprocal gestures by the PLO and Israel
on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   The idea would be for Israel to relax its grip on the territories
by reversing its detention of Palestinians while the PLO would try
to moderate the protests that began in December 1987. Since then,
403 Arabs and 17 Israelis have been killed.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, announced on
Monday the sixth U.S. session with the PLO would be held in Tunisia.
He said its purpose was ``instituting a dialogue'' with Yasser
Arafat's organization.
   Without going into detail, Redman said the idea was ``to try to
make some concrete progress in the peace process.''
   Other U.S. officials, who declined to be identified, said
Ambassador Robert Pelletreau's meeting with a PLO representative on
Wednesday would provide an opportunity to seek reciprocal easing of
tensions.
   The U.S. enovy has held five sessions in Carthage since the
Reagan administration ended a 13-year ban on dealing with the PLO
last December.
   PLO officials have complained the meetings were not substantive.
Israel, on the other hand, criticized the United States for
accepting a pledge by Arafat renouncing terrorism.
   Since then, PL0 guerrillas have conducted several raids against
Israelis in southern Lebanon. Baker has concluded the attacks do not
amount to terrorism requiring the talks to be broken off.
   Shamir, in a speech in Jerusalem, said ``we fully recognize that
the status quo is not in our interest, because it means absence of
peace, and peace is our paramount goal.''
   At the same time, Shamir reiterated Israel's reasons for refusing
to talk to the PLO or to withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza, which
were lost by Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   ``The government is united in its opposition to the creation of a
Palestinian Arab state west of the Jordan River. We are opposed to
negotiations with the PLO because it will inevitably lead to a
demand for a state west of the Jordan River,'' he said.
</TEXT>
