<FIRST>u w AM-Flight103-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0691llStrike 03-20
0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Warned of Security Gaps in 1986, Congresswoman Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with fresh reaction, subbing 10th graf, Jeffrey Kriendler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan American World Airways has yet to implement
many steps recommended by a security consultant who in 1986 warned
that the airline was doing little to prevent bombs from being
smuggled onto aircraft, a congresswoman said Monday.
   According to Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., the Israeli security
firm KPI Inc. cautioned the carrier more than two years ago that it
was ``highly vulnerable'' to terrorist attacks.
   ``The fact that no major disaster has occurred to date is merely
providential,'' KPI wrote in September 1986, Mrs. Collins said.
   Last Dec. 21, Pan Am's Flight 103 was blown from the skies over
Scotland by a bomb authorities say was placed in a radio-cassette
player, killing 270 people.
   Mrs. Collins, chairwoman of the Goverment Operations
transportation subcommittee, wrote a letter to the Federal Aviation
Administration on Monday quoting portions of reports the security
company wrote to Pan Am in September and November of 1986.
   Mrs. Collins wrote that ``within days'' of the completion of the
September 1986 paper, a terrorist attack in Karachi, Pakistan,
killed 18 Pan Am passengers and crew members.
   The studies included examinations of security at nine airports,
including Frankfurt, West Germany, and London's Heathrow Airport.
Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt and had landed in London.
   Mrs. Collins' letter said that according to information her panel
has gathered ``from a variety of sources,'' Pan Am has yet to
correct ``many of the gaps'' specified in the 1986 studies.
   ``If they had been, it is possible that those lives could have
been saved,'' she wrote, referring to the Scotland and Pakistan
disasters.
   Jeffrey Kriendler, Pan Am's corporate communications vice
president at the airline's New York headquarters, said KPI is
unfamiliar with Pan Am's current security program. He said the
company would not respond to Collins' criticism until corporate
officials had seen the letter.
   The KPI reports concluded that Pan Am conducted insufficient
checks of baggage, did a poor job of questioning passengers boarding
planes, and was slow to react to warnings of possible terrorist
activity, according to Mrs. Collins.
   ``In conclusion, there are no adequate safeguards under the
presently operating security system that would prevent a passenger
from boarding a plane with explosives on his person or in his
baggage, whether or not he is aware of the fact,'' the security
company wrote.
   The reports said X-ray examinations of luggage should be replaced
with manual searches, which were performed too infrequently.
   ``On the whole, the presently employed search techniques stand a
low chance of discovering concealed explosive charges, if at all,''
the consultant wrote.
   The company wrote that careful scrutiny of lost-and-found baggage
``is very rare,'' making it simple for explosives ``to be sent
ownerless to a supposed destination.''
   At some airports, including London, baggage with a Pan Am tag
simply placed on a conveyer belt would be loaded onto planes, even
without a registered passenger, KPI said.
   The consultant criticized airline employees for being too lax
when searching the baggage of Americans and of citizens of each
airport's country, considering them safer.
   ``It might be pointed out that the question of citizenship is
irrelevant to the terrorist threat,'' KPI said.
   The consultant said it found little effort to carefully
scrutinize suspicious-looking passengers.
   It also complained that in some instances, warnings of terrorist
plans were not relayed to all Pan Am security workers. In one
incident, all Pan Am security employees at Frankfurt and Paris were
not told of a warning received about two Middle Eastern women who
were planning to place explosives aboard a plane. The report did not
say what the consequences were.
</TEXT>
