<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Violence     03-20 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Violence,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Wounded in Occupied Lands, Four Settlers Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded 10 Palestinians
in the occupied territories on Monday, and four Jewish settlers were
arrested on suspicion of burning Arab farm equipment in a vigilante
raid.
   The Gaza Strip was paralyzed for the third day in a general
strike called after bloody riots.
   Over the weekend, seven Palestinians were killed in clashes by
army gunfire, raising to 403 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, protesting Israeli occupation of
lands seized from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
Seventeen Israelis have also died.
   Despite curfews that confined more than 330,000 Gaza residents to
their homes, six Palestinians were wounded in clashes in the seaside
strip.
   The wounded included a 9-year-old boy from Khan Yunis who was
shot in the stomach, Arab hospital officials said. The army
confirmed four wounded in Gaza.
   The army said two soldiers were slightly hurt in Gaza City when
they were attacked by Arab stone-throwers, and one lost his rifle.
   The army ordered residents to return the weapon by Tuesday
morning or face harsh sanctions, army radio reported. Arab reports
said residents were threatened with curfews and water cuts.
   Four Jewish settlers in the Gaza Strip were arrested Monday and
accused of setting fire to 16 Palestinian-owned greenhouses and a
tractor near Deir el-Balah refugee camp Saturday night. The raid was
reportedly in retaliation for a Friday attack on a settler-owned
packing house in Gush Katif.
   The national Itim news agency said an army patrol spotted the
vigilantes and informed police of the raid.
   In the West Bank, four Palestinians were wounded Monday, the army
said. Arab hospital officials said they included a 70-year-old man
from Nablus, shot in the leg.
   The head of the military administration in the West Bank, Brig.
Gen. Shaike Erez, meanwhile held a meeting with Palestinian leaders
in the area.
   ``It was not the first meeting and it won't be the last,'' said
the administration spokesman, Capt. Olivier Rafowicz.
   Arab participants said they told Erez that Israel must negotiate
with the Palestine Liberation Organization to end the uprising.
   ``People said this was a political struggle ... that needed a
negotiated and peaceful solution,'' said Gabi Baramki, acting
president of Bir Zeit University. ``We said the only negotiating
partner is the PLO.''
   Israeli leaders insist they will not negotiate with the PLO,
which they regard as a terrorist organization.
   The radical Islamic fundamentalist Hamas (Zeal) movement released
a leaflet on Monday calling for a general strike in two weeks and an
Arab boycott of Israeli products.
</TEXT>
