<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Crime     03-20 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Crime,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Bloody Underworld War Has Ended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The boss of a gang battling Japan's top underworld
syndicate told police his gang will disband, ending the bloodiest
gangster vendetta in postwar Japanese history, police said Monday.
   Hiroshi Yamamoto, 64, visited a police station near his home
Sunday afternoon to announce his decision to disband the Ichiwa-kai
gang, said police in Kobe, a major port city in western Japan.
   ``He came here, told us the gang was disbanding, and left. It all
took about three minutes,'' the officer at Higashi-Nada precinct
said.
   It is not uncommon for gangsters to make such appearances at
police stations, and many bosses even make written vows to police to
end conflicts or disband gangs, said the officer, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   But he said police are still waiting for a reaction from the
rival Yamaguchi-gumi, by far the nation's largest crime syndicate,
and further skirmishes could erupt.
   The Ichiwa-kai, which had an estimated 6,000 members at its peak,
was created in June 1984 after an internal dispute over
Yamaguchi-gumi's leadership led to a revolt by followers of
boss-candidate Yamamoto.
   In January 1985, two Ichiwa-kai gangsters fatally shot
Yamaguchi-gumi boss Masahisa Takenaka and two other syndicate
leaders.
   The Osaka High Court on Monday upheld a lower court verdict
sentencing the two to life imprisonment and also upheld sentences of
10 years for three Ichiwa-kai lookouts.
   The Ichiwa-kai attack left the Yamaguchi-gumi without a leader,
although acting boss Kazuo Nakanishi and ``young leader'' Yoshinori
Watanabe quickly led the gang into the bloody vendetta, known to the
Japanese as the ``Yama-Ichi War.''
   Police say 315 armed incidents during the four-year battle
between the two gangs left 25 people dead and more than 70 injured.
   A Yamaguchi-gumi source said Yamamoto ``timed the breakup of the
gang to match the sentencing, as a kind of gesture to the
Yamaguchi-gumi.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In Japan, where gun laws are strict and violent crime rates low,
the high-profile gunfights created public outrage and spawned
grassroots movements to rid residential areas of gang headquarters
and offices.
   The strongest of those movements evicted a Yamaguchi-gumi
affiliate from a residential area in Hamamatsu, central Japan, and
the gang today is on the verge of disbanding.
   Headquarters of both the Yamaguchi-gumi and the Ichiwa-kai are in
expensive residential districts in Kobe, but their presence has not
faced serious local opposition.
   When the Ichiwa-kai split from the Yamaguchi-gumi, the
organization had roughly 10,000 members. Police say it now has more
than 20,000.
   Police say about 86,000 gangsters operate in 3,200 gangs in
Japan. Nearly 40 percent belong to the big three nationwide
syndicates: the Yamaguchi-gumi, Sumiyoshi Rengo-kai and Inagawa-kai.
The latter two are based in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
