<HEAD>El Salvador Denies Entry To U.S. Aid Caravan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA HACHADURA, Guatemala (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-vehicle motorcade loaded with
$3 million worth of medicine and other private humanitarian aid for
El Salvador was stalled at the border Monday after Salvadoran
officials denied entry, a group spokeswoman said.
   Cynthia Curtis said the motorcade, organized by ``Building with
the Voiceless in El Salvador,'' a Washington, D.C.-based group, had
been at the border town of La Hachadura since March 13 after
crossing Mexico and Guatemala.
   Ronald Robinson of San Francisco said Salvadoran immigration
officials turned the group back even though its members had valid
entry visas. The officials claimed the country was closed to
foreigners because of Sunday's presidential elections, Robinson said.
   He said the mission was sponsored by the John F. Kennedy
Foundation for Human Rights and carried $3 million in food,
clothing, medicines and school materials donated by a number of
American private companies.
   The group is made up of 40 U.S. citizens, including 12 women,
four Canadians and and one Australian, all volunteer humanitarian
aid workers, Robinson said.
