<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Israel     03-20 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Israel,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egyptians and Israelis Discuss Peace Treaty 10 Years Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIZA, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptians and Israelis, discussing their
countries' relations after a decade of peace, agreed Monday that
solving the Palestinian problem is the only way to foster true
friendship between the former enemies.
   An Israeli Cabinet minister and two Egyptians, all major players
in development of the peace treaty signed March 26, 1979, urged the
Jewish state to recognize the Palestine Liberation Organization as a
first step toward peace across the region.
   They and a group of students, journalists and others met for a
discussion organized by the British Broadcasting Corp. and taped for
broadcast Tuesday, five days before the anniversary of the first and
only treaty between an Arab state and Israel.
   ``Let us make a difference between the two aspects of the
(treaty). The first was peace between Egypt and Israel. The second
was the solution of the Palestinian problem,'' said Butros Ghali,
Egypt's minister of state for foreign affairs.
   ``We have been successful in achieving the first. We have
completely failed in achieving the second one.''
   Ghali was deeply involved in negotiations over the 1978
U.S.-brokered Camp David Accords, which set a framework for the
treaty, and over the treaty itself.
   ``We decided in Camp David on a very important issue, that we are
going to solve the Palestinian problem,'' said Ezer Weizman,
Israel's minister of science and development and another key player
in the process. ``This is the next issue coming up, and I believe
that to continue what we started, we have to do that.''
   Ghali agreed, and added: ``Sooner or later, you will talk to the
PLO.''
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist group, and a succession of
Israeli governments has vowed never to negotiate with it.
   Weizman, a leading member of the left-leaning Labor party,
reiterated his well-known position that Israel should negotiate with
the PLO and predicted that talks could begin within two years.
   Monday's third main participant, Mustafa Khalil, was a senior
aide to the late President Anwar Sadat, whose 1977 trip to Jerusalem
led to peace between the two countries.
   Despite diplomatic relations, Egyptian-Israeli cooperation in
most fields has been very limited. Large numbers of Israeli tourists
come to Egypt, but few Egyptians go to Israel.
   Several Egyptian participants at Monday's session indicated the
extent to which bad blood remains from four Arab-Israeli wars since
1948.
   Khaled Daoud, a student at the American University in Cairo, said
he had come to the session to discuss Egypt's relations with Israel,
but ``I did not know there would be Israelis here before I came. If
I had known, personally, I would not have come.''
</TEXT>
