<HEAD>Soviet Leader Calls For United Europe Without Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev called for a
united Europe without ``offensive arms of any type'' in a videotaped
message shown Monday at an Italian Communist Party congress.
   ``The idea of the `common European house' isn't born at a desk,
but is the result of the history of Europe,'' he said.
   ``We are convinced that this is possible, that Europeans,
together with Americans and Canadians, can revive the idea ... of an
integrated Europe, where everyone maintains his own national origin
and unlimited liberty, where there are no nuclear arms nor offensive
arms of any type.''
   Delegates viewed the videotape on a huge screen at a Rome
convention hall.
   Some U.S. and European officials have expressed concern that the
popular Gorbachev will create pressure for disarmament in NATO
countries.
   Gorbachev said about his restructuring policies in the Soviet
Union that ``our people are for perestroika'' and that ``the
openness will last forever.''
   However, he added, ``We are not yet satisfied with the results we
have obtained.''
   Italian Communists, who make up their country's second-biggest
party and are in the opposition, warmly applauded Gorbachev's
remarks.
