<HEAD>Demonstrators battle police on strike-bound Corsica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASTIA, Corsica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers blocked by strikes at Corsica's
ports and airports referred to themselves Monday as hostages, and
demonstrators battled police in the French island in the
Mediterranean.
   Police threw tear gas grenades to disperse about 350 protesters
throwing stones and burning tires in front of this northern city's
administrative offices. Officials said two policemen were injured.
   A group of travelers unable to leave Corsica established a
``committee of hostages'' and urged French officials to provide
means of evacuation ``to honor the elementary and constitutional
right of all citizens to freedom of movement.''
   The island's ports and airports have been closed since the middle
of last week in an escalation of the strike by public employees that
started five weeks ago.
   French Premier Michel Rocard met in Paris with six Corsican
legislators and said the government would organize discussions on
reform programs with political, social and economic leaders of
Corsica.
   He said success would depend a ``spirit of dialogue and
responsibility.''
   Strikers are demanding what they call an insularity bonus to
compensate for high prices. Officials in Paris have not disputed the
strikers' claim that prices of basic goods are higher in Corsica
than in mainland France.
