<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-20 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blizzard in Kansas; Storms Move Into Southwest, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wintry weather lingered throughout much of the country Monday on
the first day of spring, with a blizzard hitting parts of Kansas and
stormy weather moving into much of the Southwest and Northeast.
   Snow and high winds in western Kansas reduced visibility to near
zero at times, closing Interstate 70 west of Oakley. A high wind
warning was issued for west central and southwestern Kansas.
   A high wind warning also was posted for northwestern Texas, and a
winter storm warning for the south Texas plains. A snow advisory was
issued for the Permian Basin of Texas and for southeastern Colorado
and the Oklahoma panhandle.
   A winter storm watch also was posted for much of New Mexico.
   Further to the east, strong thunderstorms raked southeast Texas
and western Louisiana, and rain extended from the central plains
through the Ohio Valley and the Tennessee Valley to the Appalachians.
   Although spring officially began at 10:28 a.m. EST Monday, a
winter-like storm was brewing in the Northeast.
   Snow in the lower Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio Valley
was expected to spread northeastward during the night. A winter
weather advisory was posted for the mountains and southwestern
sections of Pennsylvania, with winter storm watches posted for a
wide area ranging from Maine through New Hampshire, Vermont and
upstate New York.
   A snow advisory was posted for northern Indiana.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for rain from
the Rio Grande Valley of Texas through the Tennessee Valley and the
central Gulf Coast states to the mid-Atlantic coast, with
thunderstorms most likely from the central Gulf Coast to the
Carolinas. Snow was expected from the upper Ohio Valley to northern
New England, with rainshowers from the northern and central Pacific
Coast to northwest Montana. Fair to partly sunny skies were forecast
for the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to remain below 50 from the high
plains region to the northern half of the Atlantic coast; in the 20s
and lower 30s from the Dakotas through the Great Lakes region to
northern New England; in the 70s and 80s in southern Arizona,
southern and central California and from the central and eastern
Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic coast.
</TEXT>
