<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-NewYear     03-20 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-New Year,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Delivers New Year Message</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's
88-year-old patriarch, said in a New Year message Monday that
Moslems must overcome carnal desires, but admitted being unable to
do so himself.
   Tehran television quoted him as saying: ``I hope the Iranian
nation and other Moslems throughout the world will transform
themselves so they can work for the sake of God, and not for their
own victory or their carnal desires.
   ``In his lifetime, man is afflicted with carnal desires. He needs
self-discipline, and I, as the speaker of these words, have not
succeeded in this task.''
   The Persian New Year begins March 21.
   President Ali Khamenei delivered a message stressing postwar
reconstruction and development of oil and related industries. A
U.N.-sponsored truce was reached with Iraq last August after eight
years of war.
   In the past year, he said, ``undoubtedly the most important event
was the acceptance of the cease-fire ... by Ayatollah Khomeini and
its support by the people.''
   Chief Justice Musavi Ardebili canceled New Year vacations for
judges and magistrates because of a government anti-narcotics
campaign, Tehran radio reported.
   It quoted him as saying the vacations had been canceled so judges
could continue ``stamping out malicious elements and drug
smugglers.''
   A crackdown on drugs in Iran began when a new law took effect
Jan. 21, imposing the death sentence for possession of even small
quantities. According to official figures, more than 200 offenders
have been convicted in Islamic courts and executed.
   The radio also said a budget of 9.7 trillion rials ($140 billion)
was passed by the parliament Monday and approved by the Guardian
Council, which makes sure legislation conforms with Islamic law and
the constitution.
   It said the council made amendments and deleted some items, but
it did not describe the changes.
   A report by the official Islamic Republic News Agency said the
budget included $2.5 billion in loans from abroad for repairing war
damage to the infrastructure. In the past, even during the war, Iran
avoided incurring foreign debt.
</TEXT>
