<SECOND>AM-People-Chung-Williams,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chung Joins CBS, Williams Goes to NBC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC correspondent Connie Chung is jumping to CBS
and Cable News Network anchor Mary Alice Williams is joining NBC in
the latest round of big-name network-hopping.
   Chung will be Sunday anchor of the ``CBS Evening News'' and
in-studio anchor for a revamped version of CBS' struggling weekly
prime-time newsmagazine ``West 57th.''
   A statement issued by NBC News President Michael Gartner said,
``We are sorry to see Connie leave the NBC news team. We made what
we believed was a fair and attractive offer to Connie. I regret that
she was unable to accept our offer, but I wish her well in her new
role at CBS.''
   Chung was a Washington correspondent with CBS from 1971-76 and
anchor at KNXT-TV, now KCBS-TV, the CBS-owned station in Los Angeles
until 1983.
   Before joining CNN at its inception in 1979, Williams was an
anchor and reporter for WNBC-TV, the NBC-owned station in New York.
   Williams will be a co-anchor and reporter on a new prime-time NBC
show, ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow,'' the brainchild of NBC
Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff.
   Last month, CBS lost Diane Sawyer to ABC, where she will anchor a
new prime-time news show with Sam Donaldson. Late last year, NBC
News lost one of its few recognizable stars, Chris Wallace, also to
ABC for the prime-time show.
   Chung, another of NBC's best-known stars, had been considered the
likely anchor for the new NBC show, which will probably premiere as
a monthly broadcast this summer, then join the schedule weekly early
next year.
