<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Art     03-20 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Art,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sculpture Made from Older Missile, Not SS-20</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Monday that a
Soviet artist is using older SS-4 missiles, not scrapped SS-20
missiles, to make a pair of sculptures that will be displayed in New
York.
   A report that appeared widely in the Soviet press last week said
sculptor Zurab Tsereteli of the southern republic of Georgia was
using pieces of the SS-20 missiles in sculptures to be placed near
the United Nations and by Riverside Church in New York.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfiliev said the reports were
mistaken. ``The SS-20s are to be eliminated by explosion,
demolition, and after that process they don't exist anymore,'' he
told a regular news briefing.
   SS-4s, older medium-range missiles, are being cut up, and
Tsereteli received pieces of several of them, Perfiliev said.
   The missiles are being destroyed under a U.S.-Soviet agreement to
eliminate both sides' medium- and shorter-range nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
