<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-USMarines     03-20 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-US Marines,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two US Officers Sent Home After Mock Execution in War Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. Marine officers were sent home
because of a mock execution in which blanks were fired with machine
guns at Norwegian ``prisoners'' during a NATO exercise, an army
spokesman said Monday.
   ``It was meant as a joke, but both the American and the Norwegian
military leadership considered it to be a very bad joke,'' said Gen.
Torkel Hovland, commander of a Norwegian division that participated
in the ``Cold Winter'' maneuvers.
   American, British, Dutch and Norwegian soldiers took part in the
Arctic exercises held March 3-15.
   Hovland confirmed a report in the newspaper Fremover, published
at Harstad in northern Norway, describing what happened March 12
after the Norwegians were captured.
   ``The Norwegians were ordered executed, lined up and `shot'
one-by-one with machine-gun blanks,'' it said. ``When one Norwegian
officer among the prisoners refused to leave his car, an American
soldier put his gun inside the car's open window and fired blanks.''
   It said no one was injured and two American officers, a captain
and a lieutenant, were held responsible. Their identities were not
revealed.
   Maj. Yngve Jessen, a spokesman for the maneuvers, told the
Norwegian news agency NTB the incident violated ``all regulations of
the Hague and the Geneva conventions about treatment of prisoners.
We can't exclude that the American captain involved will be reduced
in rank or even be dismissed from service.''
</TEXT>
