<FIRST>u a AM-Gotti-Threat     03-20 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gotti-Threat,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caller: `There Is A Gift for John Gotti'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It might have been a warning or a prank, but the
``gift'' someone left for reputed mobster John Gotti in front of his
Little Italy hangout on Monday was not a workable bomb, police said.
   When bomb squad officers opened a plastic box they found on the
step of the Ravenite Social Club, they at first described what they
found inside as an explosive powder.
   But further analysis disclosed the powder to be two pounds of
salt and an ounce of gunpowder. Given such a small amount of powder,
plus faulty batteries and wiring, ``it appears the device would not
have detonated,'' Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo told
reporters. If it had, he added, it probably couldn't have done much
damage.
   Asked to explain the incident, he said: ``We could assume it's
either a message to Gotti that perhaps he is vulnerable or that his
club is vulnerable. It could have been a prank. It could have been a
lot of things.''
   A man telephoned the police department's organized crime bureau
shortly after 5 a.m. and said, ``There is a gift for John Gotti at
the social club.'' He did not give his name, but identified the club
as the Ravenite in lower Manhattan.
   Police Inspector Richard Mayronne said the device included a
10-inch aluminum bottle packed with powder. The bottle was partially
contained in a 4-by-6 inch plastic box which contained batteries
wired to a circuit board with an electric timer. The bottle, which
contained the powder and a coil, protruded from inside the box.
   The non-bomb was the latest slap at Gotti, reputed boss of the
Gambino crime family, who is besieged by law enforcers and mob
rivals.
   In January a battalion of police officers, some of them posing as
street vendors, arrested Gotti on the street near the Ravenite. They
threw him against a wall, patted him down and read him his rights.
Gotti, apparently stunned to be treated like a common criminal,
asked, ``What's wrong with you guys?''
   He was charged with ordering the shooting of a union official who
had himself ordered the trashing of a restaurant owned by a Gambino
family member.
   Meanwhile, prosecutors in a Mafia trial in Newark say members of
the Genovese crime family, headed by Vincent ``Chin'' Gigante,
plotted to kill Gotti to stop him from infringing on their rackets.
FBI agents, in fact, warned Gotti in 1987 that he was the subject of
such a murder plot. Gigante and Gotti are virtually the only major
New York Mafia figures to have avoided long prison sentences.
   The Ravenite, which has been the subject of intense surveillance
by investigators, is a simple storefront that sits inconspicuously
on a street of colorful, lively Italian restaurants. The club has
long been frequented by members of the Gambino crime family, notably
Aniello Dellacroce, a professional murderer who became one of the
family's two most powerful leaders.
   Dellacroce was Gotti's patron, and after the older man died in
1985 Gotti allegedly ordered the murder of Gambino boss Paul
Castellano and seized control of the family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0195 </DOCNO>
