<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Gingrich     03-20 0965</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich,2nd ld-writethru, a0758,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 26th graf to CORRECT that network did not report land deal
was part of investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, striving to prevent damage
to his race for the No. 2 leadership post among House Republicans,
promised Monday to provide full accounting of his unusual book
promotion deal.
   ``We'll check with our attorney and get it out into the open,''
said the Georgia congressman, trying to distinguish his book deal
from the one that led to ethics charges brought by Gingrich against
House Speaker Jim Wright.
   ``We were not trying to make a quick buck or arrange any
sweetheart deal,'' he said at a news conference. Although the
limited partnership formed for promotion was unusual in publishing,
it was ``much like the arrangement used for producing and promoting
a Broadway play,'' he said.
   Wright, D-Texas, clearly reveled in the attention being paid to
his nemesis.
   ``People who live in glass houses shouldn't throw stones,'' he
said.
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said Gingrich should
expect to face an inquiry himself.
   ``He should anticipate somebody filing charges... and he'll have
to live by the same standard he has set for others,'' Coelho said.
   Gingrich made ``a plea to you and the press and the American
public to listen and understand the truth,'' he said, but others
``asked for the same thing and Newt wasn't always interested,''
Coelho said.
   Three House Democrats _ Reps. Barney Frank of Massachusetts,
Martin Sabo of Minnesota and Lawrence Smith of Florida _ sent a
letter to Gingrich late Monday asking that he answer a list of
questions they said are raised by the promotion deal.
   The letter says the questions involve House rules, financial
disclosure requirements, the Federal Election Campaign Act and the
Internal Revenue Service code.
   An article in Monday's Washington Post said 21 investors put up
$5,000 apiece to promote Gingrich's 1984 book, ``Window of
Opportunity.'' In exchange, the investors were to receive 45 percent
of the profits, but there weren't any.
   They did, however, gain tax benefits from the arrangement, the
article said.
   Gingrich's wife, Marianne, who co-authored the book, received
``less than $10,000'' from the $105,000 for her work in arranging
the deal and coordinating the promotional efforts. Her tax benefit
amounted to $26, Gingrich said.
   She said the House ethics committee was consulted before the
partnership contracts were signed, and their earnings were fully
disclosed as House rules require.
   ``I did a lot of work,'' she told reporters, adding that the book
was still for sale and reciting a toll-free number if anybody wanted
to buy.
   Contrasting his volume with the one Wright has privately
published and sold, Gingrich said his book was ``a real book, 272
pages long, with real ideas, not a collection of House floor
speeches and memories,'' and it was sold in regular bookstores.
   Gingrich said he held the news conference as soon as he could
because he wanted to quickly dispel any notion of wrongdoing in the
midst of his campaign for Minority Whip.
   Gingrich is one of two announced candidates for the post, which
became vacant when Dick Cheney was confirmed last week as Secretary
of Defense. Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., is also campaigning for the
position.
   Gingrich said Monday he believes he has a majority of the 174
House Republicans committed to him, and that the article about his
book deal would not hurt, except that it was a distraction for a few
hours.
   Meantime, the House ethics committee convened for its first full
day of deliberations in Wright's case, following three weeks of
presentations and counter-arguments from its special counsel and
Wright's attorney.
   Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said the deliberations would go
through Wednesday, but added he could not predict whether final
decisions on the charges against Wright would be completed by then.
If not, the panel would reconvene early next month following the
Easter recess, he said.
   Rep. John T. Myers of Indiana, the senior Republican on the
panel, said he expects the panel will act to release the full report
of its independent counsel, Richard Phelan, but added that decision
had not yet been made.
   Both men said they expected that whatever the final outcome, it
would be bipartisan and not be the result of a polarized committee.
The 12-member panel, unique in the House, is evenly divided between
Democrats and Republicans.
   Both also said they did not expect the GOP leadership race to
impact their deliberations, and Myers said he did not believe
Gingrich's book promotion deal would be relevant.
   ``They're two separate issues,'' he said. ``That is not an issue
before the ethics committee and hopefully it will not be.'' Later,
asked about the impact of the book deal on Gingrich's chances, Myers
added: ``I don't see how they can help any. Mr. Gingrich, it poses,
I think, some problems for him.''
   ABC-TV reported Monday night that Wright was a silent partner
with a major savings and loan operator in a Florida land development
deal at the same time Wright was involved in legislation affecting
the savings and loan industry.
   The deal involved a 20-acre parcel of land near Orlando, Fla.,
according to ABC. The land was subdivided into housing lots and
Wright tripled his money in three years, making a $90,000 profit,
ABC said. One of the other buyers was RIchard Swann, an Orlando
lawyer who was chairman of the city's largest savings and loan, the
network said.
   Mark Johnson, a spokesman for Wright, ``the ABC story was utterly
false. There was not even the slightest potential for a conflict of
interest as ABC suggested. The whole underlying premise of that
story is that there some connection to the S&amp;L issue, and it's just
utterly and totally false.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
