<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DenverSymphony     03-20 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denver Symphony,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Symphony Cancels Rest of Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Denver Symphony Orchestra's 1989 spring season
will end early with Saturday's concert because of a nearly $1
million shortfall, orchestra officials announced Monday.
   Symphony officials said they were canceling eight concerts
remaining in the 1989 spring season, but said they hoped to
reorganize the orchestra in time for the 1989-1990 season. They
planned to have a proposal in hand by Aug. 1.
   ``We looked at every possible alternative before we were forced
to make this decision,'' John Low, chairman of the symphony board,
said at a news conference.
   ``Obviously, we cannot continue to run without cash in the bank,
and at this point in time we can't run until June,'' he said.
``We'll be back next year. ... We may have a reduced budget and a
smaller season, but we're going to offer the same quality
performances the Denver community demands and deserves.''
   Last fall, a last-ditch community fund-raising campaign saved the
symphony from a possible bankruptcy. But since then symphony
officials have said they faced a $985,000 shortfall.
   People holding tickets for canceled concerts may receive credit
for next season's concerts, but no cash refunds will be paid,
officials said.
   The DSO said in a statement that conductor Philippe Entremont,
who was in Paris, would not be at the last concerts scheduled
Thursday, Friday and Saturday.
   Michelle Patrick, a DSO spokeswoman, said it was Entremont's
decision not to perform this weekend. She said she did not know if
he would return to the symphony.
</TEXT>
