<FIRST>r w AM-Parkin-DODInvestigation     03-20 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parkin-DOD Investigation,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parkin Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key figure in the investigation of a Defense
Department purchasing scandal was hospitalized Monday, according to
his attorney, Gerard F. Treanor Jr.
   Treanor said he had been authorized by William Parkin, a private
consultant, and his family to say Parkin was in Alexandria, Va.,
Hospital but could give no further details.
   However, NBC-TV reported that Parkin, who had been considering a
plea of guilty, had attempted suicide by taking an overdose of pills.
   A hosspital nursing supervisor, who declined to give her name,
said Parkin ``was doing fine.''
   In the trial, scheduled to start March 27 in U.S. District Court
in Alexandria, prosecutors will attempt to prove that Teledyne
Electronics of Newbury Park, Calif., and three of its employees paid
Parkin to obtain details about a $100 million Navy radar contract.
   Parkin is accused of paying another consultant, Fred Lackner of
Woodland Hills, Calif., who, in turn, gave money to Stuart Berlin, a
one-time Navy procurement specialist, prosecutors say.
   All the defendants have pleaded innocent to the charges, which
are contained in an indictment unsealed on Jan. 6.
   Parkin worked with a number of defense contractors including
Unisys, Hazeltine, Northrup and Teledyne Electronics.
