<FIRST>r a AM-Newspage-Rose     03-20 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage-Rose,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball Investigating Charges Against Pete Rose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLANT CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball great Pete Rose is under
investigation for serious allegations, baseball Commissioner Peter
Ueberroth said Monday, and one source said the Cincinnati Reds
manager faces possible suspension for gambling.
   The commissioner's office, in an unusual and carefully worded
statement, did not say what the allegations were. Rose admits to a
fondness for betting on horse and dog races, but has never been
accused of betting on baseball.
   The usually effusive Rose declined comment on the investigation.
``If something happens, when it happens, I'll talk about it then,''
he said.
   The commissioner's statement was issued jointly with A. Bartlett
Giamatti, the National League president who has been selected to
replace Ueberroth.
   ``The office of the commissioner, which was founded to preserve
the integrity of the game, has for several months been conducting a
full inquiry into serious allegations involving Mr. Pete Rose,'' the
statement said.
   ``When the commissioner's office has completed its inquiry, the
commissioner will consider the information presented and take
whatever action is warranted by the facts consistent with the rules
and procedures of major league baseball,'' it continued.
   Rose flew to New York from spring training on Feb. 20 to meet
with Ueberroth, Giamatti and several lawyers. At the time, the
commissioner's office said the matter was private, but several
published reports said gambling was discussed.
   Not until Monday did baseball acknowledge it was investigating
Rose. And one baseball source, who asked not to be identified, said
that the statement ``was a prelude to what's going to happen in the
next couple of days.'' He said Rose might be suspended for gambling
activities.
   John M. Dowd, a trial lawyer with the Washington firm of Heron,
Burchette, Ruckert &amp; Rothwell, is leading the investigation as
special counsel to the commissioner.
   The 47-year-old Dowd headed a Justice Department organized crime
task force from 1972 to 1978 and led investigations of the FBI and
of former Pennsylvania Rep. Dan Flood. Dowd said Monday that he had
been investigating Rose for about a month and did not know how much
longer the inquiry would last.
   He would not discuss the nature of the investigation.
   Baseball personnel are prohibited from betting on baseball games,
but they are allowed to make legal bets at tracks, a common pasttime
for baseball players and managers. Despite that, baseball personnel
have been suspended for associating with gamblers.
   On one occasion last year, Rose said: ``I'm not supposed to
gamble. They talked to me about that.''
   Rose was suspended for 30 days last year for a scuffle with
umpire Dave Pallone. It was the longest suspension given a manager
in 41 years.
   Rose, who has been Cincinnati's manager since August 1986, holds
what is considered one of baseball's most unassailable records _ the
most hits in a career, 4,256. He also has played in more games than
any other player _ 3,562.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 3rdLd-Writethru a0768 03-20 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0768,0898</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Winger Cristiani Victorious in Salvador Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to CORRECT name of U.S. ambassador and move
up his comment. Pick up 16th pvs, `Cristiani, a...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfredo Cristiani, who tried to
erase memories of his right-wing party's links to death squads that
killed thousands of Salvadorans, celebrated his presidential victory
Monday over the U.S.-backed government.
   Fidel Chavez Mena, candidate of the incumbent Christian
Democrats, conceded defeat and told a news conference, ``I have
called him (Cristiani) personally to congratulate him and express my
desire that God illuminate him in governing the country.''
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker said the election result was not a
defeat for U.S. policy. In Washington, the State Department said it
was prepared to support the new Salvadoran government but only if it
protects democracy and human rights.
   Cristiani, of the Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, will
take over from President Jose Napoleon Duarte on June 1. Duarte, one
of Washington's staunchest allies, had been unable to end a
9-year-old civil war with leftist rebels that has taken an estimated
70,000 lives.
   Duarte, barred by the constitution from seeking re-election, has
said his proudest moment will come when he hands over power to an
elected successor. Duarte suffers from terminal liver cancer.
   Cristiani immediately urged all political parties to ``put down
their political banners and unite to ensure progress.'' He told a
Monday news conference that his party ``doesn't want a sectarian
government.''
   He also thanked Chavez Mena for accepting ``in a very democratic
manner the results of the elections.''
   The Central Elections Council said Arena had 53.81 percent of the
576,339 votes counted from Sunday's election, compared to 36.59
percent for the centrist Christian Democrats. Trailing were the
conservative National Conciliation Party with 4.21 percent and the
leftist Democratic Convergence at 3.2 percent. Other votes were
divided among three smaller parties.
   ``Arena has won and I congratulate Alfredo Cristiani publicly,''
said Ricardo Perdomo, the Christian Democratic chairman of the
council. He said final official results would not be announced until
a recount is concluded Thursday.
   Agriculture Minister Antonio Morales Erlich estimated voter
turnout at between 850,000 and 900,000 _ one of the lowest in
Salvadoran history and less than half of those eligible. Walker, the
U.S. ambassador, had said a turnout of 60 percent or better would
represent a defeat for the guerrilla strategy.
   Chavez Mena conceded that Cristiani would win more than 50
percent of the vote, thus enabling him to evade a runoff election
that would have been held next month between the top two contendes.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said: ``Our
relationship with that new government will depend on its adherence
to democracy and respect for human rights, the twin pillars of our
approach to El Salvador,'' said department spokesman Charles Redman.
   Redman praised the Salvadoran people for braving ``violence and
terror'' by leftist guerrillas who, he said, tried harder to disrupt
Sunday's balloting than any other election here in seven years.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the elections
``represent a strong desire by the people of El Salvador for the
ability to participate in the election process.'' But he said the
United States was ``concerned about the level of guerrilla attacks
and human rights abuses'' during the balloting.
   The United States has supported El Salvador with $3.5 billion in
aid this decade, and some congressmen have said the results leave
much to be desired.
   Cristiani, a 41-year-old coffee-grower and businessman, said late
Sunday he ``would be the president of all 5 million Salvadorans. We
are going to unify this people in order to pull ourselves out of
this profound crisis.''
   Arena was linked in the early 1980s to rightist death squads
blamed for the murders of tens of thousands of suspected leftists.
Cristiani contends the party has changed significantly and his
candidacy was evidence of that.
   But fanatical rightists remain prominent in the party, including
party founder Roberto d'Aubuisson, who was once called a
``pathological killer'' by a U.S. ambassador. D'Aubuisson has
repeatedly denied links to death squads.
   D'Aubuisson, a former army major who was cashiered in 1980 for
allegedly plotting a coup, is an Arena legislator. Although he holds
no formal party post, he was the party's top drawing card at
election rallies, where he was introduced as ``maximum leader.''
   The election marked the first time Salvadoran voters had a chance
to replace an incumbent civilian government with a distinctly
different government.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front tried
to thwart the voting with a transport ban across the
Massachusetts-sized country and attacks on military positions in 12
of the country's 14 provinces.
   The insurgents lifted the ban Monday and said that the high
absentee rate proved their contention that El Salvador's problems
could not be solved without their participation.
   At least 29 guerrillas and soldiers were killed in Sunday's
fighting, as well as two civilians, according to Col. Emilio Ponce,
chief of the joint chiefs of staff. Ponce told The Associated Press
the attacks constituted ``a nationwide offensive.''
   Three journalists _ two Salvadorans and a Dutchman _ also were
killed and a fourth seriously wounded by security forces over
election weekend.
</TEXT>
