<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru a0649 03-20 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transport Department Issues Further Warning on Bomb Devices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADD 3 grafs at end, UPDATING with FAA comments on informing
carriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transport Department told airlines and airports
Monday there is a ``high and continuing risk'' of more devices like
the bomb in a radio-cassette player that destroyed Pan Am Flight
103, killing 270 people.
   The department said it sent a telex as a reminder of its previous
warnings, which have been the subject of controversy, and to suggest
new safety measures. Transport officials would not elaborate on the
statement.
   Pressure grew for the government to explain whether the Flight
103 disaster on Dec. 21 could have been averted with better
dissemination of warnings and information about bombing equipment
found before the explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Opposition politicians have demanded Transport Secretary Paul
Channon resign because of how he handled events before the bombing,
which killed all 259 people on the Boeing 747 and 11 on the ground.
   The Evening Standard newspaper said police believe the bomb
contained only one or two pounds of explosives, but its location
near a weakened seam in the baggage hold increased its effect.
   Inspector Tom McCullough of the Lockerbie police, who are
conducting the investigation, refused comment beyond saying the
report was ``most likely speculation by the press.''
   A source the Evening Standard did not identify was quoted as
saying: ``If the bomb had been almost anywhere else it might have
killed half a dozen people or maybe even just shredded some bags.''
   In Washington, a member of Congress said Pan Am still is not
following many anti-terrorism measures an Israeli security firm
suggested to it more than two years ago.
   Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., said in a letter to the Federal
Aviation Administration the security consultant concluded the
airline was not careful enough in checking baggage, did a poor job
of questioning passengers boarding planes and was slow in reacting
to warnings of possible terrorist activity.
   She quoted from reports KPI Inc. gave Pan Am in 1986 after
reviewing Pan Am security at nine airports, including Frankfurt and
London's Heathrow Airport. Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt and
changed planes at Heathrow.
   One of the KPI reports said: ``Pan Am is highly vulnerable to
most forms of terrorist attack. The fact that no major disaster has
occurred to date is merely providential.''
   Opposition lawmakers in London continued claiming Monday that the
public was not given a full explanation of events before the
bombing. Channon made no comment.
   He canceled a speech to an airline magazine conference and did
not address Parliament after the second rejection of an opposition
Labor Party request to force him to speak.
   Labor and other opposition leaders want Channon to explain why a
warning that might have alerted Pan Am to the type of bomb used was
not sent until after the disaster.
   It was the second of two issued after the discovery Oct. 26 by
West Germany of explosives hidden in a radio-cassette player in the
possession of suspect Palestinians.
   Monday's statement by the Transport Department said: ``Since the
discovery in Germany in October last year of an explosive device
hidden in a radio, we have considered it possible that there might
be other similar devices in existence in Germany or elsewhere.
   ``In view of the high and continuing risk for electronic devices,
the department has today by telex issued a further reminder to
airports and airlines drawing attention to the guidance issued
earlier and suggesting some further steps that should be taken.''
   The first warnings were issued in November but Pan Am says it did
not receive the second, more detailed, bulletin until Jan. 17.
   Channon's department said the fact that U.S. airlines were not
told until January, a delay it said occurred because color
photographs were being prepared, was not important because the FAA
and West Germany provided similar information a month earlier.
   Channon also has been criticized for failing to tell Parliament
of either warning until last week and failing to order tighter
airport security.
   Roland Bachmeier of the West German Interior Ministry said Monday
that British experts attended a briefing Nov. 15 on the
radio-cassette player found in West Germany and ``they were in
possession of all the information.''
   FAA spokesman John Leyden said in Washington on Monday that his
agency did not send a photograph of the explosive device to airlines.
   He said the FAA's Nov. 18 security alert to carriers contained
technical details of the bomb and how it would work. He said it
wasn't until later that the West Germans developed material on the
bomb that included photographs.
   U.S. carriers serving London received the photograph from British
authorities, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
