<FIRST>r a AM-OffshoreFires     03-20 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Offshore Fires,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Calls Off Search for Seven Missnig in Oil Rig Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ships searched the Gulf of Mexico around two
badly burned oil platforms Monday but found no trace of seven men
missing after explosions and fires swept through the platforms
Sunday night.
   Thirty-five men escaped the blazing platforms, according to the
Coast Guard. Ten of those were injured, two critically.
   The side-by-side oil production platforms, which were connected
by catwalks, erupted in flames about 7:30 p.m. Sunday. The Coast
Guard said men were working on natural gas lines at the time of the
fires, but a spokesman for owner Atlantic Richfield Co. said the
cause was unknown Monday.
   ``There was work going on,'' said company spokesman Earl Sims,
``but we don't know if it was the cause.''
   Sims had no assessment of loss and said he did not know how
severely the two platforms were damaged.
   ARCO identified five of its employees who were among the seven
missing. It said the other two were employees of contractors working
aboard the rigs.
   The missing ARCO workers were Richard Freeman Jr. of Meadville,
Miss.; James R. Gibbs of Elba, Ala.; Doyle Henson Jr. of DeRidder,
La.; Barry Pritchard of Lafayette, La., and J.B. Suharto, an
Indonesian on assignment with ARCO in Lafayette. The two contractors
were not identified.
   Both the Coast Guard and ARCO suspended their search after
sundown Monday. Quartermaster 1st Class Fred Kephart said the Coast
Guard was deciding whether to resume searching Tuesday morning.
   Sims said ARCO and other rig operators in the area would continue
searching Tuesday, but ``at a reduced level,'' with just two boats
at their disposal.
   Sims said searchers boarded one of the platforms during the day,
but found no survivors or bodies.
   The other platform, the one where the fire started, was much more
badly damaged. ``There is some question about the integrity of the
structure and whether we can get on it in a safe manner,'' said
Sims. ``We'll be looking at that tomorrow.''
   The two platforms, just off the southeast tip of Louisiana, were
about 50 to 100 feet apart, with living quarters on one.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Bob Morehead said 42 people were
believed to be aboard the ARCO platforms when the fires broke out.
Helicopters and boats rescued the survivors, some of whom jumped
directly into the water while others fled the platforms in covered,
capsule-like life boats.
   Morehead said an oil slick two miles long and about 100 yards
wide extended from the structures.
   The 10 injured men were taken to West Jefferson Hospital in
Marrero, a New Orleans suburb, said spokeswoman Lynne Pourciau.
Eight were suffering from burns and two others from multiple
injuries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
