<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Journalists 1stLd-Writethru   03-20 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Journalists, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0759,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Mourn Slain Comrades</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUBS 19th graf, `U.S. Ambassador...' to restore first name.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local and international
journalists Monday mourned three colleagues killed while covering
the election and demanded that government and rebel forces commit
themselves to respect reporters' lives.
   More than 1,000 journalists were in El Salvador for Sunday's
presidential election, and many joined in funeral processions Monday
for the two Salvadorans slain by security forces. A Dutch cameraman
was killed when army troops attacked a guerrilla-held village.
   The armed forces insisted the weekend slayings were isolated
incidents but announced an army corporal had been arrested in one of
the killings.
   Col. Emilio Ponce, head of the joint chiefs of staff, said the
killings did not demonstrate a policy to hinder journalists.
   Air force troopers killed Roberto Navas, 30, and seriously
wounded Luis Galdamez, 34, near a roadblock on the outskirts of San
Salvador Saturday night. Both were photographers for the Reuter news
agency.
   The armed forces said the two were on Navas' motorcycle and
stopped at one roadblock but drove through another checkpoint.
Galdamez said they stopped at a checkpoint and identified themselves
and then were shot after proceeding.
   Mauricio Pineda, a 26-year-old soundman for a local television
station, was killed Sunday morning by a soldier in the eastern
province of San Miguel. The army acknowledged Pineda was shot
without provocation and said a corporal implicated in the killing
was under arrest and would be turned over to civilian authorities
for trial.
   Cornel Lagrouw, 30, a camerman for the Dutch television network
IKON, was fatally wounded during a gunfight Sunday between rebels
and troops in San Francisco Javier, a town 70 miles east of San
Salvador.
   Journalists with Lagrouw said he was standing next to some
guerrillas when he was struck in the chest by a bullet fired from an
army position.
   The local Association of Correspondents did not blame the army
for the shooting but condemned the crew of an air force helicopter
that jounalists said fired at the car they were using to take the
dying Lagrouw to a hospital.
   The journalists said the car was flying white flags and was
identified as a news vehicle with large letters ``TV'' taped on the
windshield, roof and sides.
   About 300 journalists and other friends and relatives were in the
procession Monday morning as Navas' body was taken to a San Salvador
cemetery.
   Many reporters also attended the afternoon ceremony for Pineda.
   Lagrouw was a resident of Nicaragua, and Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega sent condolences Monday to the Nicaraguan Association
of Foreign Correspondents. Lagrow was a member of the association.
   The statement by the Salvadoran Association of Correspondents
said:
   ``Our efforts in zones of conflict to keep the people informed
demands respect and guarantees. We demand that the parties to the
conflict take the necessary measures so that such respect and
guarantees are an everyday reality.''
   It was directed to the armed forces and the rebels Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front.
   Ponce spoke to leaders of the Association of Correspondents
Sunday night and told them, ``Though they (the shootings) happened
in a brief lapse, this kind of incident is isolated. It does not
represent any policy or desire on the part of the armed forces to
intimidate journalists or keep them from doing their job.''
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker said Monday of the shootings:
``Obviously it is a tragedy.
   ``Now it is for the government to look into it and if there is
culpability, then punish those guilty. But as of now I don't know
the facts. I don't think anyone does.''
</TEXT>
