<DOCNO> AP890320-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     03-20 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Heidi Chronicles' Moves to Broadway; A Lackluster `Macbeth'
Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heidi Holland has made the journey from
off-Broadway to Broadway with her wit and wisdom intact. In fact,
she has gotten better, although she'd be the first to deny it.
   Heidi is the insecure heroine of ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' Wendy
Wasserstein's funny feminist travelogue that takes theatergoers from
the late 1960s to the present. The play, now on view at Broadway's
Plymouth Theater after a successful run at Playwrights Horizons,
remains one of the unqualified joys of the New York theater season.
   In a series of sketches, Wasserstein traces Heidi's changing
ideas about herself, about men and about other women. Heidi, an art
historian, may not embrace every trend, notion or belief that pops
up during her 20-year Odyssey, but she examines them with a
discerning attitude that is rich in humor and not above a little
anger.
   Director Daniel Sullivan has enlarged the production for
Broadway, but he hasn't diluted its effectiveness. Large slide
projections that pinpoint specific historical moments _ from Vietnam
War protests to the first rumbles of women's as well as gay
liberation _ enhance its appeal. Snippets of old pop music also help
anchor the play in the particular time periods.
   At the center of the play stands Joan Allen's radiant performance
as Heidi. She projects an intelligence and likability that never
waver during the character's many moments of self-doubt. It's a
richly drawn portrait.
   Peter Friedman has polished his performance as the egocentric
baby-boomer publisher who is in love with Heidi but marries someone
else. He's arrogance at its most ingratiating. Boyd Gaines is funny
and at times poignant as a sardonic but caring baby doctor. Cynthia
Nixon, the one new addition to the cast, demonstrates her virtuosity
in two roles _ as a flower child in a hilarious women's rap session
and as an ambitious corporate groupie of the Reagan years.
   Wasserstein has had some off-Broadway successes, most notably
``Isn't It Romantic'' and ``Uncommon Women and Others.'' ``The Heidi
Chronicles'' is her Broadway debut, and it's something to cheer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   American audiences deserve to see the Royal National Theater of
Great Britain, but not the company of actors sent overseas by its
educational division with a ragtag version of ``Macbeth.''
   The production, now on view at the Harry DeJur Playhouse, toured
colleges and universities across the country before coming to New
York for a two-week run. Shakespeare's shortest play has been made
even shorter in this production, performed at just over two hours
with no intermission. It just seems longer.
   Director Nick Ward has a concept but not a play. This is bare
bones Shakespeare _ with no scenery and tattered, grimy all-purpose
costumes. Eight actors play all the roles. When not acting, they sit
trance-like on benches located on three sides of the stage.
   That dispassion carries over to their performances. Ken Drury, a
Nicol Williamson look-alike, possesses a resonant voice but it has
little emotion. At least a quivering Amelda Brown suggests Lady
Macbeth's obsession with power. Nothing else in this forlorn revival
seems alive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0210 </DOCNO>
