<FIRST>r a AM-Boesky-Briefcase     03-20 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boesky-Briefcase,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Flight Attendant Sues For Negligence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines flight attendant sued jailed
Wall Street financier Ivan F. Boesky for $500,000 on Monday,
claiming she suffered serious injuries when she tripped over
Boesky's briefcase during a flight in 1986.
   The flight attendant, Garvetta Spencer, who lives in a Virginia
suburb of Washington, D.C., was ``rendered sick, sore, lame and
disabled,'' according to the suit filed in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn.
   Boesky's attorney, Robert McCaw, did not return a telephone call
seeking comment Monday.
   Boesky in late 1986 paid $100 million to settle charges with the
Securities and Exchange Commission including insider trading. His
confessions rocked Wall Street and spurred a crackdown on
white-collar crime.
   Boesky began serving a three-year sentence in a federal prison in
California last April.
   Spencer's suit claims Boesky acted negligently and in violation
of federal aviation regulations when he placed an open briefcase in
the aisle during an Eastern shuttle flight from Washington to New
York on Nov. 26, 1986.
   She said she was pulling a beverage cart up the aisle when she
fell over the briefcase and landed on her lower back. The suit
claims Spencer was hospitalized for a week and spent an unspecified
amount of money on doctor visits and other medical treatment.
   The $500,000 request also includes claims for lost wages.
</TEXT>
