<FIRST>r a AM-HostageStalemate     03-20 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Stalemate,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostages Shot Before Police Stormed House, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters taken hostage by a gunman
apparently were shot before police stormed a barricaded house to end
a 42-hour standoff, a police official said Monday, denying witness
reports that suggested the women were still alive.
   Police also speculated that a sexual-abuse investigation of the
gunman, Douglas ``Dougie'' Thomas, might have prompted the hostage
situation. It ended Sunday night when Thomas fatally shot his
girlfriend, 20-year-old Karen Lambert, wounded her sister and then
took his own life.
   The wounded hostage, Nicole Lambert, 14, was in critical
condition Monday at St. John's Hospital after surgery for a gunshot
wound in her head, said hospital spokeswoman Aggie Hayner.
   Police said Thomas, 20, took four hostages late Friday at the
home of Barbara Lambert, mother of Karen and Nicole Lambert. Thomas,
whom police described as ``deranged,'' threatened to kill the
sisters, as well as Karen Lambert's daughters, Katrina, 4, and
Kelisa, 2{ months.
   The two small children were released over the course of the next
42 hours while police surrounded the house and tried to convince
Thomas to surrender. Officials decided to storm the house after
Thomas took a telephone on which he had been talking to police and
threw it out a window, according to Springfield Police Chief Mike
Walton.
   Moments later, police fired two volleys of tear gas and broke
through the barricaded front door of the house. The two women were
found shot and wrapped in quilts just inside the door, police said.
Thomas was found lying on top of them with a self-inflicted gunshot
wound in his chest.
   The Springfield State Journal-Register quoted two witnesses as
saying they heard screaming as police tried to break through the
door, and that the screams stopped before officers entered the house.
   But Police Cmdr. Dan Hughes, who said he accompanied the
Emergency Response Team that stormed the house, said no gunshots
were heard immediately before or during the assault.
   Asked whether he believed the women were shot before the tear gas
was fired, Hughes said, ``Absolutely. When, I don't know, but it was
some time earlier.''
   Thomas, said by relatives to have been released from prison last
year after serving three years for a 1985 shooting, had been under
investigation by police for possible criminal sexual abuse as a
result of a complaint filed on behalf of a minor, police spokesman
Neil Williamson said.
   While declining to give details, he said the sexual-abuse probe
``could involve one of the hostages'' and might have prompted the
rampage.
</TEXT>
