<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-VoteCount     03-20 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Vote Count,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Sabotage, Computer Problems Hurt Vote Count</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sabotaged electrical and
telephone service hampered election officials' plan for a quick vote
count in the presidential election.
   The plan had been for each of more than 260 voting location in 14
provinces to transmit facsimiles of its returns by telephone to the
national Election Council in the capital Sunday night after the
polls closed.
   Election officials had said they expected to have preliminary
returns on election night. That turned out to be optimistic.
   At midnight on election night the council announced it was
suspending the count because of ``technical'' problems with the
computer.
   On Monday morning, Jorge Alberto Diaz, the council member who
represents the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena,
told reporters that returns were not yet in from some areas affected
by power outages.
   Leftist rebels lifted their transport ban on Monday, but on
election day there were reports that returns could not be delivered
because of dangerous conditions on the roads.
   Basic service like telephones and electricity are favorite
guerrilla targets and more than half the nation's electrical grid is
not working.
   Instead of trying to transmit the results by FAX, poll officials
said, the ballots and tally sheets would have to be brought from all
over this Massachusetts-sized to the capital. Final official results
might not come until as late as Thursday.
   But even though official results were not available, the parties
made predictions about the outcome based on unofficial results from
their own poll watchers.
   Arena claimed victory with more than 50 percent of the vote
Sunday, and the Christian Democrats conceded, even though only
130,000 votes had been officially counted at the time.
   Turnout was thought to be between 50 and 60 percent of the
nation's 1.8 million registered voters.
</TEXT>
