<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Women     03-20 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Women,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultra-Orthodox Men Throw Chairs, Fruit At Worshiping Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police had to use tear gas to break up a melee
Monday between about 50 Jewish feminists trying to worship at the
sacred Western Wall and angry Orthodox men who hurled chairs,
bottles and fruit at the women.
   The ultra-Orthodox men apparently feared the women would try to
repeat past feminist efforts to carry the Bible _ which Jewish
tradition says only men may do _ and don the prayer shawls worn
exclusively by male Jews.
   Orthodox tradition has a virtual monopoly on religious affairs in
Israel.
   One woman was slightly injured by a chair that struck her head
and neck, police spokesman Uzi Sandori said. He said there were no
arrests.
   The Western Wall, also known as the Wailing Wall, is Judaism's
holiest site. It is the only remaining wall of the ancient Jewish
temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
   After the women entered a specified women's prayer area, Orthodox
men stormed the cordoned-off section and threw chairs, fruit, and
``anything they put their hands on'' at the praying women, Sandori
said.
   Ushers who work at the Western Wall tried to protect the women
and warded off the men, but police only firing tear gas after a
woman began bleeding when she was hit by a chair, Sandori said.
   He said the police did not act earlier because they are not
allowed to interfere in a religious area unless called in by the
Religious Ministry.
   Amihud Bahat, a spokesman for the ministry, said the women at the
wall had deliberately left their prayer shawls and Bible at home and
did nothing against the rules.
   ``They are feminists but they behaved appropriately,'' he said,
adding they were welcome to pray at the wall in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
