<SECOND>BC-History, Adv27,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, March 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, March 27, the 86th day of 1989. There are 279
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On March 27, 1977, 582 people were killed in aviation's worst
disaster when a KLM Boeing 747, attempting to take off, crashed into
a Pan Am 747 on a runway on the Canary Island of Tenerife.
   On this date:
   In 1512, Spanish explorer Juan Ponce de Leon sighted Florida.
   In 1625, Charles I, king of England, Scotland and Ireland,
ascended the throne upon the death of James I.
   In 1794, President George Washington and Congress authorized
creation of the U.S. Navy.
   In 1836, the first Mormon temple was dedicated, in Kirtland, Ohio.
   In 1860, M.L. Byrn of New York City patented a corkscrew.
   In 1884, the first long-distance telephone call was made, between
Boston and New York.
   In 1917, the Seattle Metropolitans became the first U.S. team to
win the Stanley Cup, defeating the Montreal Canadiens.
   In 1945, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower declared that German defenses
on the Western Front had been broken.
   In 1958, Nikita Khrushchev became Soviet premier in addition to
First Secretary of the Communist Party.
   In 1964, Alaska was rocked by a powerful earthquake that killed
114 people.
   In 1968, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin, the first man to orbit
the Earth, died in a plane crash.
   In 1978, thousands of miners returned to work for the first time
in 112 days, ending a nationwide soft coal strike.
   In 1983, a crowd shouting ``Go home!'' forced Chicago mayoral
candidate Harold Washington to cut short a campaign appearance with
former Vice President Walter F. Mondale in the city's North Side.
   Ten years ago: Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries raised the base price of their crude oil by 9 percent as
the cartel ended a two-day meeting in Geneva. The U.S. Supreme Court
ruled, 8-1, that police cannot stop motorists at random to check
licenses and registrations unless there is reason to believe a law
has been broken.
   Five years ago: Gary Hart won the Democratic presidential primary
in Connecticut. Colorado Gov. Richard D. Lamm set off a furor by
saying elderly, terminally ill people had a ``duty to die and get
out of the way'' instead of trying to prolong their lives through
artificial means.
   One year ago: Jesse Jackson, rejoicing from an upset victory in
Michigan's primary-style caucuses the day before, vowed that his
Democratic presidential campaign would continue to ``win and grow.''
   Today's Birthdays: Former British Prime Minister James Callaghan
is 77. Singer Snooky Lanson is 75. Former Secretary of State Cyrus
R. Vance is 72. Singer Sarah Vaughan is 65. Newspaper columnist
Anthony Lewis is 62. Dance company director Arthur Mitchell is 55.
Actor Michael York is 47.
   Thought for today: ``We crucify ourselves between two thieves:
regret for yesterday and fear of tomorrow.'' _ Fulton Oursler,
American journalist and author (1893-1952).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Monday, March 27</NOTE>
