<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-20 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0922</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Born to Burn'' (MCA) _ Ethel and the Shameless Hussies
   
   Ethel and the Shameless Hussies, working at some lonesome
intersection where the Andrews Sisters meet Bob Wills, are really a
lot more talented than the dopey names and outrageous outfits would
have you believe. In fact, that's the problem here _ the joke
quickly wears thin, pulling down what could be a real up-and-coming
country band with a difference.
   ``Ethel'' and her polyester pals, ``Bunni'' and ``Blanche,'' we
are led to believe, are three good ol' gals who were all married to
the same lout. They sing clever things _ ``I Thought He Was Mr.
Right, But He Left'' _ and wear a lot of animal prints and
semi-naughty corsets.
   But amid the schlock, there is some quality. Their singing is
right on the mark, and their sound leans to Texas swing, the rebirth
of which is the happiest country music trend in a long time. In real
life, Ethel even comes with credentials: She's actually the
songwriter Kacey Jones, who co-wrote the Mickey Gilley hit ``I'm the
One Mama Warned You About,'' which is reprised on ``Born to Burn.''
   These women, though, face a big decision: Is this a country band
or a vaudeville act? The gimmick that got them their big break is
going to turn them into the Buster Poindexter of C&amp;W if thy don't
find a way out real fast.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   
   ``Mystery Girl'' (Virgin) Roy Orbison
   
   Roy Orbison's sudden death last December makes it hard to
objectively consider this ``comeback album.'' Is it really good, or
does sentimentality make it seem so?
   It's really good. Not perfect, but it would have been a hit even
if Orbison hadn't succumbed to a heart attack.
   Orbison imports an all-star crew to help him, including George
Harrison, Tom Petty and most of his Heartbreakers, Bono and The Edge
of U2, Jeff Lynne, Elvis Costello, Steve Cropper and a host of
studio stars. All Orbison needed to bring was that sweet,
other-worldly voice.
   ``You Got It,'' the single, is successful for the same reason as
the Traveling Wilburys _ it's light, breezy ``feel good'' pop.
   But the meat of the album are the Bono and Edge-composed ``She's
a Mystery to Me'' and Costello's ``The Comedians.'' The spare
arrangement of the former lays bare a tale of romantic torment.
   ``The Comedians'' adds a bizarre new twist to romantic loss: The
narrator is left stuck on the top of a ferris wheel while his
girlfriend walks off holding the operator's hand. The song builds to
a dramatic climax before Orbison leaves the listener, like himself,
hanging in mid-air.
   Each of the album's 10 songs go down easily, with only ``(All I
Can Do Is) Dream You'' having much of a rock 'n' roll kick.
   That eventually becomes a problem. Songs such as ``A Love So
Beautiful,'' ``Windsurfer'' and ``The Only One'' are predictable and
tend to blend together after awhile. Orbison was successful when he
tackled challenging material; he should have tried it a few more
times.
   Still, this Rock 'n' Roll Hall of Fame member managed to thrust
himself onto the contemporary scene without looking foolish. That
happens less often than it seems.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Lieder by Franz Schubert; Kathleen Battle, soprano, James Levine,
Piano (Deutsche Grammaphon)
   
   Kathleen Battle and James Levine present a varied selection of
Schubert songs, spanning a broad emotional range. In the first half,
Battle sings mostly about the sunnier side of love. Her light,
supple voice is perfectly suited to Schubert's setting of Goethe's
``Liebhaber in allen Gestalten,'' with its repeated line, ``Would
that I were a fish, so nimble and agile.'' Those words nicely sum up
Battle's fine voice.
   Her instrument changes color for the interesting ``An die
Laute,'' in which a young man confides his love to a lute. Levine,
whose pianism is as welcome as his podium work, perfectly
approximates the sound of the lute in the accompaniment.
   This recording amply demonstrates that Battle does not lack for
charm, and does not hesitate to show it. The listener is won over on
the eighth track, a hauntingly beautiful lullaby called ``Nacht und
Traume.'' She sings softly throughout with a heart-aching sweetness.
The song is about the joy men take in their dreams, and ends with a
depressing conclusion _ a call for a return to sleep when day breaks.
   The program now takes a darker turn. Battle sings of aching
hearts in ``Rastlose Liebe,'' or ``restless love,'' and the
turbulent night of a young nun awaiting her Saviour like a trembling
bride in ``Die junge Nonne.'' Finally comes the wondrous ``Shepherd
on the Rock,'' which transverses the range of a lover's emotions _
yearning, grief, loneliness, longing and the joy of anticipation.
   To some tastes, this song is better for a deeper voice, and
Battle has trouble with some of the low notes. But she sings with
conviction and attention to detail. Clarinettist Karl Leister is
flawless, sounding like a cool mountain stream bubbling over
polished rocks.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
