<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithBicentennial-Museums     03-20 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: With Bicentennial-Museums,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Bicentennial-Museums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just about every museum in France is putting on an
exhibition to mark the bicentennial of the French Revolution. Among
them:
   ``Magicians of the Earth'' is the theme covering contemporary art
works from both industrialized and developing countries at the
Pompidou Center and the Grande Halle of La Villette. The show runs
May through August.
   Fashion-lovers can view clothes from aristocratic closets of the
revolutionary period in the Musee de la Mode et du Costume, Palais
Galliera, until May 7.
   Emphasis is on ``The Stuff of Heroes'' at the Musee des Arts et
de la Mode in the Decorative Arts wing of the Louvre. The May to
August exhibition will spotlight revolutionary-period clothes with
an emphasis on textiles, accessories and jewelry.
   The most striking art from the revolutionary period will be the
paintings and drawings by Louis David displayed at the Louvre, Oct.
26 to Feb. 12, 1990.
   The works by this ``realist'' artist and chronicler of the times
include a sketch of a hook-nosed and grim Marie-Antoinette on her
way to the guillotine.
</TEXT>
