<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithOklahoma-Indians     03-20 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: With Oklahoma-Indians,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Oklahoma-Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A taste of the Old West awaits the tour group that will travel
through what was once Oklahoma Indian territory, meeting tribal
elders and sharing their lives for a few days.
   Led by anthropologist Robert Vetter, a select group of about 12
people will learn about Indian values and spirituality, visit Indian
sacred sites, and view and participate in tribal pow-wows. The group
will explore Oklahoma and take part in the ``sweat lodge,'' an
ancient ritual of purification.
   They also will learn how to set up, take down and travel with
teepees.
   The tour, ``Journey in Indian Territory,'' runs May 3 through May
10. Robert Fields, a Pawnee Indian and adjunct instructor of
anthropology at the University of Oklahoma, will accompany the tour.
   Vetter has studied and written about Oklahoma Indian culture,
working with Oliver Pahdopony, the last medicine man of the Comanche
Indians.
   Vetter says that Indian people practice ``fictive kinship,''
meaning they extend kinship ties to people who are not blood
relatives. He says he feels related this way to some of the Indians
he has met and worked with.
   Yet he says he does not try to romanticize Indian life. ``They
are a people of the 1990s, as well as a people of the 1860s, with
the same inherent faults and virtues as the rest of us.''
   Cost is $695 per person, covering orientation, registration,
lodging, instructions, lectures, activities, some meals and ground
transportation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
