<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Workcamps     03-20 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Workcamps,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Workcamps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether it means restoring a 10th-century watermill in France,
working at a children's crisis center in Ireland, harvesting crops
in Czechoslovakia, or digging ditches in Turkey, a number of young
Americans are combining travel with volunteer service, says the
Council on International Educational Exchange (CIEE).
   ``Volunteer workcamps have been popular in Europe since the
1920s,'' says CIEE program coordinator Rick LeVert, ``but it's a
relatively unknown concept for Americans that's growing rapidly.
   The CIEE sponsors an international workcamps program in 14
countries. Typically, the summer workcamps involve 15 to 20
volunteers living in communal fashion, working and sightseeing
together.
   Most participants are 20 to 35 years old, according to CIEE, with
the minimum age 18. There are limited opportunities for 16-year-olds.
   Volunteers are responsible for transportation costs to the
workcamp and a $100 program fee. They are provided with free room
and board.
   Don Hudson spent two weeks in France last summer excavating a
chateau.
   ``You spent enough time with people to see through the
differences to underlying similarities and through the similarities
to underlying differences,'' he said.
   Erica Goldberger, 18, who worked on a forest reclamation project
in West Germany, was the only American among volunteers from the
Netherlands, West Germany, Algeria, Spain and France.
   ``I learned so much,'' she says. ``I feel much more responsible,
independent and self-confident. I learned about life in many
different cultures and made friends from all over the world.''
   Volunteers have come from foreign countries to the United States,
as well. Workcamp projects in the United States have included a sand
dune consevation project in Oregon, reconstruction of low-income
housing in New York, and an archaeological dig in Kentucky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
