<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Health     03-20 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Health,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Staying on schedule'' is the key to keeping healthy while
traveling, says two specialists at the University of Oklahoma Health
Sciences Center in Oklahoma City.
   That means eating, sleeping and bathroom habits, according to Dr.
Robert A. Rankin and Dr. O.H. Rundell.
   The two have these suggestions for reducing health problems while
traveling:
   _ Stay on your regular schedule when eating. If you get
constipated, don't wait days to do something about it. Snacking on
fruits and vegetables will help.
   _ Restrict your intake of rich foods, to prevent heartburn.
   _ If your travel keeps you away three or more days, catch up on
your sleep before leaving.
   _ When crossing several time zones, use short-acting sleeping
pills to help you sleep.
   _ Don't drink to induce sleep on airplane flights. Instead, read
a book or listen to music or relaxation tapes.
   Rankin is associate professor of medicine, Digestive Diseases and
Nutrition Section at Oklahoma Memorial Hospital; Rundell is adjunct
assistant professor of psychiatry and behavioral sciences at the OU
Health Sciences Center and director of a sleep disorders center.
   For diabetics, Dr. Ira J. Laufer, director of the Diabetes
Treatment Unit at the New York Eye and Ear Infirmary, has some
specific suggestions:
   _ Self-monitor your blood glucose, either by a test strip or
electronically with a meter.
   _ Pack enough medication for several days in a carry-on bag.
   _ Keep a copy of any prescription with you at all times.
   _ For international travel, find out if waivers are needed to
carry medication or syringes through Customs.
   _ See if your doctor can recommend a physician in your travel
area. Travel agents can help with information on international
medical and assistance services.
   _ Wear an emergency medical ID bracelet or necklace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithHealth-Guide     03-20 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: With Health-Guide,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Health-Guide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   You have a broken leg, and you have a long flight ahead of you.
You should have your cast split to prevent buildup of painful air
pressure.
   You're a dieter, on the road. Only calorie-laden menus are
presented to you. Be assertive; ask for what you need to maintain
your diet.
   You want to avoid jet lag. You can't, but you can learn to handle
it.
   This advice and other ways to travel in good health are covered
in a new book, ``Travel Well, A Gourmet Guide to Healthy Travel''
(Brontosaurus Press), written by a Dallas physician, Norman Kaplan,
and his wife, Audrey.
   Travel, the Kaplans point out, can be hazardous to your health.
Business travel can be stressful. You get less sleep and rest. You
eat and drink too much. You don't exercise enough.
   ``It is hard enough for people to control their weight, blood
pressure, cholesterol level, exercise conditioning, and
psychological equilibrium in the relatively stable home situation.
On the road, it can be almost impossible,'' the Kaplans write.
   Their book includes advice about how to deal with these problems
aloft and on the ground. To help travelers continue exercise and
diet regimens, they list hotels with workout, jogging and swimming
facilities and restaurants they say will prepare diet fare for you.
   The Kaplans say there is no proven way to fend off jet lag, but
that it will help to try sleeping earlier on eastward flights and
staying awake later on westward flights.
   To avoid stress, they advise planning, traveling light with
carry-on luggage, and using special services such as business
centers at airports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
