<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Business     03-20 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Business,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Business travel has become a big ticket item for many
corporations, and many of them are learning to manage their own or
to cut deals to cut rising travel costs.
   U.S. corporations are expected to spend over $115 billion on
travel and entertainment in 1990, up from an estimated $95 billion
last year, according to an American Express survey. A similar survey
by Runzheimer International puts the median per-company travel
expenditure for 1987 at $2,348,000, a rise of about $120,000 over
the previous two years. Travel and entertainment costs are the third
largest controllable expense for most companies, after salaries and
data processing, American Express says.
   One way companies are dealing with travel expenses is to do it
themselves, by adding in-house travel specialists to their staffs.
About 29 percent of the 1,600 companies surveyed by American Express
say they added travel managers in l988, an increase of 16 percent in
two years.
   Many companies have computerized reservation equipment on their
premises. Coupled with frequent reviews and closer enforcement of
travel policies, their travel costs continue to rise, but at a rate
less than overall average travel costs, according to Runzheimer, a
travel and living cost consulting company.
   ``Employers are finally realizing how much they're spending on
travel, and they're zeroing in on ways to control this major
expense,'' says Bradford Burris, Runzheimer publisher.
   Still, nine out of 10 companies use travel agencies, the American
Express survey shows. Heavy spending companies are able to get lower
fares and better services by consolidating the number of agencies
they use. About half use a single agency. But even when they use
outside agencies, more companies have become more directly involved
in travel and entertainment expense management.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Romance     03-20 0172</FIRST>
