<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Romance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Privacy. An inn with a canopied bed and fireplace. Or a secluded
beach. Places to share with a favorite person.
   Romantic hideaways aren't so hidden anymore, now that a
newsletter of that title is helping travelers find them.
   The small hotel in Paris where Oscar Wilde died or a cottage in
New Orleans where James John Audubon lived and painted are detailed
in the newsletter, edited and published by Barbara Brass, an
entrepenuer who says she sensed a need for romantic spots for
vacationers.
   She said a survey of her readers showed that about half them want
``romance'' or a ``romantic destination'' for their vacations. Most
of her subsribers _ 80 percent _ are male business executives or
professionals.
   ``They want an escape from humdrum reality and a chance to renew
themselves, body and soul,'' she says.
   She offers romantic tips _ such as going to the airport in a
champagne-stocked limousine _ along with details about hotels and
transportation.
</TEXT>
