<DOCNO> AP890320-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Seaport     03-20 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Seaport,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Seaport</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY707</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surviving at the foot of the glass and steel
towers of Wall Street, the 200-year-old South Street Seaport has
become one of New York City's most popular new tourist attractions.
   The restored seaport, with its tall sailing ships, historic
buildings and a full schedule of entertainments, attracts an
estimated 12 million visitors each year.
   New York's financial empire began in South Street's 18th century
warehouses and counting houses, handling the wealth growing out of a
burgeoning ship trade. With the opening of the Erie Canal in 1825,
produce and goods from the Midwest fueled the boom, and South Street
became known as the ``Street of Ships.'' China clippers,
trans-Atlantic packets, Caribbean schooners, grain barges, fishing
smacks and steamboats crowded the wharves along the lower East River
tip of Manhattan. The heyday lasted until about 1860, when New York
outgrew the port and trade shifted to the Hudson River.
   Today's Seaport thrives on tourism, its old buildings and sailing
ships helping visitors relive the past. They can take harbor
excursions aboard vintage ships like the century-old schooner
Pioneer, or tour permanently moored ships such as the four-masted
bark Peking, the full-rigged three-masted Wavertree, the lightship
Ambrose or the fishing schooner Lettie G. Howard, each about 100
years old.
   The Seaport also is home of the venerable Fulton Fish Market and
Sloppy Louie's, a small shopfront restaurant dating from the 1930s.
These have been joined by hundreds of other modern stores,
restaurants and boutiques since the Seaport restoration began in the
1970s.
   Bowne &amp; Co. stationers on Water Street is typical of the old
buildings in the 11-block restoration. A museum replica of an 1870s
print and stationery shop, it has old hand-operated letterpresses
producing cards, stationery and pamphlets for sale at the front of
the store. The South Street Museum offices are in two Front Street
buildings thought to be the oldest on the block, dating from at
least 1797. They were once used by grocery firms, and one of the
buildings still has a wooden wheel in its attic, part of an old
hand-hoisting system.
   Live indoor and outdoor concerts are regular Seaport events, and
fireworks shows are added for holiday weekends. Memorial Day events
are scheduled May 27-29; Independence Day, July 1-4; Labor Day,
Sept. 2-4.
   Special events include the Stars and Stripes Regatta in July, the
Mayor's Cup Schooner Race in September, and the Maritime Festival in
October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Hawaii     03-20 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Hawaii,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Hawaii</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hawaii always has had the image of a ``Fantasy Island''
vacationland.
   Now, it's trying to fulfill those fantasies, from a wild game
safari to Grand Prix-type auto racing. Or, a more romantic, private
champagne picnic on a remote cliff overlooking the waterfalls.
   The new Hyatt Regency Waikoloa hotel, which opened last fall at
the Waikoloa Beach Resort on the main island, offers 10 different
``fantasies'' for its guests.
   Some may consider the cost fantastic, as well. The Lauhala Point
Picnic is an extra $700 per couple; the Hulihee Palace Dinner
Fantasy, a private, five-course dinner served along with native
entertainment, is $300 (including limo to and from the palace).
Hotel accommodations run from $195 to $375 a night.
   ``The romantic fantasies are popular,'' says Patrick Cowell,
Hyatt Resorts Hawaii regional vice president, ``because they allow
busy couples a total escape from the real world and the
responsibilities of work and family life.''
   The $360 million hotel seems something of a fantasy itself. It
has a fleet of paddle boats plying a four-acre lagoon with tame
dolphins and a 77-step, pink flagstone grand staircase descending
into the lagoon. Canopied canal boats ferry guests to their rooms.
   Another top-rated hotel on the island is the Mauna Kea Beach, on
the Kohala Coast. It was chosen ``America's No. 1 Favorite Hawaii
Resort'' in a poll of subscribers to ``Andrew Harper's Hideaway
Report,'' a travel newsletter for well-traveled (and well-heeled)
business executives.
   The new Hallekulani hotel on Waikiki was featured in a recent
issue of Travel and Leisure magazine, which considered the capital
city of Honolulu ``still the best urban beach resort in America.''
   Waikiki beach, the magazine said, ``might be the most famous _
and most expensive _ beach in the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WaterlooVillage     03-20 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Waterloo Village,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Waterloo Village</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY705</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, in one place, you can contemplate
18th-century agricultural life, 19th-century industry, and
20th-century music.
   Waterloo Village is a restored rural village with buildings
spanning two centuries, offering the visitor a visible historic time
chart.
   Houses and outbuildings in rusticated stones from the 1740s show
how the homesteaders who settled here along the banks of the
Musconetcong River milled grain by water power and worked their
trades as weavers, tavern keepers, blacksmiths, apothecaries and the
like.
   Iron was found in the region, and by the time of the
Revolutionary War, Andover Forge in the village was producing gun
barrels for the Continental Army. In 1815, Brig Gen. John Smith, an
early landowner, renamed the community to celebrate Wellington's
victory over Napoleon at Waterloo that year.
   The opening of the 102-mile Morris Canal in the 1830s marked the
next era, with Waterloo serving as an inland port for barges
transporting coal, iron and grain from Pennsylvania to the Hudson
River. The barges have gone now, but the towpaths remain for walking
through forests, along lakes and rivers. Tall Victorian mansion
houses also remain as a legacy of Waterloo's mid-19th century
prosperity.
   Waterloo declined with the coming of the railroads after the
1840s and nearly disappeared after the market crash in 1929. But the
abandoned village was discovered by Percival Leach and Louis
Gualandi in the 1940s, and they began its restoration. The two men,
partners in a design firm, solicited money for restoration and
antiques for the 11,000-acre property, turning it into a historical
museum now owned jointly by the state and the non-profit Waterloo
Foundation.
   Music festivals are the 20th-century contribution to Waterloo.
Its summer concert series began 20 years ago, and since then both
classic and popular artists have entertained more than 250,000
visitors each year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0273 </DOCNO>
