<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:HiltonHeadIsland     03-20 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Hilton Head Island,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Hilton Head Island</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Head Island _ that's South Carolina _ promotes itself with
the simple motto: ``Life is simply better here.''
   No relation to the Hilton hotels, the island is 35 miles from
Savannah, Ga., 95 miles from Charleston, S.C., and for better
educated, beach-loving pleasure-seekers with money, it may indeed be
a simply better place to visit.
   The South Carolina barrier island resort had an estimated 1.2
million visitors in 1988, spending some $475 million. More than
380,000 travelers are expected this spring, between March and May,
according to the Chamber of Commerce.
   A survey of last year's visitors, conducted by the University of
South Carolina's Institute of Tourism Research, found that most
visitors _ 74.9 percent _ went simply for pleasure and cited ``rest
and relaxation'' as what they wanted most from their vacation.
Others went to attend meetings or explore retirement possibilities,
the study showed.
   Nearly 83 percent of those surveyed were college graduates,
earning $50,000 or more annually.
   Most spring visitors came from Ohio, New Jersey and North
Carolina, representing 30 percenting of the spring profile.
   Spring was an attractive time, speculated M. Dale Augenstein,
president of the Hilton Head Island Chamber of Commerce, because of
the island's uncrowded golf courses, tennis courts and
accommodations.
   The island is named for William Hilton, a 17th-century English
sea captain, who was commissioned by a group of Barbados planters to
find new land on which to plant sugar and indigo.
   There are eight planned communities on the island today, with a
population of more than 20,000 people. A four-lane highway bridge
connects the island to the mainland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
