<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY708</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hertz and Avis may not have to worry yet, but some imaginative
hotel operators are providing some unusual transportation of their
own.
   The Westin Lenox hotel in Atlanta has a 1961 Rolls-Royce Phantom
V at the disposal of its guests, who can reserve the car for trips
throughout the area.
   The 20-foot limousine is described as ``sapphire blue with a
silver mink top.'' It was bought from a private collection in
Richmond, Va., according to a hotel spokesman, and has an interior
of ``Italian burr walnut, London cloth and Wilton carpet.''
   While it's not unusual for hotels to have their own mini-buses or
vans meet guests at the airport, The Westcourt in the Buttes, a
hilltop conference resort in Tempe, Ariz., sends a London taxi to
meet its guests coming into the Phoenix Sky Harbour Airport.
   One of the resort's three white taxis is a 1962 diesel, bought
from the Central Automobile Co. of London, says C.V. Healy, general
manager of the property. The other two came from London Coach, USA,
a Detroit dealer specializing in British cars.
   ``We wanted something distinctive and immediately recognizable
for our guests,'' says Healy.
</TEXT>
