<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Europe-Inflation     03-20 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Inflation,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Heats Up In Europe Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Market Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation has been heating up in Europe for the
first time in years and that, plus the higher interest rates being
used to combat it, are causing a lot of worry across the Continent.
   But few economists believe Europe will return to double-digit
inflation or that it will threaten the European economies' comeback
of the late 1980s.
   The pickup in prices, which coincides with a resurgence in U.S.
inflation, is being blamed on faster-than-expected economic growth,
which caught European governments by surprise. Central banks across
Europe, it turned out, slackened their grip too much after the
October 1987 stock market crash, economists said.
   Both consumer buying and investment spending have been strong in
Europe and as a result, factories have been working at or near
capacity.
   Economists also blame the upward trend in the dollar and the
weakness of European currencies _ particularly the West German mark
_ last year, as well as higher commodity prices, especially for oil.
   Higher prices are being exacerbated by higher wage claims,
threatening to cause wage-price spirals in some countries.
   Since the second half of 1988, European countries have tried to
stop inflation by raising interest rates to discourage that spending
and borrowing, but there is no clear indication it is working.
   Signs are that consumers are continuing to spend. In Britain, for
example, retail sales spurted 2.5 percent in February.
   This renewed inflation is a big disappointment for Europe
following the great successes the once-lumbering and mature
economies have had in turning themselves around by making their
industries more modern and efficient.
   ``There are inflationary pressures within most of the economies
in Europe. I think the inflation fear is fairly widespread,'' said
Nigel Rendell, an economist at the London investment firm James
Capel and Co.
   European inflation will peak at 5 percent this year, its highest
level since 1985, up from with 3.5 percent last year, he predicted.
It should fall back to 4 percent next year, as U.S. economic growth
slows and the dollar weakens, he said.
   Britain and Italy are expected to fare the worst, with an average
annual rate of up to 7 percent in 1989, economists say.
   The continental economies are not as overheated as those of the
United States and Britain, said Anthony Thomas, an economist with
the London investment firm Kleinwort Grieveson Ltd. As a result,
inflation is ``a much easier problem for them to contend with,'' he
said.
   Indeed, Rendell said: ``It's important to stress that although
we're going to get back to inflation, we're not going to get back to
the teen-age (double-digit) inflation we saw in the 1970s or the
double-digit inflation we saw earlier in the 1980s.''
   Many economists think interest rates will have to go even higher,
particularly after the U.S. government reported Friday that
wholesale prices surged 1 percent in February, prompting the stock
markets to plunge. The rates might go up within the month, they said.
   But David Bowers, an economist at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd.,
said he is not convinced higher interest rates will work in Spain,
for example, because Spanish consumers aren't heavily indebted and
because a large amount of investment is foreign and funded from the
outside.
   In addition, these high rates, besides squeezing mortgage holders
and other borrowers, are boosting currencies, and that is worsening
trade imbalances in Britain and Italy.
   However, economists are not concerned that the higher interest
rates will lead to a recession.
   ``In Europe, there is a lot of (economic) momentum,'' Rendell
said. ``We see (economic) growth at relatively high levels. It will
be less than last year, but it still will be pretty strong.''
   Rendell expects economic growth of 3 percent in Europe this year
compared with 4 percent in 1988.
   Here are annual inflation rates for 1988, and forecasts for 1989
and 1990 for the major European countries. They were provided by
James Capel and Co.
   _West Germany, 1.2 percent, 2.9 percent, 2 percent
   _France, 2.7 percent, 3.2 percent, 2 percent
   _Britain, 4.9 percent 7.1 percent, 4.5 percent
   _Italy, 5 percent, 6.5 percent, 6 percent
   _Spain, 4.9 percent, 6 percent, 5.5 percent
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Angola-Diamonds     03-20 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Diamonds,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lazare Kaplan Diamond Deal Sign of Hopefulness in Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion dollar agreement to import
Angola's diamonds announced this month by New York-based Lazare
Kaplan International could translate into more than just much-needed
hard currency to the war-ravaged southern African nation.
   Under terms negotiated with Endiama, the Angolan state diamond
company, Lazare Kaplan will import $20 million a year in
high-quality, uncut gem diamonds for processing at its plant in
Caguas, Puerto Rico, company spokeswoman Amy Wiener said in a
telephone interview from New York.
   Wiener said the first shipment has arrived for cutting and
polishing in the plant.
   The agreement is the first major international business deal
announced with the Marxist-oriented government since the signature
Dec. 22 of U.S.-brokered accords by Angola, Cuba and South Africa on
the phased withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   The withdrawal is being made in return for the independence of
the South African-controlled territory of Namibia, formerly known as
South-West Africa.
   ``I was impressed by the fact that all those with whom we met in
Luanda took a business-like, non-ideological approach,'' LKI
Chairman Maurice Tempelsman said in a company news release.
   ``In view of the close diplomatic cooperation between the
American and Angolan authorities in connection with the withdrawal
of South African and Cuban forces from Angola and Namibia, there is
no reason why this agreement should not be followed by many mutually
beneficial examples of economic cooperation between our two
countries.''
   The United States has no diplomatic relations with Angola, which
gained independence from Portugal in 1975 after a 14-year colonial
war and has since been fighting U.S.-and South African-backed rebels.
   Ms. Wiener said the diamond importing agreement, the first LKI
has made with Angola, was indirectly related to the December accords.
   ``The peace process was moving forward, and continues to move
forward,'' she said. ``It can only help business, and we're
encouraged by it.''
   South Africa agreed to stop supporting Jonas Savimbi and his
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, but the United
States continues to supply about $15 million a year in military aid
through bases in neighboring Zaire.
   Before his inauguration, President Bush wrote Savimbi assuring
him of continued U.S. support in order to pressure Angolan President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos into negotiating.
   Nearly 90 percent of Angola's hard currency earnings come from
oil pumped mainly by an Angolan-American consortium in fields near
the mouth of the Zaire River.
   Under Portuguese rule, Angola was exporting between 5 percent and
8 percent of the world's diamond production. Exports fell following
independence but rose in 1981-82 to 1.3 million carats worth $165
million.
   In 1987 the Portuguese company SPE (Portuguese Entrepreneurial
Society) signed a cooperation agreement with Endiama, and 50
Portuguese technicians are working in Angola as diamond mining
advisers.
   A delegation from Endiama visited Lisbon earlier this month
following a trip to the United States, and there have been newspaper
reports here of a possible joint venture between Portugal and Angola
in mining and finishing.
   Throughout the 1980s Portugal has been an illicit export route
for unfinished Angolan diamonds. The Lisbon daily Europeu said the
illicit trade amounted to $200 million in 1983 alone.
   In 1984, Savimbi-led rebels attacked diamond mines in
northeastern Angola, and production fell off sharply.
   The area was later divided into production blocs and leased to
mining companies in the same way Angola has awarded concessions to
oil companies. The Angolan army now provides security in the
diamond-mining areas.
   Ms. Wiener said LKI does not plan to become involved in actual
diamond mining in Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890320-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SpringBucks     03-20 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spring Bucks,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses Cash In Big On Spring Breakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies ranging from breweries to
Playboy Enterprises to AT&amp;T now view the ``The World's Most Famous
Beach'' through green-tinted glasses.
   Instead of seeing a half-million tanned and sunburned college
students in town to party until they drop, they see dollar signs.
   Students spend big bucks on their annual excursion to the sand,
surf and bars of Daytona Beach, a fact increasingly recognized by
both big and small entrepreneurs.
   During the five-week period betwen March 4 and April 1 this year,
an estimated $100 million will be spent by spring breakers here for
everything from hotels, to food, to beer, according to Evelyn Fine,
director of the Mid-Florida Research and Business Center in Daytona
Beach.
   Since Fort Lauderdale cracked down on the merry making in that
sun capital a few years ago, Daytona Beach has become a haven for
college students nationwide.
   ``We're the biggest spring break destination in the world,'' Ms.
Fine said. ``Fort Lauderdale bitterly regrets losing the spring
break market.''
   If the college students are here, can businesses which cater to
that age group be far behind?
   Playboy magazine, which featured ``The Women of Spring Break'' in
its April issue, is one company with an active beach presence.
   ``Playboy is here because we're No. 1 in the college market. It's
a great party,'' said Cindy Rakowitz, a communications director for
Playboy Enterprises. ``The majority of our readers are in the 18- to
34-year-old range and that's the market that's here.''
   On the pool deck of Penrod's Clarendon Plaza Hotel, a long line
of young men waited for bikini-clad Lynne Austin, Miss July 1986,
and Ava Fabian, Miss August 1986, to autograph pictures.
   ``I am in love,'' screamed a somewhat inebriated young man,
holding his autographed photos.
   The two signed such things as ``My No. 1 sweetheart,'' and ``Love
and Kisses'' on the black and white publicity photographs.
   Playboy also gave the young men a plastic bag containing a
variety of cologne samples, sunscreen, and condoms _ all products
advertised in the men's magazine.
   Also in the bag was Playboy's Spring Break magazine.
   ``I read about Daytona Beach in Playboy,'' said senior Kurt
Brewer, a chemical engineering major from Wichita, Kan., who added
that in past years that he had spent spring break on Padre Island in
Texas.
   While Playboy was using sex to push its products, AT&amp;T was trying
to appeal to students' minds.
   For students trying to get away from the studying rat race, a
10,000-square-foot, open-air, seven-foot-high plastic and maze was
constructed on the beach.
   Known as the AT&amp;T Maze Challenges, students were encouraged to
use their wits and legs to try to make it through the maze in record
time.
   Each day, the maze's pathways, which contain AT&amp;T advertising
posters, are reconstructed into a different configuration, giving
students a chance to try several different mazes.
   ``We estimate, on the average, it will take people between 15 and
20 minutes to complete the maze,'' said David Pugliese, AT&amp;T college
market manager, who said those that complete the maze in record time
receive T-shirts, beach towels and duffel bags.
   ``Lots of people are vying for the attention of the college
students, and I feel this is a healthy and positive event as
compared to some of the things spring break is known for,''
explained Gail Piccirilli, in charge of the college marketing for
AT&amp;T, Basking Ridge, N.J., as she led a reporter through the maze.
   She added, though, she hadn't come to Daytona Beach as a student.
   ``My father wouldn't let me,'' she said.
   Other companies catering to the student crowd included brewers
Anheuser Busch, Miller and Coors and automakers Chrysler and General
Motors.
</TEXT>
