<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-20 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0457</SECOND>
<UNK>Shares Down, Dollar Up</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged today in Tokyo for their
sharpest one-day decline this year, and the dollar gained against
the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 77.01-point loser Friday,
shed another 366.21 points, or 1.14 percent, to finish trading at
31,654.80.
   The index's decline marked the largest one-day drop this year in
a trading session dominated by sell orders following a sharp fall at
the start of today's session.
   Volume traded on the first section today was estimated at 950
million shares, compared with Friday's 1.18 billion shares.
   ``Share prices were lower across the board,'' said Manji Ueda of
Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   He attributed the index's plunge to a 50-point decline in the Dow
Jones Industrial Average in New York on Friday and the trend toward
a weaker yen.
   In New York, the Dow Jones index fell sharply following a U.S.
government report Friday that the nation's producer price index of
finished goods rose a full percentage point in February, triggering
concern that inflation will grow and interest rates will rise.
   Instability on the foreign exchange market and higher interest
rates tend to discourage market participants from investing in
stock, while higher U.S. interest rates would make the dollar more
attractive to foreign currency investors.
   ``The majority of Japanese investors collected profits by selling
off risky issues after they were discouraged by the decline on the
New York market and the yen's weakness,'' Ueda said.
   ``A national holiday (Tuesday) also prompted them to sell off,''
he said.
   Financial markets will be closed in Tokyo on Tuesday, a national
holiday marking the spring equinox.
   In currency dealings, the dollar gained ground and finished
trading at 131.92 yen, up 0.85 yen from Friday's 131.07-yen close.
The U.S. currency opened at 131.88 yen and fluctuated in a range
between 131.79 yen and 132.08 yen.
   The 1 percent rise in the U.S. producer price index of finished
goods in February triggered a new wave of worries about inflation
and interest rate hikes, said a trader with Bank of Tokyo, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The dollar fluctuated in a fairly tight range in Tokyo mainly
because of position adjustments, the trader said. ``Speculative
investors sold the dollar for profit-taking around the 132-yen
level, while they bought it near 131.70 yen,'' he said.
   ``The Tokyo market's dollar-buying interest is still strong, and
investors are now concerned about the U.S. consumer price index in
February, due out Tuesday,'' the trader said.
   He said a higher consumer price index would further encourage
investors to buy the dollar and boost its value against the yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
