<HEAD>With PM-Crop Insurance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Crop Insurance Corp. reports
the following totals by state for claims paid farmers for damage
suffered in the 1988 drought:
   _North Dakota, $187.1 million in claims on $34 million in
premiums collected, a loss ratio to the insurer of $550 for each
$100 in premiums.
   _Iowa, $127.7 million in claims on $39.8 million in premiums
collected, a loss ratio of $320 for each $100.
   _Minnesota, $96.6 million in claims on $33.9 million in premiums,
or a loss ratio of $285 for each $100.
   _Montana, $94.6 million in claims on $17.5 million in premiums, a
loss ratio of $539 for each $100.
   _Illinois, $59.9 million in claims on $16 million in premiums, a
loss ratio of $374 for each $100.
   _South Dakota, $48.8 million in claims on $15.1 million in
premiums, a loss ratio of $322 for each $100.
   _Missouri, $19 million in claims on $11.9 million in premiums, a
loss ratio of $160 for each $100.
   _Nebraska, $15.2 million in claims on $27.2 million in premiums,
representing a profit of $44 for each $100. Nebraska has irrigated
farms and did not suffer as extensive losses as neighboring states
on insured crop lands.
</TEXT>
