<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-20 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Monday in patchy
trading, as the market attempted to regain its footing after
Friday's near 40-point slide.
   The market was ``nervous and sensitive,'' said Bob Wade, joint
head of market making at the brokerage firm Robert Fleming and Co.
   An early morning consolidation attempt faltered when several
market makers marked down their stocks and became reluctant to add
stock onto their books, Wade said.
   However, market watchers cautioned that the low volume appeared
to magnify the drop in prices.
   ``There's been vast movement on no real trade,'' one said.
   Market players also were cautious ahead of Wall Street's opening.
They were worried about a continuation of Friday's sell-off in New
York, where the Dow Jones industrial average declined nearly 50
points.
   At about noon in London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was off 18.3 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,054.8,
above the midmorning low of 2,052.9, but well down from the opening
best level of 2,075.0.
   Volume amounted to 221.8 million shares by midday compared with
267.1 million shares at the same time Friday.
</TEXT>
