<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Trump-Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Lowers Offer for Strike-Bound Eastern Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 1-5 to UPDATE with Trump confirming he wants at least
$125 chopped off the price; picks up 6th graf pvs, However, the...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real-estate magnate Donald Trump said today he
wants to chop more than a third off the $365 million price he's
willing to pay for the Eastern Airlines shuttle because of the
strike that has grounded the carrier.
   In a letter to Frank Lorenzo, head of Eastern's parent company
Texas Air Corp., Trump said, ``The shuttle has become an entirely
different business in that its market share and customer base may be
lost for some time to come, if not forever.''
   ``Today the business is worth considerably less than the price
negotiated last fall,'' Trump said.
   He did not specify how much he's willing to pay now, but told the
Associated Press in a telephone interview: ``I'm looking for a
reduction in excess of $125 million.''
   The New York billionaire developing announced last October that
he would purchase the moneymaking operation for $365 million in cash
and name it after himself.
   However, the strike by Eastern's mechanics and the unwillingness
of most of the airlines' pilots to cross picket lines has forced
Eastern to file for bankruptcy court protection.
   Only about 200 of the 3,600 Eastern pilots have crossed the lines
since the strike by the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers began March 4.
   Eastern has been operating only slightly more than 100 daily
fights, about one-tenth its normal level.
   The airline, which has begun advertising for new pilots, has
acknowledged there are no near-term prospects for expanding its
operations.
   Shuttle flights are among those still taking off. The airline has
been struggling to keep the shuttle between Boston, New York and
Washington in the air by offering a number of passenger incentives,
including promotional fares as low as $12.
   Trump said he remained interested in buying the shuttle and would
like to close a deal ``before the shuttle operations become worse.''
   In his letter, he asked Lorenzo to call him later today to
discuss the sale.
</TEXT>
