<FIRST>u f AM-Scotus-Business Bjt   03-20 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Clears Partial Merger Of Detroit Papers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday cleared the way for
the partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers under a 1970
law that permits an antitrust exemption for financially failing
newspapers.
   The court, over two dissenting votes, set aside an earlier
postponement granted by Justice William J. Brennan.
   In other decisions, the high court again refused to let states
and state agencies be sued for allegedly violating federal copyright
laws, and rejected an appeal by workers at a California nuclear
power plant who are challenging their employer's random drug tests.
   In the Detroit newspapers case, a federal appeals court panel in
Washington voted 2-1 on Jan. 27 to uphold then-Attorney General
Edwin Meese's decision to allow the newspapers to form a joint
operating agreement under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act.
   Under the joint operating agreement, the Detroit Free Press and
The Detroit News would combine their business, advertising and
production departments but maintain separate news and editorial
staffs.
   A group of Michigan readers and advertisers who sued to stop the
partial merger contend that the Free Press, a morning newspaper
owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., is not a failing newspaper even though
it lost $10 milion a year between 1981 and 1986.
   The opponents, calling themselves Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, say the Free Press and News, which lost $50
million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both
papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out
of business.
   Gannett Co., which owns the News, is the nation's largest
newspaper publishing group. Knight-Ridder is the second largest.
   In the copyright case, the justices refused to revive allegations
that UCLA, a California state-run university, illegally copied a
company's computer programs and instruction manuals.
   Nine major motion picture studios had urged the court to hear BV
Engineering's appeal to broaden protection against what they said is
widespread copyright infringement.
   The movie producers said, for example, that prisons in Kansas,
West Virginia, Idaho, Utah, Delaware, North Carolina and Rhode
Island are refusing to pay for films shown to inmates.
   The justices on Feb. 21 had turned away a similar appeal by a
photographer who accused a state university in Virginia of
unauthorized use of his photographs.
   In the drug-testing case, the court, without comment, left intact
a ruling that threw out, at least temporarily, a lawsuit attacking
the tests.
   The justices already are studying the validity of drug tests in
three other cases, one involving a private employer and two
concerning federal workers or federal regulations.
   The case acted on Monday stems from tests initiated by Southern
California Edison Co. at its San Onofre nuclear plant.
   In other business-related decisions:
   _The court turned away a still-pending, big-money antitrust
dispute over the sale of raw milk. The justices, without comment,
let stand a federal appeals court ruling that could cost millions
for two cooperative associations of dairy farmers and a marketing
agent for dairy cooperatives.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1982 ruled against
Mid-America Dairymen of Springfield, Mo., Associated Milk Producers
Inc. of San Antonio, Texas, and the Central Milk Producers
Cooperative, based in Chicago.
   _The court refused to let Idaho officials tax the income of
railway workers who live elsewhere but pass through the state as
crew members on nonstop freight trains. It let stand a ruling that
such a tax on crews of Burlington Northern Railroad would violate
the Constitution and be unfair to the workers.
   _The court refused to hear an appeal by a federal judge in
Pittsburgh who issued orders in the bankruptcy case of Jeannette
Corp. glass company after he disqualified himself from presiding
over the matter.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that set aside
the orders by U.S. District Judge Paul A. Simmons.
</TEXT>
