<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks declined on the London Stock Exchange
Monday, reflecting what brokers called persistent worries about
further rises in U.S. interest rates.
   The market remained preoccupied with the U.S. inflation outlook
following news Friday that the U.S. producer price index rose 1
percent in February, dealers said.
   Analysts were anxiously awaiting the Tuesday release of the U.S.
February consumer price index to see whether it confirms
inflationary worries and maybe triggers another increase in U.S.
interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 19.5
points, or 0.9 percent, lower at 2,053.6.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 14.6 points lower at
1,690.9. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 11.64 points to
close at 1,170.68.
   Volume totaled 384.6 million shares, well down from 535.2 million
shares on Friday.
