<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close 1stLd-Writethru 03-20 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Falls Sharply As Snowstorm Slams Kansas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS corn price to rising, sted falling, in last graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed sharply lower Monday
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid reports of a blizzard in Kansas
but other grain and soybean futures advanced, with soybeans posting
fairly strong gains.
   The wheat market had opened lower and remained depressed
throughout the morning on perceptions that weekend precipitation in
the Great Plains had improved growing conditions for the maturing
winter wheat crop and added badly needed moisture to the soil.
   Wheat doubled its losses in the afternoon as selling increased
following reports that wind-driven snow had closed several highways,
including Interstate 70, in western Kansas, an area especially in
need of moisture.
   ``The market went through some liquidation, despite the fact that
when we look at all the precipitation recording during the past 24
hours, it won't necessarily be characterized as a drought-breaker,''
said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   Soybean futures contined their recent upward trend on continuing
concerns about tight supplies of soybeans for immediate delivery.
   At the close, wheat was 5} cents to 8{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.27 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1} cents higher with March at $2.79 a bushel; oats were { cent lower
to 1 cent higher with March at $2.09 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents
to 8 cents higher with March at $7.77 a bushel.
</TEXT>
