<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FraudIndictment     03-20 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fraud Indictment,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Haas Securities Chairman Indicted on Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of a defunct Wall Street
brokerage firm was charged Monday with illegally inflating the
prices of three stocks in a two-year scheme undone by the 1987 stock
market crash.
   In a 15-count indictment handed up by a federal grand jury,
Eugene Laff, former chairman of Haas Securities Corp., was charged
in what authorities called the first securities fraud case emanating
from the Oct. 19, 1987, crash.
   The indictment is the latest in a three-year federal crackdown on
Wall Street crime and the first by the Manhattan U.S. attorney's
office since the government formed nationwide securities and
commodities task forces in January.
   Laff, 51, of Greenwich, Conn., was charged with conspiring to
manipulate the prices of three over-the-counter stocks to increase
the value of substantial holdings owned by Laff and Haas Securities.
   The indictment is based on the confessions of Stanley A. Aslanian
Jr., 29, a former Haas trader and presidentwho pleaded guilty in
January to conspiracy and agreed to cooperate with the government.
He has not been sentenced.
   ``I think it's a reflection of an ongoing problem of penny stock
fraud,'' Acting U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said. ``It's one that
deserves our serious consideration generally.''
   Attorneys for Laff denied the charges, suggesting that
co-conspirators, including Aslanian, wrongly accused Laff of
participating in the alleged fraud.
   ``It seems that in looking at the indictment a lot of conduct of
other individuals appears to be attributed to Mr. Laff based on the
theories of conspiracy,'' said John Lang, an attorney for Laff.
   The indictment alleges that Laff took part in a conspiracy
starting in January 1986 to manipulate the stock prices of Flores de
New Mexico Inc., T.S. Industries Inc., and Big O Tires Inc.
   He is charged with conspiracy, securities fraud, mail fraud and
obstructing a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation. Each
of the 15 counts carries a maximum five years in jail and $250,000
fine.
   Haas Securities, through Laff, allegedly cornered the market on
shares of the stocks and set artificially high prices. By sustaining
the high price, Laff allegedly was able to reap a large profit. The
indictment does not specify how much money was involved in the
schemes.
   Haas Securities, a 75-year-old firm that had 12,000 customers
before going out of business nine days after the crash, is now
liquidating its assets in U.S. Bankruptcy Court proceedings.
   The indictment says Laff acted as a ``market maker'' on the
stocks by being ready to buy and sell a specific stock at prices
published by the firm.
   Laff, Aslanian and several unnamed co-conspirators, the
indictment says, allegedly raised the prices of the manipulated
stocks and placed large blocks of shares in friendly accounts that
were concealed from the public to create the appearance of demand.
   The indictment names, but does not charge, Henry Lorin, president
of a private investment company that allegedly controlled the
accounts and bought blocks of the three stocks.
   Laff made ``bogus, non-market, unauthorized'' transactions that
artificially boosted the share prices without money ever changing
hands, the indictment claims. Laff then sold some stocks accumulated
by Haas Securities at the inflated prices.
   The charge also says Laff published false information about the
stocks, made unauthorized sales to customers who did not have the
money to pay and refused to accept sell orders from customers.
   Haas Securities went belly-up after the crash because it no
longer had the capital to stay in business. Authorities said the
alleged scheme to manipulate the stocks couldn't be maintained after
the market drop and the share prices collapsed.
   After the crash, investors demanded information about the stocks.
Haas Securities allegedly was able to sustain the prices for several
days after the crash until it filed for bankruptcy and the
manipulated share prices plunged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
