<FIRST>r f BC-Tosco-Seminole     03-20 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tosco-Seminole,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Firm to Buy Florida Fertilizer Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tosco Corp. said Monday it has
acquired the right to buy Seminole Fertilizer Corp. in a $115
million deal that would give the company its only non-oil business.
   Tosco said it obtained the right to purchase virtually all of
privately held Seminole's stock from Argus Fertilizer of Stamford,
Conn., Tosco's largest shareholder.
   Tosco, an independent oil refiner and wholesaler, said the $115
million also would cover Argus' approximately 4 percent of stock in
Bartow, Fla.-based Seminole. The deal is expected to be completed by
the end of May, said Eric Schwartz, Tosco's executive vice president.
   Seminole, which makes phosphate fertilizer, has annual sales of
$300 million and debt of $200 million, Tosco said.
</TEXT>
