<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-FarmExports     03-20 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Farm Exports,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales to Japan Top Europe for First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will sell more than $8.2
billion in farm products to Japan this year, topping sales to
western Europe for the first time, a U.S. Foreign Agricultural
Service official said Monday.
   U.S. exports to the 12-nation European Economic Community are
expected to drop to $7.3 billion for the year ending Sept. 30,
Thomas O. Kay told a House subcommittee on rural development. U.S.
sales to all of western Europe are expected to reach only $7.8
billion, he said.
   In the year ended last Sept. 30, U.S. exports to the EEC reached
$7.5 billion, compared to $7.3 billion to Japan.
   The biggest gains for U.S. farm sales are coming from the Pacific
countries, Kay said. He said China is now the biggest importer of
U.S. wheat and predicted big increases in exports to South Korea.
   ``We are transferring our resources to that area _ that's where
the future lies,'' Kay said.
   Melvin E. Sims, Argiculture Department general sales manager,
said 1989 will be the last year in which South Korea will get U.S.
government-supported loans to encourage purchases.
   Kay said total U.S. farm exports this year are projected to rise
to $38 billion, up $2.7 billion from 1988. He attributed the
increase to higher prices caused by last summer's drought, which is
expected to reduce the volume of farm exports by 2 percent.
</TEXT>
