<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in quiet U.S. trading
Monday after gaining ground overseas.
   Gold prices strengthened. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $395.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up $3 from
Friday's late bid.
   Currency traders said the dollar started out firmer following its
rise in Europe and Asia but that internal market influences and
fears of central-bank intervention depressed demand.
   ``The sentiment is still bullish, though, based on expectations
of higher interest rates,'' said Earl I. Johnson, a trader at Harris
Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.85 yen to a closing 131.92 yen. It was quoted at
132.10 yen in London, and at 131.275 yen in New York, down from
131.70 yen Friday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7115 from $1.7135 Friday.
Later, in New York, sterling stood at $1.7190, up from $1.7130.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.86835 West German marks, down from 1.87625; 1.6105 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6185; 1.19425 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19575; 6.33725 French francs, down from 6.3550; and 1,370.50
Italian lire, down from 1,377.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Friday: 1.8780 West
German marks, up from 1.8770; 1.6185 Swiss francs, up from 1.6140;
6.3575 French francs, up from 6.3450; 2.1185 Dutch guilders, up from
2.1145; 1,377.00 Italian lire, up from 1,376.25; 1.1935 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1965.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $396.10 a troy ounce, up from $393.60 Friday.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $396 an ounce, up
from $393.25 bid late Friday. In Zurich, the late bid price was
$395.50, up from $393 bid late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.94 to close at a bid $396.81.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery finished at $6.114, down from $6.124. Silver rose in London
to $6.17 an ounce from $6.14 bid Friday.
