<DOCNO> AP890320-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-20 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Plummet; Products Decline Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices plummeted in heavy trading on
the New York Mercantile Exchange Monday, reversing last week's rally
in which prices rose nearly $2 a barrel.
   The April contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, dropped 82 cents to a closing price of $19.51 a
barrel, taking back 45 percent of the previous week's gains.
   On Friday, the April contract closed at $20.33, the highest level
since Aug. 14, 1987, when crude prices were $20.57 a barrel. It
capped a week-long rally during which prices rose $1.83 a barrel
from the previous Friday.
   Refined oil products traded on the exchange also declined, but
not as sharply.
   Unleaded gasoline for April delivery declined .14 cent to 55.48
cents a gallon, while April heating oil lost .21 cent to settle at
53.36 cents a gallon.
   Traders said the crude market was technically driven, fueled in
part by normal dealings on the last day of the April contract. Other
contract months for 1989 had only modest declines.
   But market fundamentals had not warranted the high price levels
reached on Friday, they said.
   ``The market realized that and took profits today,'' said James
Steel, an energy broker at Refco Inc.
   The market had expected problems with April deliveries to
underpin the recent price rise but they never materialized, some
analysts said.
   ``Instead, the market got a bucket of cold water in the form of
the April squeeze not developing,'' said Nauman Barakat, vice
president of energy investments at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Steel said once prices broke through the $20 mark on the
downside, the momentum picked up. ``That prompted a sharp
sell-off,'' he said.
   Strong demand and declining world oil production have helped
boost prices recently, but energy specialists had forecast that the
market could not sustain prices much higher.
   ``Demand is not that strong. Given that and given expected
slowdowns in economic growth it doesn't justify oil being over $20 a
barrel,'' Steel said.
   Brokers said the slower decline in product prices helped an even
sharper fall in crude prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
