<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DetroitNewspapers     03-20 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ends Detroit JOA Delay; Opponents Plan Further Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt ^By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the partial merger of Detroit's
two major daily newspapers will ask the Supreme Court to hear their
appeal, despite the court's refusal Monday to further delay the
business deal.
   The court, with only two justices dissenting, lifted without
comment a postponement granted March 4 by Justice William J. Brennan.
   The order cleared the way for The Detroit News, owned by Gannett
Co., and Detroit Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., to merge
their business and production operations under an antitrust
exemption allowed by the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act.
   The Justice Department's approval of the partial merger was
challenged by a coalition of newspaper readers and advertisers,
Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, and Public Citizen, a
Washington-based advocacy group.
   ``We lost a battle in the war,'' said William Schultz, attorney
for Public Citizen. ``On the other hand, I feel much better because
there were two dissents than if there would have been no dissents at
all. The fact that we got two dissents puts us in the serious
category.''
   With the lifting of the stay, the newspapers can begin
immediately to put their partial merger into effect.
   But a Knight-Ridder vice president, Frank Hawkins Jr., said it
was too early to discuss timing of the merger. ``Obviously there
have to be some discussions with our friends at Gannett,'' Hawkins
said.
   Opponents' intention to continue their appeal to the Supreme
Court means the newspapers had to decide whether to proceed with the
merger at the risk of the court later ordering it dismantled.
   ``Once the merger is implemented, the egg has been scrambled, and
how do you unscramble the egg,'' said Harold Spaeth, a political
scientist at Michigan State University in East Lansing, Mich., who
specializes in the Supreme Court.
   ``If the merger was consummated and then terminated, it would be
almost like starting up a new newspaper, and you just don't do that
in a metropolitan area on a daily basis at this point in time,'' he
said.
   Schultz said he was confident there were sufficient votes on the
court to grant a petition to hear the cases. The court's order did
not specify how many of the seven non-dissenting justices in fact
supported lifting the stay.
   Spaeth, however, said the court's refusal to delay the merger
made it unlikely they would consent to hear the case.
   Justices Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens voted to extend
the postponement until the court considers a formal appeal by those
who oppose the partial merger.
   ``I can't think of a nicer way to start out the week,'' Free
Press Publisher David Lawrence said. ``Finally, we seem to be near
the point where we can assure the readers of the Free Press that
their newspaper is saved.''
   Neither Gannett nor the News commented on the justice's decision.
   Opponents of the joint operating agreement argued that the Free
Press was not a failing newspaper even though it lost $10 million a
year between 1981 and 1986. The News lost $50 million in the same
period.
   The losses were due solely to price-cutting by the newspapers in
an unsuccessful effort to force each other out of business, the
opponents said.
   The opponents' emergency request to the Supreme Court said the
agreement ``threatens the independence of daily newspapers in 25
cities'' where, like Detroit, competing newspapers still exist.
   Knight-Ridder has threatened to close the Free Press if the joint
operating agreement is denied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
