<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-20 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Tumble As Rain, Snow Moisten Fields</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices fell sharply Monday on reports that badly
needed precipitation in the Great Plains had improved growing
conditions for the winter wheat crop.
   Other grain and soybean futures advanced, with soybeans posting
some fairly strong gains. On other markets, precious metals were
mixed; copper futures fell; livestock and meat futures were mostly
higher; and energy futures finished mostly lower.
   Wheat settled 5} cents to 8\ cents lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade with the contract for delivery in March at $4.26\ a bushel;
corn was 1 cent to 2 cents higher with March at $2.79\ a bushel;
oats were { cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $2.09 a
bushel; soybeans were 2} cents to 8{ cents higher with March at
$7.76} a bushel.
   The wheat market had opened lower and remained depressed
throughout the morning after the weekend precipitation in the
Plains. Winter wheat now is maturing in the central and southern
states and northern farmers are preparing for spring planting.
   Selling increased in the afternoon, doubling wheat's losses,
following reports that wind-driven snow had closed several highways,
including Interstate 70, in western Kansas, an area especially in
need of moisture.
   ``The market went through some liquidation, despite the fact that
when we look at all the precipitation recording during the past 24
hours, it won't necessarily be characterized as a drought-breaker,''
said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   Analyst Katharina Zimmer of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets agreed
that the weekend preciptation had not been heavy, especially in
Kansas.
   But she said: ``We went into the weekend not expecting rain and
now it's still raining and snowing, maybe enough to make people
abandon their long (or buy) positions.''
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a forecast
calling for above-average precipitation in the Plains and the
Midwest next week, which could lend a bearish tone to trading on
Tuesday.
   Gold futures advanced moderately on New York's Commodity
Exchange, continuing the rally launched Friday by fears of rising
inflation. Silver futures retreated slightly.
   Copper futures dropped sharply on the Commodity Exchange,
displaying the volatility that has rocked the market for several
weeks amid tight-supply concerns.
   Gold settled $2.40 to $3.40 higher with April at $397.40 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.8 cent to 1.1 cents lower with May at $6.185 a
troy ounce.
   Copper settled 2.9 cents to 3.55 cents lower with May at $1.3335
a pound.
   Most cattle futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
in reaction to firmer cash markets. The April contract reached a new
life-of-contract high _ 78.67 cents a pound _ for the second
consecutive session.
   Pork futures were dragged down by weak cash markets for most of
the session, but a wave of late buying brought the market to a mixed
close.
   Live cattle settled .30 cent lower to .52 cent higher with April
at 78.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .65 cent
higher with March at 80.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with April at 42.62 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .05 cent to .67 cent higher with March at 37.62
cents a pound.
   Most crude-oil futures retreated slightly in a thin market,
although the April contract dropped 82 cents a barrel as traders
bailed out of long positions prior to Wednesday's expiration.
Futures on refined products ended mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 82 cents
lower with April at $19.51 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent lower
to .13 cent higher with April at 53.36 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .10 cent to .42 cent lower with April at 55.48 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
