<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Shuttle 1stLd-Writethru   03-20 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru,0909</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump, Citing Eastern Strike, Lowers Offer for Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 8th graf to UPDATE attribution of Eastern letter; picks
up 9th graf pvs bg'ng, ``We believe ...; ADDS new grafs 14-17 to UPDATE
with on-time promotion, Pan Am statement; picks up 15th graf pvs bg'ng,
In a ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump lowered his offer for
Eastern Airlines' shuttle by at least $125 million Monday because of
damage to the service by a walkout by Eastern Machinists and pilots.
   ``I bought something that had a 57 percent share of the market,''
the billionaire said in a telephone interview. ``That share has
deteriorated considerably.''
   In response, Miami-based Eastern sent Trump a letter Monday
afternoon informing him the carrier is seeking other bids for the
shuttle. The letter says Eastern has recently received ``other
offers unsolicited'' and invites Trump to re-submit a bid.
   Trump announced last October that he planned to acquire the
lucrative three-city shuttle service from Eastern's parent Texas Air
Corp. for $365 million.
   But on Monday, Trump said he wants to cut the offered price by
more than a third.
   ``I'm looking for a reduction in excess of $125 million,'' he
said, adding that he considered $200 million a reasonable offer.
   Kevin Murphy, an airline analyst for the investment firm Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co., said Trump's move could reopen the bidding for the
shuttle while signaling the developer's reluctance to get into the
airline business.
   Art Kent, a spokesman for Houston-based Texas Air, did not return
repeated calls for comment. Excerpts from Eastern's letter to Trump,
signed by Barry P. Simon, senior vice president for legal affairs at
Eastern, were released in a statement.
   ``We believe it is our obligation to all our constituencies _
creditors, shareholders, employees and the communities and traveling
public we service _ to ensure that any shuttle sale is completed on
the best possible terms for Eastern,'' Simon wrote to Trump.
   ``Your intention to not proceed at this time on the terms in the
Oct. 12 agreement requires that we take action, consistent with our
obligations under the reorganization process to solicit offers from
third parties for the shuttle.''
   On March 4, Eastern's 8,500-member Machinists union, chiefly
mechanics and baggage handlers, walked off the job. The refusal of
most of the airline's pilots to cross the Machinists' picket lines
has forced Eastern to file for protection from creditors under the
bankruptcy laws.
   Eastern's hourly shuttle service, usually a profitable operation
linking New York with Boston and Washington, has been flying during
the strike.
   In the first days of the walkout, most Eastern shuttle flights
flew nearly empty, but the airline has been trying to rebuild its
business with a number of passenger incentives, including
promotional fares as low as $12. Fares returned to normal on
Saturday.
   Eastern made another pitch Monday to lure shuttle passengers.
Starting March 23, when the cut-rate weekday fares of $49 return to
$99, Eastern will offer an on-time guarantee on shuttle flights.
   If the shuttle plane is more than five minutes pulling away from
the gate, Eastern will greet the arriving passengers with refunds on
the spot or free tickets for other shuttle flights. The exceptions
would be delays caused by airport problems or severe weather.
   A rival shuttle service operated by New York-based Pan Am Corp.
has been flying with full passenger loads.
   Pan Am has seen business on its shuttle service double since the
strike began, said Pan Am spokeswoman Elizabeth Manners. The airline
has added flights and introduced larger aircraft to accommodate the
increased demand, she said.
   In a letter sent Monday to Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo,
Trump said, ``Last fall I agreed to buy a fully operational shuttle
which held nearly 60 percent of the market, commanded the principal
loyalty and confidence of business travelers and provided excellent
service to the customer.
   ``However, as you and I discussed, the shuttle has become an
entirely different business in that its market share and customer
base may be lost for some time to come, if not forever.''
   The shuttle ``is worth considerably less than the price
negotiated last fall,'' Trump said.
   Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock in Miami said the airline has been
encouraged by shuttle traffic and it was showing signs of luring
back its regular business travelers. He referred requests for
comment about the Trump letter to Texas Air.
   Lorenzo's New York office also referred calls to the Houston
headquarters.
   Bruce Nobles, president of the Trump Shuttle, the company formed
in anticipation of purchasing the Eastern shuttle, estimated Eastern
was now carrying about 20 percent of the shuttle market.
   Systemwide, Eastern is operating only about 100 flights a day,
about one-tenth of its normal flight schedule. The airline has begun
advertising for new pilots, while acknowledging there are no
near-term prospects for expanding its operations.
   Trump, who promised to rename the hourly service ``The Trump
Shuttle'' and redecorate the blue-silver Boeing 727s, said Monday he
was still interested in buying the operation and was prepared to
close a deal with Lorenzo within a week.
   ``I'm not surprised he'd want to lower his price considering the
strike and the troubles (Eastern's) had,'' said Robert Decker, an
analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps in Chicago.
</TEXT>
