<FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 1909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pennwalt 2ndLd-Writethru   03-20 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pennwalt, 2nd Ld - Writethru,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Concern Makes $1 Billion White Knight Deal For Pennwalt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBs 3rd graf pvs to UPDATE with Centaur extending offer through
Friday. Picks up The group...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. dealt a severe blow to an
investor group's hostile takeover bid Monday by agreeing to a $1
billion ``white knight'' buyout by the French government-controlled
Societe Nationale Elf Aquitaine.
   Some analysts said they did not expect any rival bids to top the
French oil and chemical company's $132 a share offer for each of
Pennwalt's approximately 8 million common shares outstanding.
   Centaur, a New York investment group that was offering $110 a
share for Pennwalt, issued a statement extending its offer through 5
p.m. EST Friday. The offer, which had been set to expire at 5 p.m.
Monday, was extended to give the group time to review the agreement
with Elf Aquitaine, the statement read.
   The group controls about 12.7 percent of Pennwalt's common shares.
   Pennwalt jumped $13.12{ to $130.12{ a share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Elf Aquitaine said it would begin a tender offer for the Pennwalt
shares on or before Friday with a scheduled expiration 20 business
days later.
   The merger, which would maintain Pennwalt's name and keep its
headquarters in Philadelphia, is subject to shareholder approval.
The boards of both companies have approved the agreement.
   ``We are delighted that Pennwalt is becoming a member of a global
organization in which there is such a strong strategic fit between
our businesses,'' Pennwalt chairman and chief executive Edwin E.
Tuttle said in a statement.
   Unlike Centaur's offers, which Pennwalt repeatedly spurned,
Tuttle called the Elf Aquitaine buyout ``in the best interests of
all Pennwalt stakeholders.''
   Michel Schneider Maunoury, chairman and chief executive officer
of Elf Aquitaine Inc., the corporation's U.S. holding company based
in Stamford, Conn., said in a telephone interview the deal had been
under discussion for three to four weeks and he did not expect any
trouble completing it.
   Maunoury said the merger would enhance Elf Aquitaine's efforts to
develop its specialty chemical business and to increase its presence
outside Europe.
   ``It's a good company,'' he said. ``...It has good sales all
around the world, everything.''
   Elf Aquitaine, in which the French government owns a controlling
interest, has more than $20 billion in annual sales with more than a
third related to chemicals.
   Analysts said the deal likely would succeed.
   ``It gives the shareholders top dollar,'' said Donald Pattison, a
chemical analyst for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan, Grenfell Inc. in New
York. ``I don't see any way anybody could get any more out of it.
It's really a credit to management, because they stuck to their guns
and they really got a blue-chip purchaser.''
   Centaur, headed by financiers Abbey J. Butler and Melvyn J.
Estrin, announced last June it had acquired a 6.5 percent interest
in Pennwalt, which then was trading at about $62 a share.
   Pennwalt responded by selling its drug and equipment businesses
and buying back about 40 percent of its outstanding shares.
   Centaur made its initial $100 a share offer on Dec. 13, but
Pennwalt had resisted Centaur's overtures since indicated it would
seek other alternatives such as further restructuring or a sale of
the company to a third party.
   Pennwalt, which had $1.02 billion in sales in 1988, repeatedly
has refused to meet with Centaur, saying the offer was inadequate
and the partners unworthy.
   Centaur received a setback earlier this month when a federal
judge blocked a special shareholders meeting the partnership had
hoped to use to stage a proxy fight for control of Pennwalt's board
of directors.
   On Feb. 23, Pennwalt announced it planned to sell its Wallace &amp;
Tiernan equipment division based in Belleville, N.J., for more than
$40 million to a management-led group as part of its defensive
strategy.
   In a separate announcement Monday, Pennwalt said it had agreed to
sell an Italian subsidiary, Pennwalt Italia SpA, to Akzo Chemicals
BV of the Netherlands. Terms were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
