<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Southland     03-20 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Southland,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convenience Store Owner Says Losses Reflect Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southland Corp., owner of 7-Eleven convenience
stores, Monday reported it lost $37 millionin the fourth quarter and
$216.2 million for all of last year, reflecting high interest costs
and other expenses related to its 1987 leveraged buyout.
   The losses occurred despite strong operating results for its
7-Eleven stores.
   Revenue amounted to $1.97 billion in the three months ended Dec.
31 and $7.99 billion in all of 1988.
   Because of the buyout, the seven months ended July 31, 1987 were
reported on a separate accounting basis than subsequent periods,
which means results from the two periods within 1987 cannot be added
together to produce 1987 full-year financial results, and no
full-year comparisons can be made between 1987 and 1988.
   Southland's 1988 earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation
and amortization was $494.3 million, including $16.5 million from
divested operations, the company said.
   Jere W. Thompson, Southland's president and chief executive
officer, called that figure ``the most appropriate measure of our
progress.''
   ``We're very pleased overall with the company's operating and
financial achievements during its first full year after undergoing
one of the largest leveraged buyouts in history,'' Thompson said in
a prepared statement.
   Southland added 600 convenience stores to its 7-Eleven
international operation in 1988. The division now includes nearly
5,300 stores operated by licensees and affiliates in the United
States and 19 foreign countries.
   Southland operates about 7,000 additional convenience stores in
the United States and Canada, and owns a 50 percent interest in
Citgo Petroleum Corp.
   The company has completed the sale of 910 operating convenience
stores and virtually all of its other businesses scheduled for
divestiture as part of the LBO.
   To date, the company has repaid $977.5 million of its original
$2.55 billion LBO bank debt.
</TEXT>
