<FIRST>r f BC-Carl's-InsiderTrading     03-20 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Carl's-Insider Trading,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hamburger Chain Founder Loses Bid to Dismiss Insider Trading Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of the Carl's Jr. hamburger chain
lost a bid Monday to have a federal insider trading case against him
and several relatives dismissed.
   In rejecting a dismissal motion by Carl Karcher's attorney, U.S.
District Judge Edward Rafeedie ruled that a jury should hear
Karcher's claim that the civil case against him is based only on
circumstantial evidence.
   Karcher is accused of passing on information that allowed several
relatives to avoid losses on stock in Carl Karcher Enterprises Inc.,
which runs 460 Carl's Jr. fast-food outlets in California and the
West.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission case, filed in April 1988,
alleges that various Karcher relatives and one company executive
sold stock to avoid losses totaling $310,000 in advance of an
unfavorable earnings report in 1984.
   The civil suit seeks treble damages.
   Karcher and his wife, Margaret, are accused of passing insider
information to relatives, but aren't accused of selling stock
themselves. Other defendants include the couple's son, Jerome;
daughters, Barbara Karcher-Garrett, Margaret J. LeVecke, Catherine
Karcher-Everly and her husband, Daniel; and son-in-law, Donald E.
Fergus Jr.
   Alvin DeShano, who was accounting director for Karcher
Enterprises, is named in the civil insider-trading suit and also has
pleaded innocent to criminal securities-fraud charges in the case.
   Carl Karcher's brother, Donald F. Karcher, president of Karcher
Enterprises, and six members of his side of the family agreed to pay
a total of $187,560 in February to settle their part of the civil
case. They didn't admit guilt.
   Others included in that settlement were Donald Karcher's wife,
Dorothy; their daughter and son-in-law, Doneta Ann and David
Thomason, and Mrs. Karcher's sister and brother-in-law, Rosemary and
William T. Bruns.
   Carl Leo Karcher, Carl Karcher's son, was ordered in September to
pay $10,500 for his role in the case.
</TEXT>
